<HEADLINE> China's Private Sector Getting Better Legal Protection </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 21 (Xinhua) -- The All-China Federation of
Industry and Commerce has submitted to the National People's
Congress a motion for laws to protect the country's thriving
private sector.
</P>
<P>
This was disclosed by Zhang Xuwu, vice-chairman of the
federation, at the second session of its Eighth Executive
Committee here today.
</P>
<P>
The private sector of the economy has grown rapidly in the past
20 years with the assistance and guidance of state policies, and in
the future, its development should be protected by the law, he
said.
</P>
<P>
The federation will set up a specific department in charge of
legal affairs this year to protect the rights and interests of its
members, he added.
</P>
<P>
The private sector has become a key part of China's economy,
paying 54 billion yuan (6.5 billion US dollars) in taxes in 1997,
or 7 percent of the country's total industrial and commercial tax
revenues.
</P>
<P>
The sector employs about 85 million people, 68 million of them
in private business and 17 million in foreign-funded enterprises.
</P>
<P>
Zhang said that the federation will encourage more enterprises
in the sector to get involved in agriculture, high-tech
industries, service, infrastructure, state-owned enterprise
reforms, employing laid-off workers, and supporting welfare.
</P>
<P>
Jing Shuping, the federation's chairman, said today that
private ownership should play an important role in the socialist
market economy.  
</P>
</TEXT>
