<HEADLINE> Canada's Inflation Rate Up Slightly in March </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, April 21 (Xinhua) -- Canada's inflation rate was up
slightly in March, with its consumer price index's basket of goods
and services rising 0.9 percent from a year ago, Statistics Canada
reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Compared with February, the inflation increased only 0.1
percent in the month. Canadian consumers paid more for vegetables,
telephone services, tuition fees and tobacco products.
</P>
<P>
In the meantime, they paid less for gasoline, computers and
mortgage interest charges, the statistics agency said.
</P>
<P>
Fresh vegetables have been volatile in Canada in recent months
due to El Nino. The prices climbed 26.5 percent in January, fell
11.2 percent in February, and rose 7.8 percent in March.
</P>
<P>
Canadian drivers continued to enjoy low gasoline prices, which
fell for the sixth consecutive month in March.
</P>
<P>
In March, Newfoundland posted the largest price declines among
Canada's provinces, while Alberta saw the largest price increases.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
