<HEADLINE> Greek Army Chief to Visit Cyprus </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, April 21 (Xinhua) -- Chief of Staff of the Greek army
Athanasios Tzoganis will visit Cyprus for talks with the island's
political and military leaders, Cyprus News Agency (CNA) reported
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Tzoganis' three-day official visit, which begins on Wednesday,
aims to discuss the implementation of a joint defense pact signed
between the two countries in November 1993.
</P>
<P>
During his stay here, Tzoganis is expected to visit a
newly-built military air base in the western coastal district of
Paphos, to be named after the late Greek Prime Minister Andreas
Papandreou.
</P>
<P>
The air base was built under the joint defense pact which
guarantees Greece's protection for Cyprus in case of a new Turkish
offensive against the island.
</P>
<P>
This eastern Mediterranean island has been divided into Greek
Cypriot-controlled south and Turkish Cypriot-dominated north since
1974 when Turkish troops invaded and took over the northern third
of the island in the wake of a short-lived Greek Cypriot coup
seeking union with Greece.
</P>
<P>
Turkey has maintained over 40,000 troops in the northern part
of the island, which was unilaterally declared in 1983 as a
breakaway "Turkish Republic of Northern Cyprus" by Turkish
Cypriots. The breakaway state was only recognized by Turkey.
</P>
</TEXT>
