<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-21 16:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lebanese PM Holds Talks With Mubarak </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, April 21 (Xinhua) -- Visiting Lebanese Prime Minister
Rafik Hariri Tuesday held talks with Egyptian President Hosni
Mubarak on Israel's recent offer to withdraw from south Lebanon,
Egypt's Middle East News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Hariri told reporters after the two-hour meeting that he asked
Mubarak to continue his good offices to push forward the stagnant
Mideast peace process in the interest of the entire region,
including Israel.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that both Lebanon and Syria were prepared to
establish permanent and comprehensive peace in the region and to
resume talks with Israel from where they were stopped about two
years ago.
</P>
<P>
"Syria and Lebanon were ready to change the current standoff
from a state of war to permanent and comprehensive peace, if
Israel so desired," said Hariri.
</P>
<P>
Israel decided on April 1 to accept the United Nations Security
Council Resolution 425, which calls for an unconditional Israeli
withdrawal from south Lebanon. But meanwhile, Israel said it would
not exit unless security arrangements for its northern border
areas are worked out with the Lebanese government.
</P>
<P>
Israel set up a 1,200-square-kilometer security zone in south
Lebanon in 1985 with the aim of protecting its northern border
areas from Lebanese guerrilla cross-border attacks.
</P>
<P>
Lebanon and Syria, which closely coordinate their Mideast
policies, want the Israeli withdrawal from south Lebanon
unconditional and simultaneous with a Israeli pullback from the
Golan Heights, which Israel seized from Syria in the 1967 Mideast
War.
</P>
<P>
Hariri's trip followed a brief visit here last Wednesday by
Syrian President Hafez al-Assad. A flurry of diplomatic activities
are being carried out to coordinate Arab stances on the latest
development in the issue of south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
During his stay here, Hariri will also discuss with Egyptian
Prime Minister Kamal el-Ganzouri means of promoting bilateral
cooperation in economy and trade.
</P>
<P>
He will meet with Arab League Secretary General Esmat
Abdul-Meguid on issues of common interest. 
</P>
</TEXT>
