<DOCNO> XIE19980422.0015 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> East Africa to Expand Regional Development Bank </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, April 21 (Xinhua) -- Kenya, Uganda and Tanzania, the
three members of the East Africa Cooperation (EAC), vowed Tuesday
to expand the regional development bank in a bid to "integrate
the three economies into a single trade and investment area."
</P>
<P>
The East African Development Bank (EADB), set up in 1967, has
grown into a leading regional development finance body with the
capacity to meet diverse investment needs from the region, Kenyan
Minister of Planning and National Development George Saitoti said
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The EADB recorded the third successful year in 1997 with a net
profit of 4.14 million U.S. Dollars, Saitoti said at the end of
the EADB Governing Council meeting.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the minister announced that he was replaced by
Tanzanian Finance Minister D. Yona who became the new rotating
Chairman of the EADB Governing Council from Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Saitoti, Yona and Ugandan Finance Minister J.S. Mayanja-Nkangi
held the one-day meeting here to review the bank's performance in
1997 and discuss how to strengthen the bank's role in further
coordinating the three economies.
</P>
<P>
Investments attracted by the bank rose by 6.5 percent from
27.9 million Dollars in 1996 to 29.7 million Dollars in 1997 as a
result of EADB's aggressive business promotion and the
introduction of new business activities such as Asset Leasing and
Trade Finance, Saitoti said.
</P>
<P>
Throughout 1997, both disbursements and collections from the
bank's projects recorded increases of 38.5 percent and 49.2
percent respectively over 1996, according to the EADB annual
report issued Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
EADB should "continue to pursue an aggressive stance in
promoting both its core and new business" so as to boost cross
border trade and investments and finally integrating the three
economies into a single trade and investment zone, said Saitoti.
</P>
<P>
As envisaged in the EADB Long Term Strategy, the new business
activities, like Asset Leasing which became operational in 1997,
have played a prominent role in expanding the volume of business
for the bank, he said.
</P>
<P>
The bank intends to expand and enhance its Trade Finance
operation to include the financing of other export commodities
such as cotton, tea and the importation of strategic commodities
and raw materials for export oriented industries, he added.
</P>
<P>
Following the successful launching of the Local Currency Bond
in Kenya and Uganda respectively in November 1996 and December
1997, the bank now plans to start a similar local currency bond
equivalent to 10 million Dollars which will also be listed for
trading at the Dar es Salaam Stock Exchange earlier 1998.
</P>
<P>
The EADB have also agreed with the European Investment Bank in
principle to co-finance the EAC Digital Telecommunication Project
which is expected to be launched in 1998. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
