<DOCNO> XIE19980422.0017 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Infrastructure Plans to Be Cut in New Kenyan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, April 21 (Xinhua) -- The coming Kenyan budget for the
fiscal year from July 1, 1998 will only include a few projects on
infrastructure damaged heavily by months of El Nino rains, said
Minister for Public Works and Housing Kipkalya Kones Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"It is better to include only a few projects in the budget and
ensure that they are completed successfully and satisfactorily,"
he said at the opening ceremony of a conference on developing and
sustaining of national infrastructure.
</P>
<P>
Kenya has implemented "too many projects with very little
money. Accordingly, they (the engineers) scale down standards and
specifications to meet the budget," he noted.
</P>
<P>
"The end result is too many sub-standard projects which fail
as soon as they are commissioned and the country goes to square
one," he sighed.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, he said he believes that the three-day conference
can "be an ideal forum for exchange of ideas on how to improve
the infrastructure problems we find ourselves in today."
</P>
<P>
The conference, sponsored by the Institutional Engineers of
Kenya and the Engineers' Registration Board, focuses itself on
how to improve basic economic infrastructure including transport
and communications, piped water supply, sanitation and sewerage,
energy and bulk storage. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
