<DOCNO> XIE19980422.0018 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-21 16:33 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Blair's Mideast Tour Much Helpful to Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, April 21 (Xinhua) -- British Prime Minister Tony
Blair wrapped up his five-day five-nation Mideast tour Tuesday
after making progress in helping reactivate the stalled peace
process and improving the British-Arab ties.
</P>
<P>
He successfully persuaded Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin
Netanyahu and Palestinian National Authority (PNA) President
Yasser Arafat to hold a meeting in London early May on the stalled
peace process.
</P>
<P>
This means that Blair, whose country holds the current European
Union Presidency, appeared to have won the trust from the Israeli
side which has for long rejected the European mediator's role in
the peace process.
</P>
<P>
The EU has been pressing the Israeli government to implement
the agreements already signed with Arabs and abandon its hardline
policies, a stance welcomed by Arabs.
</P>
<P>
His visit, which took him to Egypt, Saudi Arabia, Jordan,
Israel and Palestine, came at a difficult time when the
Israeli-Palestinian peace process has been stalled for a year
since a Jewish settlement project was carried out in East
Jerusalem, a place claimed by Palestinians as the capital of their
future state.
</P>
<P>
The success in arranging the London meeting is particularly
important as the United States, the chief mediator in the peace
process, has reportedly said its patience is being worn out over
the prolonged stalemate.
</P>
<P>
However, Blair displayed diplomatic skills in avoiding
challenging the U.S. role in the peace process by repeating the
stance that the European role is only complementary to
Washington's.
</P>
<P>
Blair said during the trip that the EU and Britain will play
more positive role in reviving the peace process, that could also
help speed up the peace process if all the promises being turned
in practice.
</P>
<P>
He also scored a point in another attempt to improve ties, if
not mending them, with Arabs during the trip.
</P>
<P>
During the recent weapons inspection crisis in Iraq, Britain
was the first country to take side with the U.S. against Iraq and
sent its military forces to the Gulf, distancing itself away from
some Arab nations.
</P>
<P>
During the visit, Blair has repeatedly stressed the importance
of the principle of "land for peace" which is to the liking of the
Arabs.
</P>
<P>
In Gaza, Blair expressed his support to the right of
self-determination of the Palestinians, and promised to lobby
more economic aid to help build the Gaza airport and the Karni
industrial zone between Israel and Palestine. 
</P>
</TEXT>
