<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iranian Middle-Range Ballistic Missile Near </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, April 21 (Xinhua) -- A senior Israeli intelligence
officer said on Tuesday that by the end of 1999, Iran will be able
to produce the prototype of the ground to ground missile capable
of hitting Israel, Israel Radio reported.
</P>
<P>
The officer told the Israeli Knesset (Parliament) Foreign
Affairs and Defense Committee that the Iranians are approaching
completion of the development of the engine for the middle-range
ballistic missile Shihab 3.
</P>
<P>
He noted that despite the pressure from the United States,
Russia is still supplying the Iranians with the technological
know-how about developing the missile.
</P>
<P>
Israeli sources said that once Iran completes the development
of the engine, the missile project is assured of eventual
success. They said the engine has been the most difficult stage of
the Shihab 3 and after its completion, the Iranians could complete
the project themselves.
</P>
<P>
The Shihab 3 has a range of 1,300 kilometers and a payload of
700 kilograms. The Israeli sources said the missile is based on
Democratic People's Republic of Korea's No-Dung missile and Russia
took over from Pyongyang in 1994 after failures in the program's
development.
</P>
<P>
The Iranian missile issue was raised in the Knesset just after
the United States agreed on Monday to fund a third Arrow
anti-ballistic missile battery for Israel.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. decision was announced by visiting U.S. Secretary of
Defense William Cohen after his meeting with Israeli Defense
Minister Yitzhak Mordechai in Tel Aviv Monday. Cohen also pledged
more military support to Israel. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
