<HEADLINE> Sudan Seeks to Promote Relations With Arab States </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KHARTOUM, April 21 (Xinhua) -- Sudanese Foreign Minister
Mustafa Osman Ismail said Tuesday that one of the priorities of
his country's foreign policy is to promote relations with all Arab
states.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a news conference, Ismail said that Sudan will make
endeavors to improve its relations with the Arab states, which
deteriorated during the Gulf War in 1991 as Sudan supported Iraq
and most Arab countries sided with Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
On the Sudanese-U.S. relations, he indicated that dialog
between the two countries has never ceased and that his country
is not seeking confrontation with the U.S..
</P>
<P>
He said that Sudan will pursue an objective course in patching
up its relations with the U.S. at all levels, as U.S. delegations
continue to visit Sudan to explore the status of women, children
and human rights as well as the changing economic situation in the
country.
</P>
<P>
He added that he has sent a letter to British Foreign Secretary
Robin Cook calling for the development of Sudanese-British
relations. However, he said, a change in Britain's policy toward
Sudan will take some time.
</P>
<P>
The Sudanese minister asserted that Sudan's relations with all
European countries except Britain are improving. 
</P>
