<HEADLINE> New Progress Made in Angolan Peace Process: Annan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, April 21 (Xinhua) -- United Nations Secretary General
Kofi Annan has said that "new progress" has been achieved in the
political field in the Angolan peace process.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. chief made the remarks in a report to be tabled to
the Security Council.
</P>
<P>
The report reaching here Tuesday said, out of the 12 tasks
stipulated by the new agenda passed in March this year, 11 has
been accomplished, leaving only the task of re-establishing
national authorities in regions occupied by the National Union
for the Total Independence of Angola (UNITA) unfulfilled.
</P>
<P>
The report noted that the military situation in Angola is
"relatively quiet", though there was still insecurity in certain
areas, which had affected the work by U.N. observation mission
and humanitarian agencies in the country.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. mission will continue with its investigations into
the "incidents in violation of the cease-fire agreement" to
revert the insecure situation, the report pledged.
</P>
<P>
On the demobilization of former UNITA militiamen, the report
said, 6,435 out of the 7,877 remnants soldiers registered have
been de-militarized.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. Security Council will discuss on April 29 the Angolan
peace process and the term of U.N. observer mission in Angola
whose deadline is April 30.
</P>
<P>
Blondin Beye, U.N. special envoy to Angola, Monday told the
press in Lisbon, Portugal, on his way to the U.N. meeting, "It is
almost settled" that the Security Council would postpone the term
of the U.N. observer mission in Angola since there has been
positive progress in the peace process.
</P>
<P>
Beye didn't comment on whether the Security Council would
cancel its sanctions on UNITA. But he believed that no more
sanctions would be imposed on UNITA other than the existing ones.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
