<HEADLINE> Baghdad Holds Mass Funeral for Dead Children </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, April 21 (Xinhua) -- A mass funeral was held in
Baghdad on Tuesday for 52 Iraqi children who died of
sanctions-spawned malnutrition diseases.
</P>
<P>
The funeral procession set out from ar-Rasheed street, heading
for the United Nations office in Baghdad. Arab student
organizations as well as a U.S. student delegation, now visiting
Iraq, were taking part.
</P>
<P>
Sultan Ash-Shawi, chairman of the Iraqi Association for
Children Support, told reporters that he held the
U.S. administration responsible for these children's deaths.
</P>
<P>
He accused the United States of being persistent on
maintaining the sanctions with no legally justified reason for
its prolongation, now that Iraq has fulfilled its obligations
under relevant U.N. Security Council resolutions.
</P>
<P>
He called upon the international community to seriously and
expeditiously act for the lifting of the unjust sanctions and put
an end to the "U.S-committed systematic genocide" against the
Iraqi people.
</P>
<P>
Ash-Shawi later handed a protest note to the
U.N. representative in Baghdad, on behalf of the families of the
dead children.
</P>
<P>
More than a million Iraqi children have died because of the
sanctions which have caused acute shortages of food and medicine
that hit almost all sections of the society.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. imposed sanctions on Iraq in 1990 after its invasion
of Kuwait. 
</P>
