<HEADLINE> Ethiopia Loses 1.9 Billion Tons of Soil to </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, April 21 (Xinhua) -- Ethiopian Vice-Minister of
Agriculture Getachew Tekelemedhin said Tuesday that the country
loses 1.9 billion tons of soil to erosion per year.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a meeting here on soil fertility management, the
vice-minister said Ethiopia loses 600 million Birr (68 million
Dollars) per annum to reduced agricultural production triggered
by the effects of soil erosion.
</P>
<P>
According to the Ethiopian News Agency, if the current trend
continues unabated, Tekelemedhin said, a sizable farming
community in the country will be forced to earn their livelihood
from sources other than farming.
</P>
<P>
The prominent factors for soil degradation in Ethiopia are
population pressure, deforestation, poor agricultural techniques,
overgrazing and drought.
</P>
<P>
He said the soil fertility initiative launched by the World
Bank and the United Nations Food and Agriculture Organization
plays an important role in preventing soil degradation in
sub-Saharan countries including Ethiopia.
</P>
<P>
Also on the occasion, Ismail Serageldin, vice-president of the
World Bank's special program, expressed the bank's readiness to
support Ethiopia's soil fertility initiative.
</P>
<P>
The meeting has drawn representatives of governmental and
non-governmental organizations, donor agencies, the World Bank
and scientists on soil fertility. 
</P>
</TEXT>
