<HEADLINE> Iran, Pakistan to Cooperate to Solve Afghan Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, April 21 (Xinhua) -- Iran and Pakistan Tuesday
underlined the importance of cooperation among Afghanistan's
neighboring countries in a bid to solve the Afghan crisis after
the Taliban militia agreed to join peace talks.
</P>
<P>
According to the Iranian official news agency IRNA, Pakistani
special envoy for Afghan affairs Iftekhar Murshid told his Iranian
counterpart Alaeddin Boroujerdi that cooperation between Iran and
Pakistan was "absolutely necessary to bring the Afghan peace
process to a successful conclusion."
</P>
<P>
He said that "the Pakistani government and the prime minister
himself are determined to bring the Afghan crisis to an end, a
feat we are hoping to achieve through cooperation with the
Islamic Republic of Iran."
</P>
<P>
Murshid arrived here Tuesday morning to coordinate with
Iranian officials after U.S. ambassador to the United Nations Bill
Richardson announced Friday that the Taliban group and the
anti-Taliban Northern Alliance have agreed to hold face-to-face
talks on April 27 in Pakistan's capital of Islamabad.
</P>
<P>
Murshid said that Taliban's readiness to enter negotiations
with their opposition was a step towards creating understanding
among the Afghan warring factions.
</P>
<P>
He also briefed Boroujerdi the results of Richardson's visit
to Pakistan and Afghanistan as well as the negotiations involving
the representatives of the U.N. and the Organization of Islamic
Conference (OIC) regarding the Afghan crisis.
</P>
<P>
Boroujerdi welcomed the Pakistani proposal to cooperate with
Iran to push the Afghan peace process, saying that Iran supports
cooperation between the U.N. and the OIC to resolve the Afghan
crisis.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Tehran radio reported that Iranian Foreign Minister
Kamal Kharrazi Tuesday also met the Pakistani envoy, voicing
Tehran's readiness to cooperate with Islamabad to solve the
Afghan issue.
</P>
<P>
The pro-Islamic Taliban regime came to power after its armed
forces captured the capital of Kabul in September, 1996. It drove
out the government troops led by President Burhanuddin Rabbani,
leader of the alliance of guerrillas who stormed into the capital
in 1992 after years of war with then Soviet-backed regime.
</P>
<P>
Ever since, a new civil war has been continuing between the
Taliban forces, which control most parts of the country, and the
guerrilla alliance which occupies the north. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
