<HEADLINE> Egypt's Satellite Space Channel Leased to Libya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, April 21 (Xinhua) -- Egypt Tuesday signed a contract
with Libya to lease a space channel to its western neighbor on its
first satellite Nilesat to be launched into orbit this month, the
Middle East News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The contract was signed by Amer Aun, the representative of the
General Secretariat of Information and Culture in Libya and Amin
Bassyouni, chairman of the Egyptian Satellites Company (Nilesat).
</P>
<P>
In an address on the occasion, Egyptian Minister of Information
Safwat al-Sherif stressed the importance of cooperation between
Egypt and Libya in the new Egyptian satellite project.
</P>
<P>
"This is an affirmation of Egyptian-Libyan relations and a
unified action that serves the entire Arab nation, balances
globalization and Arabism and maintains Arab cultural and
historical identity as well as traditions," he said.
</P>
<P>
Sherif described Nilesat as a satellite of "Egyptian origin and
Arab identity."
</P>
<P>
Aun, the Libyan representative, said this project enables
Egypt, a pioneer in the Arab media, to move from a country that
uses satellite technique to one that manufactures satellite.
</P>
<P>
The Egyptian satellite Nile 101 will be carried into space on
April 28 by an Ariane rocket from a launching pad in South America.
</P>
<P>
It carries 400 radio and 12 space channels which become 83
television channels by the use of the pressed digital system used
in the Nilesat.
</P>
<P>
Up til now, nine space channels have been leased out of the 12
channels on the satellite. A space channel is expected to be
leased to Lebanon shortly. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
