<HEADLINE> AL, Francophone Organization Forge Closer Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, April 21 (Xinhua) -- The secretaries general of the Arab
League (AL) and the Francophone Organization Tuesday signed a
protocol on enhancing cooperation between the two bodies and among
their member states in the economic and cultural fields.
</P>
<P>
The protocol, signed by AL's Esmat Abdul-Meguid and Boutros
Boutros-Ghali, of the organization of French-speaking countries,
accentuates the importance of continuing coordination between the
two secretaries general in a regular way to guarantee active
cooperation between the two organizations.
</P>
<P>
It also outlines some joint projects and activities to be
carried out by the Cairo-based AL and the grouping of
French-speaking countries.
</P>
<P>
The protocol reflects their joint desire to promote cooperation
among all regional gatherings as well as their wish to enhance
peace, development and international cooperation in accordance
with the U.N. charters.
</P>
<P>
The two organizations will work to promote the development
process in Africa within the framework of historical and cultural
ties that link it to the Arab countries.
</P>
<P>
Six Arab states, namely Egypt, Ethiopia, Comoros, Morocco,
Tunisia and Djibouti belong to the Francophone Organization, whose
majority members come from the African continent.
</P>
<P>
Sources close to the AL said this protocol shows the two
organizations' belief in the role the regional gatherings should
play at the international level.
</P>
<P>
In late March, Boutros-Ghali invited Abdul-Meguid to a
conference of the Francophone Organization in Paris to discuss
the organization's relations with other regional groups,
particularly with the AL. 
</P>
</TEXT>
