<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, April 21 (Xinhua) -- Nigerian police operating at the border
between Lagos and Benin have been put on full alert following the
seizure of large quantity of ammunition in bags of cassava flour.
</P>
<P>
The police said Tuesday that in a latest case, more than 400 rounds
of ammunition were discovered last week at the same border checkpoint
in a sack which the owners claimed contained garri.
</P>
<P>
When the man was challenged on the findings, he quickly bolted into
Benin, a police spokesman said, quoted by the News Agency of Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
While intensive investigations are underway to nab the suspect, the
police appealed the public and commercial bus operators to report any
suspicious object.
</P>
<P>
According to the official news agency, arms being trafficked into
Nigeria from neighboring countries have been on the rise following the
civil wars in Liberia and Sierra Leone.
</P>
<P>
The police hold that most of the ammunition smuggled into the
country was being used in armed robbery and other clandestine
operations.  
</P>
