<HEADLINE> Iraq Gets Angry Over Statement by UNSCOM's Depute Chief </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, April 21 (Xinhua) -- Iraq complained to the
United Nations on Tuesday that the recent statement by Charles
Duelfer, the depute chief of the United Nations Special Commission
(UNSCOM) in charge of dismantling Iraq's weapons of mass
destruction, violated his conditions of employment.
</P>
<P>
The statement by Charles Duelfer, published by The New York
Times on April 15, 1998, contains his evaluation of the results of
the visits to Iraq's presidential sites and a quotation from his
report, which the U.N.Secretary-General had yet to transmit to the
Security Council at the time the interview was published.
</P>
<P>
In a letter to U.N. chief Kofi Annan, Nizar Hamdoon, Iraq's
envoy to the United Nations, said this violated an undertaking by
UNSCOM employees not to make statements or give interviews, unless
specifically authorized to do so.
</P>
<P>
The recent statement by Duelfer, an American, "confirms this
fact and also confirms the need for the United Nations to be more
attentive to ensuring the impartiality of officials operating
under its flag," Hamdoon added. 
</P>
