repeated that the report was a fabrication, South African Press
Association (SAPA) reported.
</P>
<P>
Apart from claiming that there had been an organization called
FAPLA (Force of African People's Liberation Army) aimed at
subverting the 1999 general elections and at assassinating the
president, the report further claimed FAPLA had aimed to murder
judges.
</P>
<P>
FAPLA was also claimed to have planned to occupy parliament,
broadcasting stations and key financial institutions, and planned
to orchestrate general disorder over a period of about four
months before the elections.
</P>
<P>
Mandela said that about 130 people were named in the report as
members, leaders and supporters of the organization, and these
included very senior military personnel, political figures and
others.
</P>
<P>
He repeated the government's assertion that the plan had never
existed.
</P>
<P>
The Commission of Inquiry had concluded that the report was
"without substance and inherently fantastic," he said.
</P>
<P>
South African National Defense Force chief General Georg
Meiring, who handed the report to Mandela on February 5, has
announced resignation over the report.
</P>
<P>
He would leave the army on May 31, one year ahead of his
scheduled retirement. 
</P>
