<HEADLINE> UNEP Unveils Short-term Action Plan to Contain Forest Fires </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, April 21 (Xinhua) -- Under the leadership of
Klaus Topfer, Executive Director of the United Nations Environment
Programme (UNEP), fire-fighting experts from around the world have
come up with an immediate, short-term action plan to contain the
forest fires still raging out of control in Indonesia's East
Kalimantan province, a U.N. release said on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The plan, at cost of 10 million U.S. dollars, covers the
provision of equipment and training for 1,000 local fire-fighters,
use of aircraft, operational management, communications and
support to government liaison teams.
</P>
<P>
The forest fire experts also looked at action to be taken in
the medium to long-term, and brought their recommendations to
meetings of international organizations and donors.
</P>
<P>
The last report of the United Nations Disaster Assessment
Coordination mission to Indonesia estimates that over 250,000
hectares of land in East Kalimantan have been razed by fires this
year, and concludes that the situation is out of effective control.
</P>
