<HEADLINE> Most European Shares down on Weak Dollar </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 21 (Xinhua) -- Most of the major stock markets in
Europe reversed Monday's healthy gains and ended down Tuesday,
with only London closing flat and Paris and Frankfurt down
sharply.
</P>
<P>
Britain's FTSE-100 index of leading shares recovered from an
early loss of one percent or 69 points to end on a flat note in
thin trading, up only 0.9 point or 0.02 percent at 5955.0.
</P>
<P>
Dealers said that the market was largely unaffected by the
inflation figures which were in line with expectations, but
investors were nervous ahead of Wednesday's jobs report, which is
seen as potentially significant in determining U.K. interest rates
prospects.
</P>
<P>
Some traders said that the market was only consolidating after
having surging up quite a lot recently.
</P>
<P>
In Frankfurt, German shares closed trade with a loss of 53.06
points or 0.98 percent at 5,388.94 on the DAX-30 index, hit by the
weakness of the dollar against the mark.
</P>
<P>
Traders said that the weak dollar triggered profit-taking in
export sensitive stocks such as car and drug stocks.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that VW, Europe's largest carmaker, was badly
affected by the dollar's decline and its shares fell four percent.
Meanwhile, BMW, another carmaker giant, ended early five percent
down.
</P>
<P>
The Paris CAC-40 index closed 25.29 points or 0.65 percent
lower at 3,860.40, but managed to bounce off early lows following
Wall Street's rally.
</P>
<P>
Dealers said that investors were reluctant to bid up shares in
the wake of the dollar's fall to below six francs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
