<HEADLINE> S.Leone Freezes Foreigners' Bank Accounts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, April 21 (Xinhua) -- Sierra Leone has ordered the
immediate freezing of the bank accounts of 93 foreigners
suspected of collaborating with the military junta ousted in
mid-February, the government said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
According to a report reaching here, the 93 foreign nationals
include Lebanese, Indians, Westerners and Africans.
</P>
<P>
The banks involved are Barclays, Standard Chartered and the
Sierra Leone Commercial Bank, the report said, quoting Justice
Minister Solomon Berewa.
</P>
<P>
The first two are the biggest foreign banks in Sierra Leone,
which only resumed business operations at the end of last month,
20 days after the returned of President Ahmed Tejan Kabbah from
exile in neighboring Guinea since may last year.
</P>
<P>
According to the justice minister, the 93 foreigners "are
suspected of having collaborated with the ousted military junta
and also to have defrauded the country of much-needed revenue
through customs duties fraud".
</P>
<P>
Bank sources reportedly said that the sums frozen amounted to
millions of U.S. Dollars.
</P>
<P>
"The government order to freeze their accounts was delivered
to U.S. together with the list of the 93 yesterday (Monday)," one
banker was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
While the West African Peacekeeping Force ECOMOG is carrying
the final offensive to mop up the remnants of the junta and rebel
allies in the east of the country, the trial of more than 40
junta members and collaborators is going on.
</P>
<P>
The Sierra Leonean government earlier this month ordered the
deportation of 22 foreign business nationals living in the
country for their alleged assistance to the junta.
</P>
<P>
The police accused the deportees of violating the economic
sanctions and embargo imposed by west African countries and
importing arms and ammunition for the junta.  
</P>
</TEXT>
