<HEADLINE> Clinton Still Undecided on Northern Ireland Trip </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 21 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton is
still considering a trip to Northern Ireland to campaign for a
peace accord despite opposition by some political leaders there,
the White House said on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Clinton is to attend a summit of the Group of Seven leaders and
Russia in Birmingham in Britain in May. U.S. officials had
indicated that he may go to Northern Ireland during the trip.
</P>
<P>
"We are continuing to hold open that possibility," White House
spokesman Mike McCurry said during a regular briefing on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Clinton has said he will leave it up to the governments to
decide if a trip by him would be helpful and will await their
invitation.
</P>
<P>
Such a trip to Belfast would fall just days before a May 22
referendum in Northern Ireland and one in Ireland on whether to
accept a peace agreement reached between the Northern Ireland
parties on April 10.
</P>
<P>
McCurry said U.S. officials were consulting further with the
British and Irish governments and staying in touch with leaders of
the Northern Ireland parties as well.
</P>
<P>
He said deputy National Security Adviser Jim Steinberg was
planning a trip to the region in the next week or so for
consultations.
</P>
<P>
"We will go if it is in the interest of peace in Northern
Ireland," McCurry said.
</P>
<P>
David Trimble, leader of the biggest pro-British party in
Northern Ireland, the Ulster Unionist Party, has said Clinton
should not visit before the referendum. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
