<BODY>
<HEADLINE> German Security Authorities Confirms Authenticity of </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, April 21 (Xinhua) -- German security authorities Tuesday
confirmed the authenticity of a letter which claimed that the Red
Army Faction (RAF) terrorist group had formally disbanded.
</P>
<P>
In an eight-page typed letter sent to the Reuters news agency in
Bonn on Monday, the RAF, a band of leftist urban guerrillas who
pursued a campaign of bombings, kidnappings and assassinations in
the 1970s and 1980s in a bid to destroy the then West German
society, acknowledged the irrelevancy of their project and
declared themselves disbanded.
</P>
<P>
The German Federal Office of Criminal Police in Wiesbaden on
Tuesday said the letter had been proved to be authentic because
the paper used as well as the two-color RAF seal were identical to
previous letters sent by the group.
</P>
<P>
The latest news, however, has aroused a controversy between
German government officials and opposition parties over whether it
is now time to lift the emergency legislations adopted at the
height of the RAF terrorism in the late 1970s which broadened
police power of surveillance and detention of suspected RAF
members.
</P>
<P>
While opposition parties calling for lifting the special laws,
government officials warned that it was still premature to
proclaim an end of terrorist threat in Germany.
</P>
<P>
German Interior Minister Manfred Kanther on Tuesday also
stressed his opposition to a general amnesty for RAF members.
</P>
<P>
The RAF is believed to responsible for killing at least 30
people, including high-ranking politicians and business
executives.
</P>
<P>
The last assassination for which the group claimed
responsibility was the 1991 murder of Detlef Rohwedder, who headed
the agency established after the German reunification to privatize
former East German state-owned enterprises. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
