<DOCNO> XIE19980422.0055 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Says Not to Change Position on Lockerbie Trial </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 21 (Xinhua) -- The United States Tuesday
reaffirmed its claim that two Libyan suspects in the Lockerbie
bombing must be tried either in Britain or in the United States,
rather than in a neutral country.
</P>
<P>
Washington was reacting to a report that Libyan lawyer Ibrahim
legwell had reached an agreement with Scottish lawyer Robert Black
and Jim Swire, who represents British families of victims of the
1988 Pan Am 103 airliner bombing over Lockerbie, Scotland, that
his two clients linked to the bombing will be ready to stand trial
under Scottish law in a neutral country.
</P>
<P>
But the United States said it would not change its position.
</P>
<P>
"Libya is obligated under Security Council resolutions to
deliver the suspects for trial in either the U.K. or the U.S.,"
State Department spokesman Lee McClenny said.
</P>
<P>
"We have no doubt that this latest Libyan agreement reflects a
desire to evade its obligations rather than a willingness to see
justice done," he said.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that Scottish lawyer Black and Swire held talks
in Tripoli this week with Legwell and Libyan foreign affairs and
justice officials. They also met Libyan leader Muammar Gaddafi in
a bid to gain support for a trial plan formulated by Black.
</P>
<P>
Legwell said Tuesday that he and the Scottish lawyer agreed "on
several basic points and details."
</P>
<P>
"I confirmed to them... that my clients would stand for trial
before such a court, which will be set not in Scotland nor the
United States, but in a neutral country," he said.
</P>
<P>
"We also agreed that it would be established with an
international panel of judges to be agreed upon and presided over
by a senior Scottish judge. The court would operate under the
criminal law and procedure of Scotland," he added.
</P>
<P>
McClenny said, "The British family member who visited Libya is
entitled to his views. Other Pan Am 103 family members will have
their own."
</P>
<P>
The American families of victims of the bombing also denounced
the reported agreement. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
