<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Takes Measures to Deal With Pilot Shortage </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 21 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. Air Force is to
reduce overseas assignments and increase bonus pay to encourage
fliers to stay longer in the military, as a way to deal with a
potential shortage of pilots, the Air Force chief of staff said
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The Air Force was reportedly expecting to be 835 pilots short
of its required 14,000 this year and it predicts that by 2002 the
pilot gap could more than double, causing possible readiness and
shortage problems.
</P>
<P>
Air Force Chief of Staff General Michael Ryan said Tuesday that
more than 800 pilots refused bonuses of 60,000 U.S. dollars to
extend their time in service five years beyond the nine they
signed up. Only 36 percent of pilots at the nine-year mark agreed
to stay on, said Ryan.
</P>
<P>
He told reporters at the Pentagon that the experienced pilots
are decreasing partly because they were often deployed away from
families or given administrative jobs that take them out of the
cockpit.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the lure of better money in commercial flying also
is adding to a rising attrition rate of veteran Air Force pilots,
he said.
</P>
<P>
"It's not their fault they're leaving," Ryan said. "It may be
our fault. It's hard work and it's hard on their families."
</P>
<P>
The Air Force is now offering bonuses of up to 110,000 dollars
for a five-year extension, while pilots who agree to stay for a
couple of years more can get an extra 22,000 dollars annually.
</P>
<P>
The Air Force also is to replace some desk jobs that are now
held by pilots with Air Force personnel who don't fly. And it is
trying to reduce overseas assignments for pilots, including for
military exercises. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
