<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-21 20:26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Libya: Solution to Lockerbie Being Worked Out </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, April 21 (Xinhua) -- A senior Libyan official said
Tuesday moves will be taken in days to reach a solution
"acceptable to all" on ending the Libya-West crisis over Lockerbie
air bombing, Egypt's Middle East News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Libyan Secretary of Justice and Public Security Mohamed
Belqassim al-Zawi made the remarks following a meeting with Arab
League (AL) Secretary General Esmat Abdul-Meguid to coordinate
future moves to settle the dispute over the trial of two Libyans
suspected in blowing up a Pan-Am flight over Lockerbie, Scotland,
in 1988.
</P>
<P>
Al-Zawi said their talks covered the recent decision by the
International Court of Justice (ICJ) to handle the crisis and the
recent special session of the U.N. Security Council to follow up
the latest developments.
</P>
<P>
U.N. sanctions were imposed on Libya in 1992 in response to
Tripoli's refusal to hand over the two Libyan suspects in the
bombing of the Pan-Am flight in which 270 people were killed.
</P>
<P>
Britain and the U.S. insist the two Libyans be tried in Britain
or the U.S., a stance rejected by Libya.
</P>
<P>
Libya has said more and more countries have supported Libya in
terms of reaching a compromise on having the two Libyans stand
trial in a neutral country no matter who the judges will be or who
will choose them.
</P>
<P>
Al-Zawi attributed this to years of efforts by Tripoli, the AL,
the Organization of African Unity, the Non-Alignment Movement and
the Organization of Islamic Conference.
</P>
<P>
He said Tripoli has reached an agreement with Jim Swire and
Robert Black, two representatives of the British victims, to exert
collective efforts to pressurize Britain and the U.S. to accept a
flexible and peaceful solution.
</P>
<P>
Swire and Black visited Libya on Thursday, carrying suggestions
to Libyan officials on bringing the two Libyan suspects to trial
before an international judiciary body, comprising five judges,
presided over by a Scottish judge to be appointed by the British
prime minister.
</P>
<P>
The Libya-West showdown has been again put under the spotlight
following the ICJ ruling in February, that the court has the
authority to settle the Lockerbie case.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. and Britain have watered down the ruling and insisted
that the Security Council is the body concerned with the issue.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
