<HEADLINE> Cohen: U.S. Willing to Help Better Greek-Turkish Relations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, April 21 (Xinhua) -- The United States was willing to
help Greece and neighboring Turkey to improve their strained
relations, said U.S. Defense Secretary William Cohen after meeting
his Greek counterpart Akis Tsohatzopoulos on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press conference, Cohen, who arrived here Tuesday
from Turkey on a lightning visit, said that they discussed the
Greek-Turkish relations, the Cyprus problem and the situation in
the Balkan region.
</P>
<P>
He said that Washington was willing to help both countries turn
from an atmosphere of suspicion to a climate of trust, calling on
an end to the use of threat of force.
</P>
<P>
The two countries should resolve their disputes through
negotiations, he said.
</P>
<P>
With an increase in contacts and the exchange of ideas, the
possibility of a peaceful solution of Greek-Turkish differences
was increased.
</P>
<P>
Describing Cyprus' deployment of Russian-made S-300 anti-
aircraft missiles as "a mistake," Cohen stressed that ways must be
found to bring Turkish Cypriots and Greek Cypriots to talks.
</P>
<P>
As for the Balkan rapid-reaction force, he said that U.S. could
also help in the creation of a multinational force for the Balkans
with the aim of aiding regional stability and cooperation.
</P>
<P>
For his part, Tsohatzopoulos said that Greece was concerned
about the security of Cyprus and would stand by it in the defense
of rights as long as there was a threat whether from Turkish
troops on the island or from the refusal of Turkey to contribute
to the ending of the military cooperation and to an acceptable
resolution of the Cyprus problem. 
</P>
</TEXT>
