<HEADLINE> Namibia's Diamond Output Expected to Grow </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, April 21 (Xinhua) -- Namibia's diamond output is
expected to grow significantly after Namibian Minerals
Corporation (Namco) recovered gem quality diamonds off the
Namibian coast.
</P>
<P>
It is envisaged that with the entry of Namco into offshore
mining, offshore diamond production in Namibia would increase by
up to 20 percent this year, South African Press Association
(SAPA) reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Namibia's total diamond production could increase by more than
500,000 carats a year, SAPA said.
</P>
<P>
Namco estimated that it would recover 150,000 carats of
diamonds valued at about 27 million U.S. Dollars in the first
year of production.
</P>
<P>
The company started operation at the Koichab area in Luderitz
Bay early this year.
</P>
<P>
Namco's Chief Executive Officer and Chairman, Alastair
Holberton, was quoted as saying at the weekend that 95 percent of
the diamonds recovered are of gem quality.
</P>
<P>
Namco has reportedly finalized a three-year marketing
agreement with IDC Holdings, a private company based in London
and Antwerp.
</P>
<P>
IDC's Managing Director, Jack Lumer, said that the shape and
purity of the diamonds recovered by Namco were particularly
attractive to manufacturers and that he did not envisage any
problems in establishing a strong overseas demand for the gems.
</P>
</TEXT>
