<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Greek Army Chief in Cyprus for Military </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, April 22 (Xinhua) -- Chief of Staff of the Greek Army
Athanasios Tzoganis pledged here Wednesday that Cyprus and Greece
will enhance military cooperation in accordance with the joint
defense pact between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Tzoganis made the remarks upon his arrival here Wednesday for a
three-day official visit to Cyprus, which is the first of its kind
by a Greek army chief of staff.
</P>
<P>
The Greek military official told reporters that he will have
meetings with Cypriot political and military leaders and will be
briefed on military issues regarding Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
Tzoganis noted that "Cyprus' defense capability is today at a
far better level than ever before, especially since the
implementation of the joint defense pact." He was referring to the
joint defense pact signed between the two countries in November
1993, which provides protection for Cyprus' air and sea by Greece
in case of a new Turkish offensive against the island.
</P>
<P>
"We can confront existing threats to a great extent and the
reason I am here is to continue efforts for improvement and
examine the solution of possible problems or face any threats,"
Tzoganis said.
</P>
<P>
On Cypriot government's decision to purchase Russian-made
anti-aircraft missiles, Tzoganis said "Cyprus is an independent
state and it is its government that takes these decisions,
therefore I'm sure that every decision taken would be to the
benefit of Cyprus."
</P>
<P>
Later Wednesday, Tzoganis had a meeting with Cypriot President
Glafcos Clerides, during which they exchanged views on military
issues concerning Greece and Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
During his visit, Tzoganis is expected to visit a newly-built
military air base in the western coastal district of Paphos, which
is to be named after the late Greek Prime Minister Andreas
Papandreou.
</P>
<P>
Turkey has warned that it will destroy military aircraft
deployed on the air base if it is used by Greece.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided into Greek Cypriot-dominated south and
Turkish Cypriot-controlled north since 1974 when Turkey landed its
troops and took over the northern third of the island in the wake
of a short-lived Greek Cypriot coup seeking union with Greece.
</P>
<P>
Turkey has maintained about 40,000 troops in the northern part
of the island. Turkish Cypriots unilaterally declared a breakaway
"Turkish Republic of Northern Cyprus" in 1983, which is only
recognized by Turkey. 
</P>
</TEXT>
