<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 1500 GMT, April 22 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO -- Visiting Chinese Vice-President Hu Jintao said
Wednesday that the development of Sino-Japanese friendly and
cooperative ties has brought great benefits to the two countries
and the two peoples.
</P>
<P>
Hu made the remarks here during a meeting with Japanese Foreign
Minister Keizo Obuchi.
</P>
<P>
Noting that bilateral relations have made remarkable progress
in various fields since the normalization of diplomatic ties
between the two countries, Hu expressed appreciation over Japan's
positive attitude in promoting bilateral ties. (Japan-China-Visit)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BEIJING -- President Jiang Zemin, in a meeting here Wednesday
with Portugal's Prime Minister Antonio Guterres, said that China
and Portugal and the European Union should make joint efforts to
bring peace, stability and prosperity to the world in the 21st
century.
</P>
<P>
Jiang said that the prime minister's visit is very important
because of Macao's return to China next year, and that friendly
relations between China and Portugal will be further promoted and
cooperation in the last phase of the transition period
strengthened through this visit.
</P>
<P>
He said that as long as both parties emphasize the overall
situation and long-term stability and development of Macao, and
solve certain problems, the transition will be smooth.
(China-Jiang-Portugal-Meeting)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat has rejected a
British proposal on separating the issue of Gaza airport from
Israel's further redeployment in the West Bank, Israel Radio
reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The report quoted diplomatic sources in Jerusalem as saying
that Arafat's position could make it very difficult for the
upcoming London talks to achieve progress in advancing the stalled
peace process.
</P>
<P>
British Prime Minister Tony Blair, who wrapped up a three-day
visit to the region Tuesday, proposed that Israel and the
Palestinians first settle the Gaza airport issue and the launching
of the Karni industrial park on which they have agreed in
principle. (Palestine-Britain-Proposal)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
GENEVA -- The United Nations Commission on Human Rights
rejected a U.S. motion Tuesday to renew the resolution on
investigating Cuba's human rights record for another year.
</P>
<P>
Of the 53 commission members, 19 voted against the motion, 16
for and 18 abstained. The motion was submitted by the United
States alone.
</P>
<P>
It was the first time that a U.S.-backed anti-Cuba resolution
had been turned back since 1992, and the vote result was seen
another major diplomatic blow to the U.S. (UN-Cuba-Motion)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Thirty Arab interior and justice ministers met here on
Wednesday to finalize and sign a landmark agreement on fighting
terrorism.
</P>
<P>
The meeting is an Arab effort to hammer out a joint
anti-terrorism strategy.
</P>
<P>
The draft agreement calls on signatory states to cooperate in
preventing and combating terrorism in accordance with laws and
internal measures.
</P>
<P>
It opposes any possible attempts of the signatory states to
organize, finance, commit or take part in committing terrorist
acts in any way. (Arab-Fighting Terrorism)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
MANILA -- Negotiators from the Philippine government and the
separatist Moro Islamic Liberation Front (MILF) Wednesday pushed
through with their scheduled low-level talks in a southern
Philippine city.
</P>
<P>
Ghadzali Jaafar, MILF vice chairman for political affairs, told
the Philippine News Agency (PNA) that a joint government-MILF
committee on the cessation of hostilities met in Marawi city,
capital of Lanao del Sur province, in the morning.
</P>
<P>
In the two-day meeting, Jaafar said, the MILF will continue to
seek for the government's recognition of MILF territories in
Mindanao island, the southern Philippines. (Philippines-Peace
Talks) 
</P>
</TEXT>
