<HEADLINE> Chinese Minister Meets With Portuguese Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 22 (Xinhua) -- China will become an aging
society in 20 years, with more than 250 million people above the
age of 60.
</P>
<P>
This was revealed by Doje Cering, Chinese Minister of Civil
Affairs, while meeting with Eduardo Rodrigues, Portuguese minister
of Solidarity and Social Security, here today.
</P>
<P>
Aging will be a major problem that China has to face in the
future, he said, and both men agreed that exchanges and
cooperation on research on aging should be increased, because it
is a challenge to most countries.
</P>
<P>
China has more than 120 million senior citizens, who account
for 9 percent of its population, Doje Cering said. A recent survey
showed that the number of the elderly in China is growing at 3
percent annually, and by the year 2030, the number of the elderly
is expected to exceed the population of Europe.
</P>
<P>
China is ready to increase exchanges with all countries and to
learn from their experience, he said.
</P>
<P>
Rodrigues said the problem is global and that he hopes that
Portugal and China will increase exchanges between experts and
make a joint effort to find solutions to the problem.
</P>
<P>
Doje Cering also gave Rodrigues a briefing of the structure and
functions of his ministry and the Basic Social Security System in
China. 
</P>
</TEXT>
