<HEADLINE> UN Aid For Northwestern Chinese Province </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XINING, April 22 (Xinhua) -- Four United Nations officials have
finished their first visit to a UN poverty-relief project in
China's Gansu Province.
</P>
<P>
The visit lasted from April 18 to 22 and the officials say they
are satisfied with the local government efforts in the project,
which is Gansu's largest agricultural development program, with an
investment of 35.7 million US dollars.
</P>
<P>
The officials from the UN Office of Project Services,
International Foundation of Agriculture Development, and World
Food Program visited the counties of Hualong, Xunhua, and Ping'an,
where the project is being carried out and where it is expected to
benefit 260,000 people, half of Gansu's total number of
impoverished people.
</P>
<P>
The project started last year and has developed 381 ha of
farmland, planted 850,000 trees, built 7 km of rural roads, and
trained 340,000 farmer technicians.  
</P>
