<HEADLINE> Israeli Soldier, Allied Militiaman Wounded in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, April 22 (Xinhua) -- An Israeli soldier and a
pro-Israeli militiaman were wounded Wednesday during Lebanese
guerrilla attacks in south Lebanon, the country's Voice of the
People radio reported.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli soldier was wounded when his position at the
hilltop of Radar inside the Israeli occupied south Lebanon came
under mortar barrages by the guerrillas of the Iranian-backed
Hezbollah, or Party of God.
</P>
<P>
The radio quoted security sources in the country's coastal
city of Tyre, not far from the occupied zone, as saying that they
saw a total of five missiles landed inside and around the Radar
position at noon.
</P>
<P>
In retaliation for the attack, Israeli artillery bombarded the
villages of Mensulia and Majdal Zoun, north of the western sector
of the zone, believed to be the Hezbollah hideaways.
</P>
<P>
The shelling did not cause any casualties, the radio added.
</P>
<P>
In another development, a member of the pro-Israeli South
Lebanese Army (SLA) was wounded by a roadside bomb explosion
inside the SLA-controlled town of Jezzine in the northern part of
the zone.
</P>
<P>
Israel set up a 1,200-square-kilometer "security zone" in south
Lebanon in 1985 with the proclaimed aim of protecting its northern
settlements from cross-border Lebanese guerrilla attacks. Since
then, the Israeli occupying forces and the SLA have been engaged
in a war of attrition with a resistance movement spearheaded by
Hezbollah. 
</P>
