<HEADLINE> HK Retains Third Place in Global Competitiveness </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, April 22 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong retained its third
rank, despite the adverse impact of the Asian financial crisis, on
this year's list of the world's most competitive economies, Hong
Kong press reports said on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The United States holds on to its No. 1 place, followed by
Singapore, according to World Competitive Yearbook annual
rankings, published by the International Institute for Management
Development in Lausanne, Switzerland.
</P>
<P>
The report rates the competitiveness of 46 economies by
measuring economic strength, openness to trade, government
policies, financial services, infrastructure, management, science
and technology, education and training.
</P>
<P>
Japan slipped out of top 10 most competitive economies --
plunging from ninth in 1997 to 18th this year, the report said.
</P>
<P>
China moved up the list to 24th from 27th last year.
</P>
<P>
Russia remained bottom of the table in 46th place. 
</P>
</TEXT>
