<HEADLINE> Malaysian Navy to Get Frigates from U.K. Next Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, April 22 (Xinhua) -- The Malaysian navy will
receive two GEC-Yarrow F-2000 guided-missile frigates from Yarrow
Shipbuilders LTD of Scotland by early next year, Navy Chief
Vice-Admiral Ahmad Ramli Nor said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"The plan is for them (Yarrow) to deliver the frigates by the
end of this year and we receive them early next year. We will then
begin the process to commission the ship into the navy's armada,"
he was quoted by the Malaysian national news agency Bernama as
saying at the on-going Defense Services Asia '98 (DSA '98) here.
</P>
<P>
The navy chief cited difficulties in integrating various
state-of-the-art combat systems on board the ships -- KD Jebat and
KD Lekiu -- as the main reason behind the frigates' late delivery.
</P>
<P>
The ship's combat system was made by a Dutch-based company
while the cannon and missiles system was from France and the sonar
from Germany.
</P>
<P>
He said the various systems installed on the 1.42 billion
ringgit (about 380.697 million U.S. dollars) frigates needed a
powerful computer for processing a high flow of information which
was the main cause of the problem.
</P>
<P>
The frigates were planned to be armed with Bofors 57mm guns,
British Aerospace Dynamic Vertical Launch Seawolf air defense
missiles and Aerospatiale MM-40 Exocet anti-ship missiles.
</P>
<P>
He said the navy had not decided on the type of the shipborne
helicopter to complement the frigate's role.
</P>
<P>
There are about 20 Malaysian navy personnel stationed at the
shipyard to oversee the project and to familiarize themselves with
the technology on board the ships. 
</P>
</TEXT>
