<HEADLINE> Bird Week Starts in Northeast China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGCHUN, April 22 (Xinhua) -- A week-long exhibition started
today in China's Jilin province to get humans better acquainted
with their friends, the bird.
</P>
<P>
It has displays and picture shows to help people learn more
about birds' habits, migration, and the protection they need,
according to the provincial museum of natural history.
</P>
<P>
There are some 9,000 types of birds on earth now, 1,100 of
which exist in China. Jilin is reported to have 328 kinds,
including 60 on the state protection list.
</P>
<P>
But, their numbers are decreasing sharply and some rare species
are even on the verge of extinction because of environmental
pollution, forest destruction, and bird poaching, says Yang Shihe,
secretary-general of the Jilin Provincial Wildlife Protection
Association.
</P>
<P>
In response to the State Council's call to help the birds in
1981, the provincial government has held a series of activities
like tree planting, hanging up bird houses, summer camps, and
seminars, to help people, especially children, be more aware of
the importance of wildlife protection.
</P>
<P>
More than 2,000 injured animals have received help in the past
decade, according to one provincial official, who says that 8
natural reserves have been built in the region.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
