<HEADLINE> China Looking For Fair Competition In Telecommunications </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 22 (Xinhua) -- Li Huifen, the CEO of China
United Telecommunications Corp., told the 1998 China Business
Summit of the World Economic Forum here today that China is
redoubling its efforts to promote fair competition in the
telecommunications sector by drawing a clear line between the
function of government and enterprises and improving legislation.
</P>
<P>
She said that the Ministry of Information Industry will help
the development of a competitive mechanism in the domestic
telecommunications market and that, as an administrative institute
of the information industry, the Ministry will not interfere in
the operations of telecommunications companies.
</P>
<P>
She said that there won't be a case of it being both a player
and a judge in a competitive market.
</P>
<P>
China Unicom, which was set up in 1994 to break the 40-year-old
monopoly of China's telecommunications by China Telecom, is the
only other national state-owned company providing basic
telecommunications services.
</P>
<P>
Li said that China also needs a better legal framework to halt
monopolies and to see that there is fair competition.
</P>
<P>
China Unicom has a mobile telephone network in over 80 cities,
and local telephone operations in two cities and is building
another local telephone network in Chengdu, in southwestern
China. The number of customers is expected to exceed one million
by the end of this year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
