<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Needs More Planes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 22 (Xinhua) -- China's need for airplanes will
increase greatly in the next few years, according to Chen Feng,
chairman and president of Hainan Airlines Company Ltd.
</P>
<P>
Chen told the 1998 China Business Summit of the World Economic
Forum here today that the number of passenger and cargo planes
flying feeder routes in the country is inadequate to meet the
demands of China's fast growing economy.
</P>
<P>
Chen said the volume of domestic air transport will grow
steadily over the next 20 or so years. In 1996, one out of every
25 Chinese flew at least once and that was about a sixth of the
world average. At the same time, demand for air transport grew at
twice the world average.
</P>
<P>
Chen said that civil airlines are in great need of cargo
planes. There are only 8 cargo planes flying on non-trunk routes
in the country at present, and the capacity of feeder routes still
lags far behind that of rapidly expanding trunk routes.
</P>
<P>
He said that the growth of small regions and complex
topographical factors call for an expansion of feeder lines.
</P>
<P>
In the past few years, China has imported a number of 100- to
200-seat aircraft from foreign manufacturers like Boeing, and that
civil airlines will decide the type of sideline airplanes they
want according to the length of feeder routes and their specific
operating costs.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
