<HEADLINE> U.S. Bank Chief to Visit Zimbabwe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, April 22 (Xinhua) -- Chairman of the United States
Export-Import Bank James Harmon will lead a business development
mission for a two-day working visit to Zimbabwe this week, the
U.S. information service in Harare said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
In a statement, the information service said Harmon would
arrive on Thursday in Bulawayo, Zimbabwe's second largest city,
where the country's international trade fair is being held.
</P>
<P>
During his visit, Harmon will hold a series of meetings with
business, financial and government leaders.
</P>
<P>
The visit, the first by a U.S. Export-Import Bank chairman to
southern Africa, is part of an eight-day business development
itinerary to three Aub-Saharan Africa countries which include
Namibia and South Africa.
</P>
<P>
The mission is a follow-up to U.S. president Bill Clinton's
recent trip to Africa and the bank's commitment to the bi-partism
"patnership for economic growth and opportunity in Africa"
legislative initiative, the information service said.
</P>
<P>
Harmon would also use the trip to assess demand for financing
U.S. exports to promote and expand the exports to Africa.
</P>
<P>
The bank activities in Zimbabwe have been concentrated in
aircraft, mining, telecommunications and manufacturing sectors.
</P>
<P>
Since 1993, the bank has financed 653 million U.S. dollars in
exports to nine Sub-Saharan countries and recently established an
advisory committee to coordinate its activities in the region.
</P>
</TEXT>
