<HEADLINE> Myanmar Rejects Human Rights Charges </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, April 22 (Xinhua) -- The Myanmar government Wednesday
rejected allegations against it of human rights abuse and ethnic
repression.
</P>
<P>
The rejection is believed to be directed against a resolution
on the human rights situation in Myanmar presented at a current
meeting of the United Nations Human Rights Committee.
</P>
<P>
"The anti-Myanmar-government elements routinely, through
Amnesty International, are deliberately fabricating such stories
to influence a report to the committee on the human rights
situation in Myanmar," the government said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
The Myanmar government also refuted allegation that it imposed
"oppressive measures against ethnic and religious minorities". It
said 99 percent of all the armed ethnic groups have renounced
armed struggle and made peace with the government. 
</P>
