<HEADLINE> China's Supreme Court Approves Death Penalty In 3 Cases </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 22 (Xinhua) -- China's Supreme People's Court
today upheld the death penalty for three people who were found
guilty of making fake value-added tax invoices.
</P>
<P>
The three were executed today by local police authorities.
</P>
<P>
Wu Yonggui and Wu Tianhong of Zhejiang Province and Xu Shitie
of Hubei Province made a large number of false value-added
invoices and used them to avoid paying 3.32 million yuan, 3.31
million yuan, and 18.75 million yuan in taxes, respectively. Each
of them earned several hundred thousand yuan from the business.
</P>
<P>
They were sentenced to death and deprived of political rights
for their lives by the local courts in accordance with the law
after the first and second court rulings.
</P>
<P>
In examining the three cases, the Supreme People's Court said
that the three, in making false value-added invoices, have caused
great losses to the state, and should be dealt with harshly.
</P>
</TEXT>
