<HEADLINE> Middle East Business Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, April 22 (Xinhua) -- The following are business briefs
from Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
TEHRAN -- Iran will import 3 million tonnes of wheat this year
to meet its domestic demand, a major newspaper Wednesday quoted an
Iranian official as saying.
</P>
<P>
Deputy chief of Iran's Grain Organization Masoud Kouchak
Mohseni said on Tuesday that Iran's wheat production was
expected to be 10.5 to 11 million tonnes this year and the
government hoped to buy 7 million tonnes from farmers.
</P>
<P>
AMMAM -- The Jordanian Arab Investment Bank, which has five
branches in the Palestinian self-rule areas, will open a sixth
branch in the West Bank city of Hebron next month.
</P>
<P>
Vice board chairman of the bank Hani Al-Qadi said that the
Hebron branch is now rendering all banking services to its
customers there.
</P>
<P>
He said that the total assets of the branches have increased to
65 million U.S. dollars from 45 million dollars in 1996.
</P>
<P>
MANAMA -- Bahraini Minister of Oil and Industry Sheikh Issa Bin
Ali al-Khalifa, said at a conference in Manama Wednesday morning
that his country plans to expand and develop its gas conveyance
and distribution network at several stages.
</P>
<P>
He said that the expanding and developing processes will
cost 60 million U.S. dollars and will be carried out from
1998 to 1999.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Egyptian Petroleum Minister Hamdi al-Banbi has
announced that as much as 8.6 billion Egyptian pounds (about 2.5
billion dollars) would be devoted to the biggest project for the
accumulation and conveyance of natural gas in the West Desert.
</P>
</TEXT>
