<HEADLINE> Arafat Rejects Britain's Delinking Proposal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, April 22 (Xinhua) -- Palestinian leader Yasser
Arafat has rejected a British proposal on separating the issue of
Gaza airport from Israel's further redeployment in the West Bank,
Israel Radio reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The report quoted diplomatic sources in Jerusalem as saying
that Arafat's position could make it very difficult for the
upcoming London talks to achieve progress in advancing the stalled
peace process.
</P>
<P>
British Prime Minister Tony Blair, who wrapped up a three-day
visit to the region Tuesday, proposed that Israel and the
Palestinians first settle the Gaza airport issue and the launching
of the Karni industrial park on which they have agreed in
principle.
</P>
<P>
He believed that once they make progress on the interim issues,
new momentum could be created to break the year-old deadlock in
the peace process.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinians have been insisting on an early implementation
of the long overdue Israeli redeployment in the West Bank as well
as a settlement of issues including the building of an airport and
seaport, and a safe passage between Gaza and the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
However, Blair did succeed in persuading Arafat and Israeli
Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu to attend the London meetings in
early May, during which the U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright will talk with them separately before a summit can be
held.
</P>
<P>
Arafat flew to Egypt Wednesday, one day after Blair's visit,
for talks with Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak. Mubarak has
invited Netanyahu for a meeting in Cairo to discuss the dangerous
situation of the peace process prior to the London meetings.
</P>
<P>
Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr Mousa said Arafat and Mubarak
discussed the U.S. proposal on Israel's second troop redeployment
in the West Bank and the Palestinian side has accepted the
U.S. plan for a 13.1 percent pullback in a period of 12 weeks in
exchange for new Palestinian security guarantees.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu convened his security cabinet early Wednesday to
discuss the redeployment. But so far there has been no sign that
Netanyahu is willing to give up more than 9 percent of the West
Bank.
</P>
<P>
Arafat and Mubarak apparently tried to coordinate their
positions before U.S. Middle East peace envoy Dennis Ross' return
to the region to sell the U.S. idea on Israeli withdrawal and work
out an agenda for the London meetings. 
</P>
</TEXT>
