<HEADLINE> Chinese Mortality Rate Continues to Drop </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 22 (Xinhua) -- About 6 out of every 1,000
Chinese died of illness, traffic accidents, poisoning, suicides,
and other causes last year, according to a Ministry of Health
report today.
</P>
<P>
The mortality rate in China has been falling in the past 40
years. In the 1950s, it was 11 out of 1,000 people.
</P>
<P>
The rate in cities is a bit lower than in rural areas, and
death of males is higher than that of females, whether in cities
or in rural areas.
</P>
<P>
Life in big cities like Beijing and Shanghai seems to cause
more deaths than in small and medium-sized cities. In big cities
there were more than 6 deaths per 1,000 people, compared to 4 per
1,000 in small and medium-sized cities.
</P>
<P>
The report said that the drop in the mortality rate did
not mean an increase in the natural growth rate, the difference
between the rate of births and the rate of deaths.
</P>
<P>
The population growth rate has continued to fall over the past
four decades, mainly because of a decrease of the birth rate.
</P>
<P>
From 1957 to 1997, China's birth rate had dropped from 34.03
per 1,000 to 16.57 per 1,000, and the natural growth rate of
population from 23.23 per 1,000 to 10.06 per 1,000. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980422.0108 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UNICEF Calls for More Urgent Aid to S. Sudan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, April 22 (Xinhua) -- Chief of the United Nations
Children's Fund (UNICEF) Carol Bellamy Wednesday called for more
emergency aid to southern Sudan at the end of her five-day visit
to Kenya, Somalia and Sudan.
</P>
<P>
She left for west Africa later the day after reviewing
UNICEF's humanitarian activities in the three countries.
</P>
<P>
"We are in a critical period -- with 300,000-350,000 --
vulnerable people at risk in the (southern Sudan's) Bar El Ghazal
alone. We are in the 'hungry' season," she said at a press
conference.
</P>
<P>
"We must also have more funding for seeds, tools and medicines
and more food pledges -- without this we cannot provide the
assistance required and thousands will die in the coming months,"
she warned, adding that the body needs two more planes to deliver
food in southern Sudan.
</P>
<P>
However, UNICEF, the coordinator of international aid
operations to southern Sudan through the Operation Lifeline Sudan
(OLS), "is pleased with the Sudanese government access clearance
earlier this month," she noted.
</P>
<P>
Now OLS, made up of UNICEF, World Food Program (WFP) and 35
non-governmental organizations, enjoys "the best access to its
operational areas, particular in the Bahr El Ghazal" after the
aid suspension in the previous two months, she said.
</P>
<P>
On Tuesday, the WFP warned that the food situation in the Bahr
el Ghazal region has reached a critical level and the region
would face catastrophe unless it receives more relief food soon.
</P>
<P>
Food needs in the area are estimated at a minimum requirement
of 6,000 tons for 350,000 of the worst affected people there.
</P>
<P>
Other areas in southern Sudan like Upper Nile and Eastern
Equatoria are also facing serious food shortages due to a
combination of drought and war, said the OLS earlier this week.
</P>
<P>
The Sudanese civil war broke out in 1983 when the rebel Sudan
People's Liberation Army (SPLA) re-started fights against the
Muslim-ruled north for more autonomy and religion freedom in the
animist and Christian-dominated south.
</P>
<P>
At least 1.3 million Sudanese have been killed by war or
war-related famine since then. 
</P>
</TEXT>
