<TEXT>
<P>
DAMASCUS, April 22 (Xinhua) -- Speaker of the Kuwaiti National
Assembly (Parliament) Ahmed Abdul Aziz Al-Sadoun stressed here
Wednesday that Israel should withdraw from south Lebanon immediately
and unconditionally.
</P>
<P>
Israel's proposal to withdraw from south Lebanon conditionally
is unacceptable for Lebanon, Syria or the Arab nation, Al-Sadoun
told reporters before ending a three-day visit to Syria.
</P>
<P>
Israel decided on April 1 to endorse the United Nations
Security Council Resolution 425 demanding a unilateral Israeli
withdrawal from Lebanon. But meanwhile, it said no troops would
be pulled back unless security arrangements are negotiated with
the Lebanese government.
</P>
<P>
Lebanon and Syria, which wants the return of the Golan Heights
captured by Israel in the 1967 Middle East War, have rejected the
offer. They insist that the withdrawal be unconditional.
</P>
<P>
The two countries agree to coordinate their stances on key
issues and not to unilaterally make peace with the Jewish state.
</P>
<P>
During the visit, Al-Sadoun held talks with Syrian President
Hafez al-Assad in the coastal resort of Latakia on bilateral,
regional and Arab issues.
</P>
<P>
He voiced support of Kuwait for Syria's principal position on
the Middle East peace process and other issues of the Arab world.
