<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australia: Traditional Family Is Fading Fast </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, April 22 (Xinhua) -- The notion of a traditional
nuclear family in Australia is fading fast with one in four
children living with only one of their natural parents, official
statistics showed Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
An Australian Bureau of Statistics (ABS) family survey found,
out of 4.6 million children aged under 18 in the country, 1.1
million lived with only one of their natural parents, usually as a
result of marriage breakdown.
</P>
<P>
It found almost one quarter, or 200,000 children, had no
contact with their other parents, either by visits, phone or
letter.
</P>
<P>
Of the 1.1 million children, there are more than 800,000
children lived in one-parent families while 350,000 lived in step
or blended families.
</P>
<P>
In the five years since the last ABS family survey, another
83,000, or 7.5 percent of new one-parent families were created.
</P>
<P>
The majority of children of broken homes lived with their
mothers (88 percent). Only three percent of those children were
cared for by parents equally in a shared arrangement.
</P>
<P>
The survey also found younger children were likely to visit the
non-custodial parents more frequently than older children, with 60
percent of children aged up to two years of age making fortnightly
visits to their other parents.
</P>
<P>
An alarming 41 percent of one-parent and blended families did
not receive any cash support payments from their non-custodial
parents. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980422.0114 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 47 People Killed by Bush Fire in Southern Sudan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, April 22 (Xinhua) -- At least 47 people were killed
by a weekend bush fire in northern swamp area of Tonj Country in
southern Sudan's Bahr el Ghazal Province.
</P>
<P>
A press release issued here Wednesday by the World Vision said
that the fire reportedly took off when a wind storm fanned the
flames of small fires lit by farmers to clear land for planting.
</P>
<P>
The fire swept through a settlement at the swamplands near the
village of Ananatak on April 19 where people in this area of
southern Sudan traditionally move to in the dry season in search
of water.
</P>
<P>
A World Vision team rushed to the site and discovered the
charred corpses of at least 15 people, said the press release,
adding that the death toll stood at 47 on April 21.
</P>
<P>
The release noted that the World Vision compound there also
sustained damage during a dust storm caused by strong winds.
</P>
<P>
Tonj County is one of the areas in Bahr el Ghazal Province
currently suffering from severe food shortage caused by a
combination of drought and insecurity. 
</P>
</TEXT>
