<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Marine Resources Becoming Major Part Of China's Economy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 22 (Xinhua) -- China plans to make marine
resources a major part of the country's economic development in
the next century, according to Jiang Chengsong, vice-minister of
Land and Natural Resources.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the 28th World Earth Day ceremonies, Jiang said
China's marine economy has grown at an annual rate of more than 20
percent over the past few years.
</P>
<P>
He said he expects the marine sector to have 500 billion yuan
in output value by the year 2000, or 5 percent of the country's
total GDP, and that will increase to 10 percent by 2010.
</P>
<P>
The country's marine economy mainly includes fisheries, salt
production, and shipping. China produces a fourth of the world's
aquatic products, and has ranked first in output worldwide for 7
years running.
</P>
<P>
It has developed 16,000 hectares of salt pans and has become
one of the world's largest sea salt producers.
</P>
<P>
Ocean transportation has also been growing rapidly, and its
main ports can handle more than 800 million tons annually.
</P>
<P>
Offshore oil and gas, marine fish breeding, tourism, marine
resources, and mining are all growing rapidly, Jiang said, and
China has made great headway in protecting its marines resources
for more than a decade.
</P>
<P>
He said that China strictly abides by the U.N. Maritime
Convention and has its own maritime laws and regulations.
</P>
<P>
To develop marine resources in a better way, China has drawn up
the National Marine Development Program, Policy on Marine
Technology, and Agenda on Marine Development in 21st Century, he
said, and is now drafting a white paper on the maritime policy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
