<HEADLINE> Lebanese FM Meets Ambassadors on Israeli </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, April 22 (Xinhua) -- Lebanese Foreign Minister Farez
Boueiz Wednesday met the ambassadors of the five permanent
members of the United Nations Security Council to explain
Lebanon's stance on Israel's withdrawal offer.
</P>
<P>
Boueiz told the ambassadors of China, Russia, France, the
United States and Britain that Israel's offer to withdraw from
south Lebanon is a "maneuver" aimed at separating Lebanon from
Syria in their peace talks with the Jewish state.
</P>
<P>
Israel decided on April 1 to endorse the U.N. resolution 425,
which demands a unilateral Israeli withdrawal from Lebanon. But
meanwhile, it said no troops would be pulled back unless security
arrangements are negotiated with the Lebanese government.
</P>
<P>
Lebanon and Syria, which agree not to unilaterally make peace
with Israel, have rejected the offer. They insist that the
withdrawal be unconditional.
</P>
<P>
Boueiz expressed hope that the five nations will support
Lebanon's position on the issue and help stop Israeli occupation
of its southern territories.
</P>
<P>
He is expected to meet with ambassadors of Arab, non-aligned
and European countries on Thursday in an effort to rally support
for the Lebanese stance.
</P>
<P>
Israel is occupying a 1,200-square-kilometer border strip in
south Lebanon to allegedly protect its northern areas from
cross-border attacks by Lebanese Muslim guerrillas. 
</P>
</TEXT>
