<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Focus on Water Conservancy Projects (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
According to Zhu, China is one of 13 countries with an
inadequate water supply, with per capita consumption equal to
one-fourth of the world's average. The utilization ratio of water
energy is only 10 percent, which has become a "bottleneck"
hindering the country's economic development, he said.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that China has invested more than 200 billion
yuan to build 85,000 reservoirs and 200,000 kilometers of dikes
and dams since 1949. As a result, the additional irrigated land
has reached 36 million hectares.
</P>
<P>
Though China invested 23.8 billion yuan on water facilities in
1996, 14.1 billion yuan more than 1992 figure, Zhu said the
country still needs to invest more. Most of the country's water
irrigation works were built in the 1950s or the 1960s, which
means they need to be outdated or repaired.
</P>
<P>
Zhu emphasized that the Central Government has earmarked a
special fund for key water projects. Local governments also
initiated a fund for the construction of local water facilities.
</P>
<P>
To raise more funds for water conservancy construction, he
said China should attract more overseas investment. So far,
China has introduced 770 million U.S. dollars of direct
overseas investment for the projects.
</P>
<P>
The Ministry of Water Resources has entrusted the Bank of China
to make preparations for an investment fund for medium- and
small-sized hydropower stations, which is a good example of ways
the country can absorb more overseas funds, he said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
