<HEADLINE> German MP Calls for Removal of Iran-German Row </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, April 22 (Xinhua) -- Iran and Germany should commit
themselves to removing hurdles in order to improve their ice-cold
relations, visiting German parliamentarian Gunter Verhugen was
quoted as saying Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with local daily Iran News, Verhugen said that
Bonn "seeks closer cooperation with Iran but this necessitates
action by both sides."
</P>
<P>
He named the Mykonos case and the death sentence on the German
merchant Helmut Hoffer in Iran as the two main obstacles to better
relationship between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
A Berlin court last April accused Iranian leaders of
involvement in the assassination of four Iranian Kurdish leaders
in the Mykonos restaurant in Berlin in 1992, stirring a political
crisis between Iran and the European Union (EU).
</P>
<P>
It was only until last November that relations between the EU
and Iran returned to normal. But this did not last long when an
Iranian court sentence the Germany merchant to death for having
illegal sexual relations with an Iranian woman.
</P>
<P>
Verhugen arrived here Monday on a visit aimed at convincing
Tehran to pardon Hoffer.
</P>
<P>
"Iran is a reliable trade partner for Germany and I encourage
the German government to invest in Iran and to attempt to solve
the political differences now looming," he said. 
</P>
