<HEADLINE> Alleviating Unemployment to Be Main Priority of Thai </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, April 22 (Xinhua) -- Thai Prime Minister Chuan Leekpai
said Wednesday that one of his government's priorities has been
the prevention and alleviation of the unemployment problem.
</P>
<P>
He made the remarks at the opening ceremony of the
International Labor Office's (ILO's) High-Level Tripartite Meeting
on Social Responses to the Financial Crisis in East and Southeast
Asian Countries held here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"Towards this end, I believe a comprehensive labor policy and
employment schemes -- focusing upon labor market information,
skill training, job creation and placement, wages and social
security systems, and industrial relations -- are necessary," he
said.
</P>
<P>
He also called for equal importance to be given to national and
international economic and social development policies.
</P>
<P>
Chuan noted that national action will not suffice and therefore
called for international cooperation at the international level.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, ILO Director-General Michel Hansenne highlighted the
impact of the economic crisis in the region.
</P>
<P>
An ILO report predicted that unemployment rates in Thailand,
Indonesia and South Korea, the three countries hardest hit by the
financial crisis, will rise to 6 percent, 10 percent and 7 percent
respectively.
</P>
<P>
Hansenne said the ILO stands ready to assist governments to
face up to the "vigorous structural reform" required, to enhance
the necessary dialogue between governments, workers and employers
and to put in place social safety nets which "not only soften the
blows of crisis but contribute to preventing them from occurring."
</P>
<P>
The three-day high-level tripartite meeting involves workers,
employers and governments facing the negative social consequences
of the financial crisis in the region.
</P>
<P>
The meeting will focus on employment and social protection
issues and review the social consequences of reform policies,
propose actions at country level and discuss follow-up measures.
</P>
</TEXT>
