<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cancer, Respiratory Illness Are China's Biggest Health Threats </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 22 (Xinhua) -- About 135 out of every 100,000
Chinese urbanities died of cancer and some 147 out of every
100,000 rural people died of respiratory illnesses last year,
according to a report released by the Ministry of Health today,
making them the major cause of death in China.
</P>
<P>
Cancer has replaced cerebral hemorrhage as the No.1 killer in
cities and was responsible for more deaths than in 1996. Males
seem to be more susceptible to the deadly diseases than females.
</P>
<P>
Respiratory illnesses caused fewer deaths than in 1996, but
still remained the biggest threat to people in rural areas.
</P>
<P>
Ten major diseases or problems account for more than 91 percent
of the total number of deaths. These include cerebral hemorrhage,
heart attacks, injuries, poisoning, and digestive tract problems.
</P>
<P>
More urbanites are having problems with endocrine,
neurological, and mental disorders, and rural people still have to
deal with infant illnesses, tuberculosis, and some infectious
diseases. They often have little or no access to medical services
and some infectious diseases are still not under control and pose
a big health problem, according to Liu Aimin, of the Chinese
Academy of Medicine.
</P>
<P>
But, at the same time, many urbanites with better access to
medicare are showing new problems like nervous disorders caused by
the pressures of excessive work and competition, he says.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
