<HEADLINE> Chinese Language World Cup Soccer Web Site Launched </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, April 22 (Xinhua) -- The world's most comprehensive
Chinese language World Cup '98 Web Site was officially launched
here on Wednesday, offering Chinese language Internet viewers
around the globe unparalleled coverage of this summer's festival
of football.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese language World Cup Wed Site has been developed by
China Internet Corporation (CIC), a Hong Kong-based company
responsible for the creation of the nationwide business
information network China Wide Web supported by such world leading
news and information organizations as Xinhua News Agency, AFP and
Reuters, in partnership with China Telecom.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese language World Cup site, at the Web addresses
http://www.worldcup98.china.com and
http://www.worldcup98.hongkong.com, provides coverage of World Cup
France '98 to viewers across China's mainland via China Telecom's
public communications network, and to Chinese language Internet
users in Hong Kong, Asia, and the rest of the world.
</P>
<P>
"I'm delighted to be associated with the launch of the Chinese
language World Cup Web Site, which provides important opportunity
to positively promote the work of local Hong Kong football, as
well as that of international football, to a global Chinese and
English language Internet audience," Timothy Fok, President of the
Hong Kong Football Association, said at the launching ceremony.
</P>
<P>
The site, available to Internet viewers in both simplified and
traditional Chinese characters, as well as English language
football fans, with fast-breaking news, photos and graphics
provided by Agence France Presse (AFP).
</P>
<P>
The World Cup site offers news coverage on the teams and events
in the weeks leading up to the finals, together with a guide to
the groups and fixtures, and match forecasts, venues, dates and
times for all the matches from Stage 1 through to the Finals on
July 1 this year.
</P>
<P>
A comprehensive World Cup archive details the news events,
scorers, facts and figures throughout the entire history of the
world's largest football competition. Football fans can also get
in on the action with interactive "chat rooms", World Cup site
email newsletters and exciting competitions for World Cup prizes.
</P>
<P>
"China is a country with perhaps the largest soccer following
in the world - this is yet another example of China Internet
Corporation leveraging on advanced multi-media technology to bring
compelling and engaging content to Chinese Internet viewers," said
China Internet's Director of Product Management Vicky Hung.
</P>
<P>
"In 1997, China Internet was responsible for delivering
comprehensive coverage of Hong Kong's historic handover to a world
Internet audience. This year the World Cup provides a focus for
delivering world-class Internet content to Chinese language
Internet audiences, and will play a further significant role in
Internet development in China," she added.
</P>
<P>
"The launch of the World Cup Wed Site is a milestone for the
co-operation between AFP and CIC and Xinhua," said Denis Brulet,
AFP's Regional Director for Asia Pacific.
</P>
<P>
"And we look forward for an even closer co-operation in the
future," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
