<HEADLINE> Plane Replica Installed at HK New Airport </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, April 22 (Xinhua) -- The Farman biplane replica,
which flew over the new Hong Kong International Airport five
months ago, was installed at the airport passenger terminal
Wednesday for long-term display.
</P>
<P>
The original Farman biplane, flown by Belgian aviator Charles
Van den Born, made the first powered aircraft flight in Hong Kong
on March 18, 1911. A full-sized, flying replica was commissioned
by the Hong Kong Historical Aircraft Association (HKHAA) and was
built with funds provided by Shell Hong Kong Ltd.
</P>
<P>
At a handover ceremony Wednesday afternoon, Shell's director
Robert Young said, the replica will invite admiration and respect
from millions of visitors to Hong Kong, as it truly represents the
daring and entrepreneurial spirit of the city.
</P>
<P>
He hoped that it will "serve as an inspiration for generations
to come."
</P>
<P>
Airport Authority board member Maria Tam noted that the Farman
replica will "serve as a reminder to us all of the great
accomplishments made in the development of aviation in Hong Kong."
</P>
<P>
Dr. Ted Pryor, chairman of the HKHAA, revealed the
association's next goal -- the building of a world-class aviation
museum of Hong Kong, a site for which has already been reserved on
the old airport at Kai Tak.
</P>
<P>
"The facility will honor Hong Kong's aviation pioneers and
provide a unique attraction for both local residents and overseas
visitors," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
