<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hong Kong Customs Seize Smuggled Cigarettes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, April 22 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong customs officers
seized 300,000 smuggled cigarettes worth about 400,000
H.K. Dollars (51,282 U.S. Dollars), and arrested three suspects in
an anti-cigarettes-smuggling operation here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
During the operation, there was a minor crash between the
customs vehicle and the goods vehicle, but no injury was reported.
</P>
<P>
The three suspects, aged between 22 and 35, will be charged
with offense of dealing with goods to which dutiable commodities
ordinance applies and obstructing the customs officers from
execution of their duties.
</P>
<P>
Following in-depth investigations, officers from the Marine and
Land Enforcement Command followed a target goods vehicle in Sham
Shui Po, Kowloon, early Wednesday morning.
</P>
<P>
Around 7.30 am, the officers swung into action on seeing two
suspects removing cartons of dutiable cigarettes off the vehicle
in a street. The officers arrested the two men and the driver
following a chase.
</P>
<P>
The maximum penalty for the offense is a fine of 1 million
H.K. Dollars and imprisonment for two years, said a spokesman for
the Customs and Excise Department.
</P>
<P>
The anti-cigarettes-smuggling operation is still continuing to
smash distribution centers of contraband cigarettes, he added.
</P>
</TEXT>
