<HEADLINE> Release of ICRC Workers in Somalia Hopeful </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOGADISHU, April 22 (Xinhua) -- The release efforts of the ten
staff of the International Committee of the Red Cross (ICRC)
kidnapped in Mogadishu continued Wednesday with elders from the
Abgal clan of Ali Mahdi and representatives from the kidnappers
engaged in one of their last serious talks.
</P>
<P>
Sources close to the negotiators said the abductors have
receded from their point of asking for nearly one million US
Dollars ransom. The elders are now pressing the abductors not to
mention any kind of ransom, but accept what are offered by the
business community of their people.
</P>
<P>
The sources said discussions continued with the intention to
offer the gunmen something between 60,000 and 150,000 US Dollars.
The elders Wednesday expressed a great hope that they will be
able to secure the release of the hostages sometime late the day
or Thursday the latest.
</P>
<P>
According to an aid worker who visited the kidnapped ICRC
staff members, the health of the hostages is good and they are
fed well even though they have been terrorized Tuesday after the
release efforts nearly fell apart.
</P>
<P>
The mattresses were taken away from them and they were told
that there's no one here in Mogadishu worrying about their
existence or release so that they should talk to their relatives
and superiors outside Somalia with a cellular telephone they were
offered, said the worker.
</P>
<P>
However, early Tuesday afternoon, everything was restored back
to normal, the mattresses were given back and discussions resumed
until two o'clock Wednesday morning before they took a break of a
few hours. Now the discussions continue again, the hope is that
they will be released late the day or Thursday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
