<HEADLINE> China to Focus on Water Conservancy Projects </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 22 (Xinhua) -- China has mapped out an ambitious
plan for water conservancy facilities in the next 13 years.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with Xinhua here recently, Zhu Dengquan,
vice-minister of the Ministry of Water Resources, said that top
priority will be given to the sector during the 1998-2010
period.
</P>
<P>
China will reinforce its dikes and dams and the
nationwide water supply will be increased to 680 billion cubic
meters by 2010 and the total irrigated land of the country is
projected to hit 57 million hectares, he noted.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, China will expand its installed hydropower
capacity to 150 million kilowatts by 2010 and control 1.4 million
square kilometers of soil erosion.
</P>
<P>
According to Ren Guangzhao, another high-ranking official of
the ministry, during the 13 years, China will pay more attention to
the construction of irrigation works of all sizes.
</P>
<P>
At first, he said, the country will give priority to the
construction of flood-control works located on big rivers and
lakes, especially the Three Gorges Project on the Yangtze River
and the Xiaolangdi Project on the Yellow River.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the annual growth rate of water supply is planned
to reagh 1.4 percent to meet the demand of economic development.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
