<HEADLINE> First 23 Genocide Convicts to Be Executed Friday </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, April 22 (Xinhua) -- The first executions of 23
genocide convicts will take place in Rwanda on Friday at 10:00
a.m, the Rwanda News Agency Wednesday quoted the state-run Radio
Rwanda as reporting.
</P>
<P>
The number of convicts announced in Radio Rwanda's news
broadcasts was initially 33.
</P>
<P>
But Rwandan Minister of Justice Faustin Nteziryayo explained
that "only 23 will be executed, because the files of other
convicts who have requested presidential clemency have not yet
been completed."
</P>
<P>
Five locations have been selected for the public executions.
They are Nyamirambo Soccer Stadium in the capital Kigali, Nyamata
in Kigali Rural, Cyasemakamba in eastern Kibungo prefecture,
Murambi in northeastern Umutara prefecture, as well as Gikongoro
in Gikongoro prefecture.
</P>
<P>
"This will act as a lesson to people who do not respect the
life of others and the government is condemning those who are
still carrying out the killings of innocent people," Radio Rwanda
commented Tuesday morning.
</P>
<P>
All those who will be executed had applied for the
presidential clemency, which has been refused.
</P>
<P>
With these executions, Rwandan courts are showing that they
are willing to punish those who committed the 1994 atrocities.
</P>
<P>
More than 500,000 people reportedly perished in the 1994
genocide that was perpetrated by the presidential guard, the
former government soldiers, and the extremist Hutu militia and
some locals who have been incited to wipe out Tutsis and
opposition Hutus. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
