<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-22 11:47 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> - Arab Ministers Meet for Anti-Terrorism Pact </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, April 22 (Xinhua) -- Thirty Arab interior and justice
ministers met here on Wednesday to finalize and sign a landmark
agreement on fighting terrorism.
</P>
<P>
The meeting is an Arab effort to hammer out a joint
anti-terrorism strategy.
</P>
<P>
The draft agreement calls on signatory states to cooperate in
preventing and combating terrorism in accordance with laws and
internal measures.
</P>
<P>
It opposes any possible attempts of the signatory states to
organize, finance, commit or take part in committing terrorist
acts in any way.
</P>
<P>
The document defines terrorism as an act of violence or a
threat to use violence, irrespective of motives or ends, that
takes place to implement an individual or collective criminal
scheme aimed at terrorizing people, endangering their lives, and
destroying the environment, or public or private utilities, or
national resources.
</P>
<P>
However, the draft pact confirms the right of the people to
armed struggle against foreign occupation and aggression.
</P>
<P>
It legitimizes the struggle to liberate occupied lands, obtain
the right to self-determination and independence and maintain
national unity according to the principles and resolutions of the
United Nations.
</P>
<P>
Egypt's official Middle East News Agency said that all the Arab
countries have accepted the agreement. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980422.0143 </DOCNO>
