<HEADLINE> Indonesian Gov't to Speed Up State Enterprises Reform </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, April 22 (Xinhua) -- The Indonesian government here
Wednesday pledged to speed up it state enterprises reform in a bid
to enhance their efficiency in the fiscal year 1998/99 (starting
April 1).
</P>
<P>
State Minister of the Empowerment of State Enterprises Tanri
Abeng said at a press conference that "The reform will be
conducted in the fields of management and ownership," adding the
target is to accelerate the privatization.
</P>
<P>
The government projects it will raise 15 trillion rupiah (1.87
billion U.S. dollars) from the privatization program, said Abeng.
</P>
<P>
Currently, there are five state companies listed on the Jakarta
bourse. Another seven state companies will be privatized soon
either through initial public offerings or private placement by
inviting strategic investors.
</P>
<P>
Officials said earlier, the proceeds from the share sales would
be used mainly to help cover the 1998/99 budget deficit, which is
estimated at 3.2 percent of the gross domestic product.
</P>
<P>
The budget deficit will be generated mainly by subsidy spending
on staple foods, fuel, electricity, medicines and credits for
cooperatives and small and medium-sized enterprises.
</P>
<P>
The minister said the privatization program was part of the
reform package agreed between the Indonesian government and the
International Monetary Fund early this month.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, he said, the government will cooperate with the
World Bank in drawing up transparent privatization procedures
which will be finished at the end of June this year.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia has a total of 164 state firms. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
