<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Trade Minister on WTO Membership for China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 22 (Xinhua) -- Shi Guangsheng, Chinese minister
of Foreign Trade and Economic Cooperation, has called for an end
to China's exclusion from the World Trade Organization (WTO).
</P>
<P>
Shi made the call today during talks with Joaquim Pina Moura,
Portuguese minister of economics.
</P>
<P>
Membership in the organization is "not only a need of China,
but also of the WTO," said Shi following an in-depth briefing
on the Chinese government's position on the issue.
</P>
<P>
Chinese Customs statistics show the country's 1997 trade volume
posted a year-on-year growth of 12.1 percent to 325.06 billion
U.S. dollars, making the country the 10th largest trading nation
in the world.
</P>
<P>
Portugal supports China's entry into the WTO, said Moura,
adding Portugal is willing to play its role in the European Union
to support China's WTO membership.
</P>
<P>
The two sides agreed that the global economic affairs should be
decided by the majority of countries through equal consultations,
rather than simply by a few, so as to ensure a sound
development of the world economy.
</P>
<P>
Moura pointed out that China has already established a basic
structure for free trade.
</P>
<P>
He said Portugal will fully consider China's special conditions
as a developing country, and expressed the hope that the European
Council would pass a resolution defining China as a market economy.
</P>
<P>
Shi expressed appreciation for Portugal's stand, and noted that
China's entry into the WTO will greatly enhance its economic
cooperation with Portual and other countries.
</P>
<P>
The two ministers also discussed matters related to mutual
investment and trade issues.
</P>
<P>
Moura is visiting China along with Portugal's Prime Minister
Antonio Guterres.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
