<DOCNO> XIE19980422.0149 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> California Lawmakers Reject Appeal for Computer Makers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, April 21 (Xinhua) -- A proposal to limit computer
makers' liability for the year 2000 problem died Tuesday when a
California legislative committee voted against it.
</P>
<P>
The State Assembly Judiciary Committee agreed with trial
lawyers that the industry should not be given cover for "a crisis
of its own making."
</P>
<P>
Co-authored by two California Assembly men, the proposal meant
to limit the financial liability of designers and manufacturers of
computer systems, programs and software due to problems expected
on January 1, 2000, when many old systems may miscalculate the new
year and "crash" unless they are retrofitted or replaced.
</P>
<P>
Of the 15 votes, the proposal received only six in favor. The
bill needed at least eight votes to pass.
</P>
<P>
The year 2000 problem is projected to cause billions of dollars
worth of damage as a result of computer malfunctions and billions
more will be spent in advance on system repair.
</P>
<P>
Lawsuits could be another cost resulting from it. The committee
Tuesday was told that lawsuits in California against hardware and
software companies could easily total 2 billion dollars or more.
</P>
<P>
Much of the debate presented to the committee turned on a key
legal question about the year 2000 problem -- is it a product
defect? If so, then manufacturers of the product should be held
responsible.
</P>
<P>
One side of the argument held that the problem arose not from
negligence but from limited resources. The other side said that it
was an intentional design defect, citing the fact that some
companies have continued to market computers with the glitch.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980422.0150 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-22 </DATE_TIME>
