<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IMF to Decide Second Tranche of Aid to Indonesia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, April 22 (Xinhua) -- The International Monetary Fund
(IMF) will decide its second 3 billion U.S. dollar tranche of
bailout package for Indonesia at the Fund's board meeting to be
held on May 4, a senior official said here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The assistance, part of the IMF-led 43 billion U.S. dollar
package, will be implemented in three stages, said Coordinating
Minister of Economy, Finance and Industry Ginandjar Kartasasmita
at a press conference held jointly by several cabinet ministers
after attending a meeting of the Economic and Financial Resilience
Council headed by President Soeharto.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, he said, the World Bank and the Asian
Development Bank (ADB) will also hold their board meetings
separately to decide their promised aids to Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
The ADB had agreed to provide 1.5 billion U.S. dollars to
Indonesia while the World Bank one billion U.S. dollars in the
near future.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia and the IMF reached an agreement in October last year
on the 43 billion U.S. dollar package. The Indonesian government
promised to conduct wide-ranging economic and financial reforms.
</P>
<P>
In December last year, the IMF gave the first 3 billion U.S.
dollar tranche of assistance to Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
However, it delayed the second 3 billion dollar tranche of the
bailout package.
</P>
<P>
Ginandjar said the government has seriously carried out its
latest agreement with the IMF signed on April 8.
</P>
<P>
He said the value of the rupiah has picked up from 10,200
against the U.S. dollar on March 17 to 7,750 per dollar on April
22.
</P>
<P>
This indicated that the public confidence in the rupiah and the
country's economy has gradually recovered, he added.
</P>
<P>
The Indonesia's economy has been badly hit by the Southeast
Asian monetary crisis since July last year. The rupiah has lost
more than 70 percent of its value against the greenback. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
