<HEADLINE> Share Prices Continue to Decline on Singapore Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, April 22 (Xinhua) -- Share prices continued to
decline on the Singapore market as the benchmark Straits Times
Industrials Index (STII) lost another 16.82 points to close at
1475.52 points on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Dealers said that the STII slumped mainly on a three percent
plunge in the index's largest component, the Singapore Press
Holdings (SPH). The financial stocks also took a knock, they said.
</P>
<P>
The total market volume was thin at 137.29 million units,
valued at 321.83 million Singapore dollars (about 202.41 million
US dollars). Declines again overwhelmed advances by 224 to 90,
while 281 other counters remained unchanged.
</P>
<P>
Singapore Telecom was the most actively traded counter as it
registered a turnover of 6.75 million units. It was followed by
Lion TeckC which had 5.07 million shares traded. Rekapac was next
with 4.95 million shares changed hands.
</P>
<P>
Asean led the gainers of the day as it rose by one dollar to
finish at 8.5 US dollars. Local computer sound card maker Creative
50 and local soft drink maker F&AMP;N increased by ten cents each to
end at 35.9 and 6.6 Singapore dollars respectively. ITE Elec was
up by six cents to close at 32 cents.
</P>
<P>
On the downside, Transmarco was the biggest loser as it
declined by 2.3 dollars to end at eight Singapore dollars. SPH
(Singapore Press Holdings) fell by 60 cents to close at 16.9
Singapore dollars. OCBC (Overseas Chinese Banking Corporation)
lost 30 cents to finish at 6.5 Singapore dollars. 
</P>
