<HEADLINE> Marijuana to be Banned in Sydney Olympics </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, April 22 (Xinhua) -- Marijuana is certain to be
banned by the International Olympic Committee's (IOC) for the
Sydney 2000 Olympic Games, a top IOC official said in Sydney on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Executive board member Jacques Rogge of Belgium said the IOC
wanted to outlaw recreational drugs to avoid a repeatition at this
year's Winter Olympics when Canadian snowboarder Ross Rebagliati
was allowed to keep his gold medal despite testing positive for
cannibas.
</P>
<P>
"The IOC has taken the decision that it will ban these
so-called soft drugs," Rogge was quoted as saying. "We will change
the rules to avoid these loopholes."
</P>
<P>
The IOC responded by setting up a task force of its own four
executive board vice-presidents to formulate a clear policy on
recreational drugs which it planned to present at next week's IOC
board meeting in Sydney. 
</P>
</TEXT>
