<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. Human Rights Commission Rejects U.S. Motion Against Cuba </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, April 22 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations Commission on
Human Rights rejected a U.S. motion Tuesday to renew the
resolution on investigating Cuba's human rights record for another
year.
</P>
<P>
Of the 53 commission members, 19 voted against the motion, 16
for and 18 abstained. The motion was submitted by the United
States alone.
</P>
<P>
It was the first time that a U.S.-backed anti-Cuba resolution
had been turned back since 1992, and the vote result was seen
another major diplomatic blow to the U.S.
</P>
<P>
In his annual report last month to the commission, Carl-Johan
Groth, the U.N. rapporteur to Cuba since 1992, criticized a
40-year-old U.S. embargo against Cuba and said human rights record
in the U.S. itself needed improvement.
</P>
<P>
Before the vote, Carlos Amat Flores, head of the Cuban
delegation, said the international community had recognized "a
series of signals" that Cuba is opening up, including Pope John
Paul II's visit to his country last January.
</P>
<P>
He accused Washington of having a "history of supporting brutal
dictatorships around the world," saying the U.S. embargo against
Cuba was "the only case of massive violation of human rights in
Cuba." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980422.0173 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Angolan Forces to Defend Territorial Sky </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, April 22 (Xinhua) -- Angolan Defense Minister Pedro
Sebastiao has said that the Angolan armed forces will act within
days to defend its territorial sky.
</P>
<P>
Since the territorial sky of Angola is still facing invasion
by unidentified planes, the armed forces will take actions soon
to avert the situation, Sebastiao told the press Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
He said that the armed forces will also take measures to
ensure the safety in land border areas, particularly, in the
northern and eastern frontiers.
</P>
<P>
As to the peace process in Angola, Sabastiao said that the
1994 Lusaka Peace Protocol is being implemented.
</P>
<P>
He added that positive steps have been made in politics,
while many problems still exist in military aspect.
</P>
<P>
The defense minister said that measures must be taken if the
military situation continues worsening.
</P>
<P>
Recently, the remnants of the National Union for Total
Independence of Angola (UNITA) kept creating disturbances,
attacking the newly-established local governments and ambushing
vehicles running normally on the highway, which has greatly
threatened the safety of the people and their properties.
</P>
<P>
Sebastiao revealed to the media that the Angolan armed forces
will fight unremittingly against the criminal armed groups across
the country.
</P>
<P>
Fighting against the organized criminals is in line with the
peace accord, Sebastiao said, adding that it needs no approval
from any authority because the main mission of the Angolan armed
forces is to maintain peace and territorial integrity of the
country.
</P>
<P>
Since October 1997 when the United Nations Security Council
passed resolutions to impose sanctions against UNITA, planes from
some countries still invade into the Angolan air to send
materials to the rebel movement.
</P>
<P>
In January, the Angolan Air Force interrupted one plane from
South Africa transporting materials for UNITA. Then, the United
Nations and the Organization of African Unity repeatedly demanded
that the member countries should comply with the U.N. Security
Council's sanction resolutions.
</P>
<P>
Sebastiao disclosed that a workshop on national defense will
be held by the defense ministry from April 23 to 25. The
workshop is aimed at enabling the leaders of People's Assembly,
the administration and the armed forces to understand profoundly
the operations of the national defense organs.
</P>
<P>
Defense experts from Portugal, the United States and Brazil
will be invited to make speeches at the meeting, Sebastiao said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980422.0174 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Africa Upgrades in Competitive List </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, April 22 (Xinhua) -- South Africa has moved up
from 44th to 42nd in a list of the 46 most competitive nations in
the world, the Business Day reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
South Africa is now ranked ahead of Venezuela, Colombia,
Poland and Russia, the newspaper quoted an economic survey as
saying.
</P>
<P>
The survey released in Lausanne, Switzerland showed that
countries such as India, the Philippines, Turkey and Czech
Republic seem to be more competitive.
</P>
<P>
Struggling Japan plunged down the list, while the United
States stayed in the top spot, the survey showed.
</P>
<P>
Japan fell nine places in the World Competitive Yearbook
annual rankings, from ninth in 1997 to 18th this year. Five
years ago, Japan ranked the second.
</P>
<P>
According to the survey, Singapore ranked second and Hong Kong
held third place this year as they did in 1997. And China also
rose to 24th from 27th place this year.
</P>
<P>
The study compares the competitiveness of the 46 countries
measured in terms of their economic strength, education and
openness to international trade.
</P>
<P>
The survey defines national competitiveness as a country's
ability to help its businesses to be competitive. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980422.0175 </DOCNO>
