<HEADLINE> 14 Killed in C. Nigerian Communal Clash </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, April 22 (Xinhua) -- At least 14 people, including two
women, were killed Tuesday in a renewed clash between the Bassa
and Ebira communities in Toto, a border town between Nassarawa
state and capital Abuja, in central Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
Several vehicles, buildings and dispensing pumps of some
petrol stations in the town were also burnt in the fracas which
began Monday night, the Daily Times reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The national newspaper said that four fresh human heads were
seen hung beside a transformer in the heart of the town by
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Sources were quoted as saying that the main cause of the
dispute was traceable to the age-long land feud between Ebira and
Bassa which had been worsened by political differences.
</P>
<P>
The hitherto quiet town of Toto was in a war mood, with youths
and men, mostly Ebiras, brandishing arrows, cutlasses, bows,
machetes and guns.
</P>
<P>
A detachment of mobile policemen were reported to have been
drafted to the area to maintain peace, but the daily said they
were nowhere to be found.
</P>
<P>
However, an inspector of police was quoted as saying that
there was nothing they could do to contain the development.
</P>
<P>
"That was why we laid down our arms and we are outside," he
added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
