<HEADLINE> Deals Worth 3b Inked at Guangzhou Fair </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, April 22 (Xinhua) -- The ongoing 83rd China Export
Commodities Fair in Guangzhou, capital of south China's Guangdong
Province, has reported business deals valued at over 3.07 billion
U.S. dollars since opening on April 15.
</P>
<P>
The business volume for the seven-day period equalled figures
for the 1996 fair, but fell by 3.29 percent when compared to 1997
fair.
</P>
<P>
The European Union, United States, Hong Kong and Macao recorded
increased transaction volumes during the week.
</P>
<P>
However, the business volume for Southeast Asian countries fell
by 100 million U.S. dollars when compared to the previous fairs.
</P>
<P>
Light industrial products and arts and crafts accounted for the
lion's share of business transactions, with impressive figures
also recorded for electronic products and machinery, textiles and
clothing.
</P>
<P>
Brisk business volumes were also recorded for high value-added
scientific and technological products, and quality export
commodities.
</P>
<P>
The two week fair attracted 37,579 business people from 156
countries and regions through April 21, respective rises of 6.29
percent and 6.43 percent on the previous two fairs. 
