<HEADLINE> Philippine Government, Muslim Rebels Resume Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, April 22 (Xinhua) -- Negotiators from the Philippine
government and the separatist Moro Islamic Liberation Front (MILF)
Wednesday pushed through with their scheduled low-level talks in a
southern Philippine city.
</P>
<P>
Ghadzali Jaafar, MILF vice chairman for political affairs, told
the Philippine News Agency (PNA) that a joint government-MILF
committee on the cessation of hostilities met in Marawi city,
capital of Lanao del Sur province, in the morning.
</P>
<P>
In the two-day meeting, Jaafar said, the MILF will continue to
seek for the government's recognition of MILF territories in
Mindanao island, the southern Philippines.
</P>
<P>
But Lt. Gen. Joselin Nazareno, head of the government cessation
committee, said the government will try to negotiate only for a
"hands-off" policy on two major MILF camps, according to the PNA.
</P>
<P>
The two camps are Abubakar, the largest MILF stronghold located
in Maguindanao province, and Busrah in Lanao del Sur province.
</P>
<P>
Other MILF-held areas will be considered "zones of peace" by
the government, Nazareno said.
</P>
<P>
Boasting a membership of nearly 12,000, the MILF is currently
the largest anti-government force in the country after the
mainstream Moro National Liberation Front (MNLF) signed a peace
treaty with the government in 1996.
</P>
<P>
The government began low-level peace talks with the MILF in
January 1997 and forged a comprehensive ceasefire in June. But the
two sides are still wide apart over the agenda and the timetable
for formal peace talks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
