<HEADLINE> Cambodian King Sihanouk Meets Price Ranariddh </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SIEM REAP, Cambodia, April 22 (Xinhua) -- Cambodia's King
Norodom Sihanouk Wednesday met with his son Prince Norodom
Ranariddh at Siem Reap where he is staying.
</P>
<P>
Ranariddh, who arrived here on Wednesday morning from Bangkok,
told reporters after the meeting that he and his father talked
about the forthcoming general elections and the supervision of the
elections by international observers.
</P>
<P>
But they did not touch the issues of a ceasefire and pardon to
the generals who supported him, the prince said.
</P>
<P>
Ranariddh added that he and his father appealed to the
Association of Southeast Asian Nations (ASEAN) countries, the
United States, Japan and the United Nations to send more observers
to Cambodia to supervise the preparations and the process of the
elections.
</P>
<P>
He stressed the elections cannot be held smoothly without the
cooperation of the Funcinpec and the Cambodian People's Party, the
two largest parties led by him and Hun Sen, the second prime
minister who ousted him last July.
</P>
<P>
Ranariddh reiterated that he had no cooperative relations with
the Khmer Rouge and did not know if General Nhiek Bun Chhay and
Ta Mok, the remaining leaders of Khmer Rouge, had their forces
integrated.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, King Sihanouk said that he was very pleased
to see the international efforts that helped Cambodia hold the
elections, and reaffirmed his support to a joint statement
released by the "Troika" of the ASEAN and the Friends of Cambodia
on Sunday in Bangkok.
</P>
<P>
It was Ranariddh's second trip home, but his first meeting with
the king since he was granted royal pardon.
</P>
<P>
He was sentenced in absentia by a military court last month to
35 years in prison and ordered to pay more than 50 million
U.S. dollars in damages.
</P>
<P>
The king pardoned him on March 21, paving the way for him to
participate in the elections scheduled for July 26. 
</P>
</TEXT>
