<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigeria May Amend Constitution for Presidential </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, April 22 (Xinhua) -- A provision may have been made in
Nigeria's yet-to-be released draft 1995 Federal constitution for a
sole presidential candidate in the country, the Guardian reported
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The leading national daily based the projection on the
thinking of the country's Transition Implementation Committee
(TIC), which said Tuesday that the adoption of Head of State
General Sani Abacha by all the five political parties was borne
out by the "secret" constitution.
</P>
<P>
The draft constitution has been used by the government
sometimes, but only few Nigerians are aware of the contents of
it.
</P>
<P>
The polls will still be held on August 1 to pick a president
as the parties' consensus adoption of Abacha has not foreclosed
to scheduled election, TIC said.
</P>
<P>
The only difference is the voting will be a yes-or-no choice
on the candidature of the head of state, TIC added.
</P>
<P>
The latest development did not mark an end to the current
transition to civil rule program Abacha launched three years ago,
TIC Deputy Chairman Alhaji Hassan Yusuf said, adding that
Abacha's sole candidacy was neither undemocratic nor
unconstitutional.
</P>
<P>
"If it reaches the closing of nomination day and it is only
one candidate, then the election will be held by vote of 'Yes' or
'No'," he said.
</P>
<P>
But the United States and Britain have berated the adoption of
Abacha as the sole presidential candidate in one voice.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. decried that the adoption has made the transition
program "seriously flawed and failing", alleging that the
Nigerian government has manipulated the democratic process in the
west African country.
</P>
<P>
Britain has threatened that Commonwealth ministers were likely
to meet soon to discuss whether to apply a limited package of
sanctions against Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
It is reported that the two countries are to hold talks
shortly on what to do about Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Nigeria's National Democratic Coalition has also
unfolded plans to resist Abacha's candidature. The
anti-government organization also called on supporters to reject
it. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
