<HEADLINE> Beijing Marks 2,000 Years of Buddhism in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 22 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Buddhists and scholars
have urged that more attention be paid to Buddhism's modern
situation after the religion has spread in China for 2,000 years.
</P>
<P>
"Buddhism is still attracting a great number of people in an
era of high-technology and prosperous economy, and the fact has
proved the religion's significance," said Jin Hui, vice president
of the China Buddhism Association, at a forum held here today at
the Chinese Academy of Social Sciences (CASS) to mark the 2000th
anniversary of Buddhism in China.
</P>
<P>
Statistics from the association show that there are 200,000
monks and nuns registered at temples throughout China, and
hundreds of millions are influenced by the religion.
</P>
<P>
Master Jin Hui said that it is not wise to eye Buddhism as
something backward that is about to become extinct. But he also
hinted that Buddhism should improve its self-management in
accordance with Chinese law to enable it to survive into modern
times.
</P>
<P>
"Buddhists should respect other people's and Party's beliefs,
and cooperate with the government to achieve political goals," he
said.
</P>
<P>
Chinese Buddhists have been persecuted and temples damaged at
least four times during the past 2,000 years for political
reasons, Liu Ji, vice president of the CASS, said, adding that the
most serious case occurred during the so-called "Cultural
Revolution" (1966-76). But everything has changed after the reform
and opening-up in the late 1970s when the Party's policy of
religious freedom was resumed.
</P>
<P>
The recent policy promulgated by the central government is to
actively guide Buddhism.
</P>
<P>
Liu also suggested that Buddhism be reformed to help push the
"Spiritual Civilization," a campaign to train more patriots and
morally perfect citizens.
</P>
<P>
Many of the scholars and monks said at the forum that China
should focus on research into Buddhism's modern functions,
including diplomatic and commercial functions.
</P>
<P>
A Buddhism research center, whose members are professors from
more than 10 universities and eminent monks nationwide, was
established at CASS today.
</P>
<P>
Buddhism, which originated in India, entered China 2,000 years
ago. There have been debates on the accurate year of its Chinese
debut.
</P>
<P>
In recent years, many Chinese and Japanese scholars believed
that 2 B.C. was the year when Buddhism first appeared in the
country.
</P>
<P>
Buddhism spread to other Asian countries, including Korea and
Japan, and the Zen School, which was a typical Chinese version of
Buddhism, has even found its way into the West. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980422.0185 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mongolian Parliament Accepts Government Resignation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ULAN BATOR, April 22 (Xinhua) -- The Great Hural (parliament)
of Mongolia Wednesday accepted resignation of the government led
by Prime Minister Mendsaikhan Enkhsaikhan.
</P>
<P>
At its Wednesday session, 59 deputies voted for and one against
the government's request for resignation en masse.
</P>
<P>
Enkhsaikhan was requested to stay in the prime minister's
office of a caretaker cabinet before the Great Hural appoints a
prime minister to form a new government.
</P>
<P>
On January 15, the Great Hural passed two laws which allow
parliament members to concurrently hold government posts including
premiership.
</P>
<P>
On April 16, the National Democratic Party and the
Social-Democratic Party asked Enkhsaikhan's government to resign
and hand the premiership to the chairman of their coalition -- the
Democratic Union.
</P>
<P>
Enkhsaikhan submitted a formal request to Great Hural Chairman
Radnasumberlyn Gonchigdorzh afterward.
</P>
<P>
Tsakhiya Elbegdorj, vice-chairman of the Great Hural and
president of the National Democratic Party, is expected to be the
new prime minister. 
</P>
</TEXT>
