<HEADLINE> Rich Nations Urged to Assist Developing Countries with Water </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 22 (Xinhua) -- Rich nations should voluntarily
help developing countries with water resource development and
management with generous support in funding and technology
transfer, said a senior Chinese water official here today.
</P>
<P>
Zhu Dengquan, 59, vice-minister of water resources, said that
developing countries are trapped in a dilemma of developing an
economy and reducing pollution.
</P>
<P>
"Failing to cooperate with developing nations in their struggle
for sustainable use and protection of water resources, developed
countries' interest in water resources will also inevitably
suffer," Zhu said.
</P>
<P>
Zhu told Xinhua in an interview, "I quite appreciate French
President [Jacques] Chirac's words, 'what is to cause the next
century's wars and strife will not be crude oil and land, but
water resources."
</P>
<P>
He said that advanced countries stress commercial benefits too
much and the nature of intellectual property rights of their
skills when negotiating with developing countries over water
resources aid.
</P>
<P>
As a result, he added, they largely end up playing word games
in fulfilling their promise of helping developing countries.
</P>
<P>
"Advanced countries have a duty to assist developing countries,
providing them with no-interest or low-interest loans," he
said. "They should also be more generous in technological
transfer."
</P>
<P>
"Assistance in water resource management should be a
governmental action rather than a commercial one," he noted.
</P>
<P>
Zhu attended an international conference on water and
sustainable development in Paris last month. He said that many
delegates showed strong interest in China's experiences in water
resource development, protection and management, hailing China's
experiences as reference for other developing countries.
</P>
<P>
Many businesspeople also approached the Chinese delegation with
topics such as how to participate in China's water supply and
hydro-power generation, believing that there is an enormous
investment potential in water resources in China, he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980422.0187 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Private Sector Prosperous in Beijing's Economy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 22 (Xinhua) -- The Yuebin Restaurant located in
the Cuihua Hutong (Lane) of Beijing has only one room and three
tables, but it is regarded as a trend-setter in the capital's
private economic sector.
</P>
<P>
Eighteen years ago, Zhang Guixian, 47, opened the Yuebin,
Beijing's first privately run restaurant, with 1,000 yuan (120
U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
Zhang's courageous move was highly praised at a time when China
had just started its economic reform and opening-up to the outside
world.
</P>
<P>
Talking about those past years, Zhang said that although her
restaurant was small, it always drew a large number of clients
that included government officials, sociologists, foreign
ambassadors and journalists.
</P>
<P>
Privately run restaurants can be found everywhere in Beijing
nowadays. And the private economic sector is expanding into all
fields, from small businesses to the high-tech industry and real
estate.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that Beijing now has more than 40,000 privately
run enterprises, with registered assets of 25 billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
Some privately run businesses, like Yongyou Software and Yeshi
Clothing, have developed into large conglomerates and own market
shares in other parts of the country and overseas.
</P>
<P>
Unlike Zhang Guixian, private business entrepreneurs in
Beijing, currently do not have to start their business in their
middle ages. Many young entrepreneurs are well-educated and know a
lot about state policies.
</P>
<P>
Shao Genhuo, a 32-year-old with a doctorate degree in
philosophy from the China Agricultural University, set up an
animal feeding company with only 20,000 yuan four years ago. He is
now boss of Beijing's largest privately run group dealing with
farming and animal husbandry.
</P>
<P>
His group, named "Dabeinong," has acquired more than 30
state-owned enterprises by means of purchasing, shareholding,
trusting and leasing, and solved problems of re-employment of
several hundred workers. Last year, sales volume of Shao's group
reached nearly 600 million yuan.
</P>
<P>
Zhang Shicheng, vice-president of the Beijing Society of
Self-Employed and Private Business, said nearly 800,000 people in
Beijing are now engaged in the non-public-owned economic sector
like self-employment and privately run businesses, which have
become an important channel of employment. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
