<HEADLINE> Japan's Deputy Foreign Minister Visits Iran </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, April 22 (Xinhua) -- Japanese Deputy Foreign Minister
Masahiko Komura arrived here on Wednesday for a four-day visit.
</P>
<P>
Iran's official news agency IRNA reported that Komura is
expected to convey a message from Japanese Prime Minister Ryutaro
Hashimoto to Iranian President Mohammad Khatami.
</P>
<P>
But it did not disclose the details.
</P>
<P>
Komura's visit is viewed as defying United States efforts to
isolate the Islamic republic.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. has imposed economic sanctions on Iran and asked its
allies not to develop political and economic relations with the
country.
</P>
<P>
Japanese ambassador in Tehran Takaya Suto was quoted by IRNA as
saying that Komura's visit is "very crucial" and would help expand
the Tehran-Tokyo ties in political, economic and cultural fields.
</P>
<P>
Suto said that Iran, as an oil-rich country, plays a key role
in issues in the Persian Gulf, Middle East and Central Asia.
</P>
<P>
He voiced welcome to Khatami's proposal to carry out dialogs
among different civilizations, which he said would help defuse
regional and international tensions.
</P>
<P>
Japan became Iran's biggest trade partner last year with a
trade volume of 4.44 billion U.S. dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
