<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading French Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, April 22 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news items
in leading French newspapers Wednesday:
</P>
<P>
Liberation:
</P>
<P>
-- Ten years after the Matignon Agreement which put an end to
violent conflict between France and the Kanak independence
fighters of New Caledonia, the parters of the South Pacific
territory and the French government Tuesday signed in Noumea an
agreement on the future status of the territory.
</P>
<P>
The agreement predicts a large autonomy for the island, prior
to its full independence in a transitional period of 15 to 20
years. The agreement will be submitted for approval by the local
parliament at the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
-- For the first time in history, the French National Assembly
summoned four former government ministers, including former Prime
Minister Edouard Balladur, for a hearing on Tuesday on the role
played by France in Rwanda before, during and after the 1994
genocide. Although the ministers pleaded for the "positive" role
played by France, the hearing was more significant in symbolic
meaning than the contents of the questions and answers.
</P>
<P>
Le Figaro:
</P>
<P>
-- The deputies from the centrist Union for French Democracy
and the Socialist Party in the National Assembly will establish a
united front Wednesday in voting for the government project on
introducing the European single currency euro. The deputies of the
Gaullist Rally for the Republic (RPR) and the Communist Party
said they will vote against the draft law.
</P>
<P>
PRP parliament group chairman Jean-Louis Debre said that
although the RPR supports euro, it does not approve the
"political manipulation" by the Socialist government to impose its
economic and social policy through the law.
</P>
<P>
-- April 27 will be the 150th anniversary of the abolition of
slavery by France. Victor Schoelcher, a State Under-Secretary for
Colonies, issued a decree abolishing slavery in the wake of the
1848 Revolution.
</P>
<P>
About 12 million Africans were sold from their homes to America
by Europeans in more than three centuries. France joined "the slave
trade" for 200 years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
