<HEADLINE> Australian FM to Visit Vietnam </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, April 22 (Xinhua) -- Australian Foreign Minister
Alexander Downer announced here Wednesday he will visit Vietnam
from April 24 to 28 for talks with Vietnamese leaders over
political, economic and trade issues.
</P>
<P>
During his visit, Downer said, he will "meet for the first time
with the new Vietnamese leadership, including the president and
prime minister, as well as the deputy prime minister" and his
counterpart Foreign Minister Nguyen Manh Cam.
</P>
<P>
"The bilateral relationship continues to expand, with regional
security dialogue and human rights dialogue as important features
of that relationship," Downer said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
Australia and Vietnam, which established diplomatic ties 25
years ago, "also share a range of key regional interests," Downer
said.
</P>
<P>
"My visit takes place as Vietnam prepares itself for (the)
membership of APEC (Asia Pacific Economic Cooperation), which
Australia warmly welcomes, and in the lead-up to its hosting of
the ASEAN (Association of Southeast Asian Nations) summit at the
end of this year," he added.
</P>
<P>
"While in Vietnam I will discuss the details of Australia's aid
with Vietnam and explore ways in which Australia and Vietnam can
work together in the further economic and social development of
Vietnam."
</P>
<P>
Downer said he will meet representatives of the Australian
business community in both Hanoi and Ho Chi Minh City.
</P>
<P>
"Australian businesses are well represented in Vietnam in
construction and building supplies, telecommunications, banking,
accounting, brewing, manufacturing, dairy products and education
and training."
</P>
<P>
"I will seek to encourage Vietnamese government leaders to
continue their commitment to economic reform which will further
open up opportunities for two-way trade and investment." 
</P>
</TEXT>
