<HEADLINE>   Middle East Business Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, April 22 (Xinhua) -- The following are business briefs
from the Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
AMMAN -- French hotel company ACCORD signed a tourist agreement
with the Jordan Investment Cooperation (JIC) on Tuesday on
developing tourist projects in Jordan.
</P>
<P>
Under the deal, the ACCORD will market the Ma'in spa near
Amman and the JIC will send 10 people to France to learn the
principles of tourist administration in ACCORD companies,
semi-official Jordan Times reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The pact was a follow-up to the first official tourist
agreement between the two countries signed in 1992.
</P>
<P>
AMMAN -- The United States' denim-maker Jordache is planning to
open a joint plant with a local partner at the newly-established
Qualifying Industrial Zone (QIZ) in Irbid to cash in on the
duty-free status for the zone's products destined for U.S. market.
</P>
<P>
The Jordache Inc. and the Century Investment Group of
Jordan (CIG) hope to export their casual wear products to
the U.S. and Europe by the end of 1998, according to Jordan Times
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
As an appreciation of Jordan's contribution to the Middle
East peace process, the U.S. earlier this year allowed Jordan
to establish the QIZ. Commodities made in the QIZ can be
exported to the U.S. duty free.
</P>
<P>
AMMAN -- Sixteen international companies are competing to win a
concession for operating a future railway which is to facilitate
transportation of phosphate from the Dead Sea area to the Red Sea
port city of Aqaba, semi-official Jordan Times reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The concession winner will be able to operate the Aqaba
Railway Corporation (ARC) independently to expand its current
railway system at the cost of 100 million U.S. dollars, the paper
quoted Minister of Transportation Sami Gammoh as saying.
</P>
<P>
The project is the first privatization initiative in Jordan's
transportation sector and meant to meet the increased demand for
Jordan's phosphate in European and Asian markets, the paper
said.
</P>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY -- A market study showed Tuesday that Saudi
Arabia's computer market is growing by 30 percent to 35 percent
annually and trend is toward faster, smaller and compact version.
</P>
<P>
Saudi Press Agency quoted the study released in a computing and
education exhibition in Saudi Red Sea coast city of Jeddah as
saying that presently, companies and organizations are installing
or developing their own networks.
</P>
<P>
More than 200 companies from Saudi Arabia and abroad are
taking part in the exhibition.
</P>
<P>
Tehran -- Iran's Deputy Oil Minister Ali Hashemi announced on
Tuesday that the country had found a new gas field with 2.1
trillion cubic feet of gas and 10.5 million barrels of liquid gas
in the southern province of Fars.
</P>
<P>
The gas reserves of the field is worth over three billion
U.S. dollars and will be developed in the next two years.
</P>
</TEXT>
