<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Continues to Open Financial Market (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 22 (Xinhua) -- Three insurance groups from
Britain, Australia and Canada were recently allowed to set up
branches in China, and the French Banque Nationale de Paris also
was awarded a business licence in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
The latest moves indicate that China is continuing its policy
of opening its financial market to foreign companies while
implementing fundamental reforms within its financial system.
</P>
<P>
China initiated its financial opening-up policy 19 years
ago. Foreign financial institutions have been gradually developing
and becoming a significant component in China's financial system,
playing an increasingly bigger role in China's economic
construction.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman for the People's Bank of China (PBOC) said that, so
far, foreign financial institutions have set up 544 offices and
173 branches in China in both banking and insurance.
</P>
<P>
The branches are from 20 countries and regions including Japan,
Hong Kong, the United States, France and Britain, and most of the
branches are distributed in China's financial centers such as
Shanghai, Shenzhen, Beijing, Guangzhou and Tianjin.
</P>
<P>
So far China has allowed foreign banks to establish business
institutions in 23 cities and Hainan Province.
</P>
<P>
The past few years have been the best for foreign financial
institutions to develop in China. Three years ago Beijing had no
branches of foreign financial institutions, and now 14 foreign
banks are offering financial services and more than 220 foreign
financial institutions have established offices in the capital.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980422.0197 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-22 09:56 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mubarak Hold Talks With Arafat </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, April 22 (Xinhua) -- Visiting Palestinian National
Authority (PNA) President Yasser Arafat Wednesday held talks with
Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak on the recent efforts for
reactivating the Middle East peace process.
</P>
<P>
Arafat, who flew in Tuesday night from the Saudi Arabia,
briefed Mubarak on the results of his talks with British Prime
Minister Tony Blair in Gaza on Monday, during which they explored
ways to push forward the stalled peace process.
</P>
<P>
After the tete-a-tete talks, a plenary session was held to
include Egyptian Prime Minister Kamal el-Ganzouri, Foreign
Minister Amr Moussa, the Palestinian Liberation Organization
Executive Committee chief Abu Mazen, Palestinian Planning and
International Cooperation Minister Nabiel Shaath and the aides.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinians welcome Blair's proposal on hosting meetings
to bring together Arafat and Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin
Netanyahu to salvage the peace process. Arafat, however,
conditioned a summit on the participation of Europeans and
Americans.
</P>
<P>
In an interview Wednesday morning with the Cairo-based Voice of
Arabs Radio, Palestinian ambassador to Britain Afif Safieh said
the Palestinian side has also asked for the participation of both
Egypt and Jordan in London talks.
</P>
<P>
Safieh, who had been present at Blair-Arafat talks, pointed out
that the London talks will provide the last chance to salvage the
peace-making in the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
He highlighted the importance of the role of Britain and the
European Union in general in pushing forward the peace march as
complement to the American brokerage.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu, at the invitation of Mubarak, is due in Cairo next
Tuesday for talks on unblock the peace impasse.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu has agreed to attend the London meetings to be held
on May 4. U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright will meet
there with Arafat and Netanyahu separately before the two can meet
with each other in search of a breakthrough.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. suggested that Israel withdraws from 13.1 percent of
the West Bank in tandem with Palestinian security guarantees. But
the scope has been rejected as too much by Israel, which insisted
on no more than 9 percent and might eventually settle for 11
percent.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian-Israeli talks were stalled since March 1997
over Jewish settlement expansion in East Arab Jerusalem and an
overdue Israeli troop pullback from the West Bank. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980422.0198 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Continues to Open Financial Market (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Except the nine foreign banks which have been ratified to do
Renminbi business in Pudong area of Shanghai, the business scope
of foreign banks is confined to foreign-exchange deposits and
loans, note discounts, remittances, warranties, import and export
settlements and ratified foreign exchange investment, and their
customers are limited to foreigners, foreign-funded enterprises
and foreign exchange credit of state-owned enterprises.
</P>
<P>
Despite these restrictions, foreign banks still achieved rapid
business development with considerable profits, demonstrating a
good business environment for foreign financial institutions.
</P>
<P>
Statistics from the PBOC show that, by the end of 1997, the
total assets of foreign banks in China was 37.99 billion U.S.
dollars, with the total outstanding amount of loans and deposits
at 27.5 billion U.S. dollars and 4.48 billion U.S. dollars,
respectively. All these figures reflected significant increases
over the previous year.
</P>
<P>
Experts said foreign financial institutions have been playing
an important role in China's economic development. Last year
foreign banks granted loans of 27.5 billion U.S. dollars, of which
88.2 percent was granted to businesses within China, while their
outstanding amount of deposits from China was only 3.68 billion
U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Foreign financial institutions have brought advanced operating
technologies, fund-raising tools and management methods to China
and provided training for China's international financial
personnel. In addition, they also helped promote competition
within China's financial system.
</P>
<P>
Experts generally held that, with the progress in China's
economic and financial reforms, foreign financial institutions
will gradually be given the same treatment as their Chinese
counterparts, and that the green light will be given to more
foreign financial institutions in coming years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980422.0199 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Acts to Control Dust Pollution in Mines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 22 (Xinhua) -- China will introduce new
technologies and facilities in addition to its legal and education
measures to control dust pollution in mines.
</P>
<P>
Statistics of the Ministry of Health shows that the number of
Chinese patients with pneumoconiosis, a common disease in mines
caused by inhaling too much dust, totaled 526,000 by the end of
1996. Of these, 119,000 died of the disease, the highest figure in
the world. And, in three years, the disease brought China an
annual economic loss of more than 11 billion yuan (1.3 billion
U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
Experts have been organized to improve the production
technology and develop new materials and machines that produce
less dust, said Lin Yongsan, vice-minister of Labor and Social
Security.
</P>
<P>
He said related departments are improving education to
employees in mines, providing them with basic industrial hygienic
knowledge and enhancing their knowledge for self-protection. The
ministry will soon release a documentary about controlling dust
pollution.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese government has issued a number of laws and
regulations about industrial hygiene and safety in recent years to
protect mine workers' safety and health, added Lin.
</P>
<P>
Mining is one of China's basic industries. About 95 percent of
China's 2,000 counties have mining activities. At present, China
has about 260,000 mine employing nearly 20 million people.
</P>
<P>
According to China's laws and regulations, mining companies
should regularly provide health examinations to workers, and those
with pneumoconiosis can get economic compensation.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
