<HEADLINE> US, Britain Frown on Abacha's Candidacy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, April 22 (Xinhua) -- The United States and Britain
Tuesday frowned on the adoption of General Sani Abacha as their
consensus presidential candidate by Nigeria's five political
parties.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. State Department spokesman James Rubin, who spoke in
Washington, urged the head of the Nigerian military government to
reject his nomination by the parties, saying that it is crucial
to the restoration of a stable democratic policy in Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. condemned what it described as the "manipulation" of
the government's transition to civil rule program.
</P>
<P>
Rubin Said: "It appears that the government of Nigeria is
manipulating the transition in order to secure the nomination of
General Sani Abacha, who is now in control of the country, as the
sole candidate in the presidential election planned for August
1."
</P>
<P>
"So far, Nigeria's transition is seriously flawed and failing.
What we've seen so far is the manipulation of the democratic
process by General Abacha and his cronies."
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said the U.S. is urging Abacha "to live up to
his promise to his fellow Nigerians and the entire world and to
refuse the nomination so that a genuine transition to civilian
democratic rule may take place."
</P>
<P>
Britain, which had earlier condemned Abacha's adoption as a
sole candidate, went further Tuesday to threaten to initiate
further sanctions against Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
The British Foreign Secretary, Robin Cook, was quoted by the
British Broadcasting Corporation (BBC) as giving the hint at
Britain's first annual report on human rights around the world.
</P>
</TEXT>
