<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Agreement on Status of New Caledonia Reached </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, April 22 (Xinhua) -- The pro-French and pro-independence
parties of the South Pacific islands of New Caledonia reached an
agreement on the future of the territory on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement, the indigenous Kanak people of New
Caledonia could realize their dream for independence within 20
years through a referendum on independence to be held between 2013
and 2018, after one and a half centuries of colonial rule by
France.
</P>
<P>
The agreement was signed in Noumea, capital of New Caledonia,
by French government representative Alain Christnacht, pro-French
RPCR party president Jacques Lafleur, and pro-independence FNLKS
party president Roch Wamytan.
</P>
<P>
The 18-page agreement was reached under the personal
intervention of Prime Minister Lionel Jospin.
</P>
<P>
State Secretary for Overseas Affairs Jean-Jack Queyranne said
New Caledonia will enter an "evolutionary process" toward
independence and cease to be an overseas territory of France by
the end of this year.
</P>
<P>
The French government will transfer "in an irreversible way"
the most important powers to the local government which is
established around the local parliament, said the agreement.
</P>
<P>
The governor, appointed by Paris, will be replaced by a
collegiate government to be elected by the parliament.
</P>
<P>
At the referendum, local people will decide whether the
territory will change its status of justice, public order, defense
and money, and therefore fully cut its links with France.
</P>
<P>
Prior to the referendum, the French government will also
"remould the lasting social links "between the French community
and indigenous Kanak community, in order to allow the Kanak people
to establish with France the new relations corresponding to the
realities of our times."
</P>
<P>
The customary rights of the Kanak tribal leaders will be
reinforced and the use of Kanak language will be increased in
schools and media.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Jospin will go to Noumea to inaugurate a Kanak
cultural center named after Jean-Marie Tjibaou, a Kanak leader
assassinated in 1988 by a Kanak extremist for signing a ceasefire
agreement with the French government. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
