<HEADLINE> Turkey-Iran Ties Still Marred by Concerns </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, April 22 (Xinhua) -- Turkey is still concerned about
Iran's alleged support for the outlawed Kurdish Workers' Party
(PKK) despite their warmer relations, the Daily News reported on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"We still maintain our reservations towards Tehran because of
the PKK. We have not yet been persuaded (that Iran does not
support the PKK)," a senior Foreign Ministry official, who
declined to be named, was quoted by the paper as saying.
</P>
<P>
Turkey regards Iran as a key neighbor and has a good will to
improve bilateral relations, he said. But he stressed that
previous mistakes should not be repeated.
</P>
<P>
Ankara has repeatedly accused Tehran of providing military and
financial support to the PKK, which has been fighting a separatist
war in southeastern Turkey since 1984.
</P>
<P>
Iran, however, has categorically rejected the accusation,
saying that it has never aided or sheltered PKK militants.
</P>
<P>
"The PKK issue will be brought to the table during the
security committee talks (between the two countries)," the
official said.
</P>
<P>
Local reports have said that Turkey and Iran will hold a series
of talks on security and economic issues in the coming weeks.
</P>
</TEXT>
