<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Western Management Adapts to Chinese Traditions (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, April 22 (Xinhua) -- When the Chinese public gets
incensed about reports of overseas-funded businesses exploiting or
abusing Chinese workers' most basic rights, the experience of
3-year-old Xie Congwen comes as a nice change.
</P>
<P>
The toddler's life was saved less than six months ago by help
from Alcoa (Shanghai) Aluminum Products Co. Ltd., a Sino-American
joint venture which employs the boy's parents.
</P>
<P>
With money donated by co-workers, a suitable hospital was found
in Melbourne, Australia, by Graeme Turnley, the former Alcoa
general manager, and his wife. The Xie family was able to stay in
Melbourne from July through October until Congwen had recovered
from a series of operations necessitated by a life-threatening
congenital disease.
</P>
<P>
As a result, Alcoa (Shanghai) was commended recently for good
labor-capital relations along with 10 other Sino-overseas
companies in Shanghai's Minhang Economic and Technological
Development Zone.
</P>
<P>
"Those cited represent an increasing number of foreign-funded
enterprises that have started to absorb in their management style
a Chinese tradition that the business is looked upon as a family
which takes care of everybody working in it," explained Lu
Youming, general manager of the Shanghai Minhang United
Development Co. Ltd., which manages and services the zone on
behalf of the local government.
</P>
<P>
He added that examples of good labor-capital relations also
indicate that what Chinese employees hope to get from the
businesses are not only good wages, but also a corporate culture
which encourages the members to help each other.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980422.0211 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Western Management Adapts to Chinese Tradition (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Concurring with Lu's opinion, Alcoa's financial director Peggy
L. Phillips said the most important factor for an enterprise is
the people working there. Alcoa will help anybody in difficulties,
Chinese or foreign, she said.
</P>
<P>
"Good labor-capital relations also help boost efficiency,"
Phillips said.
</P>
<P>
Among those cited, Lu said, are businesses who paid huge bills
for cancer treatment or kidney transplants for employees, or
raised funds to send children of poor families back to school.
</P>
<P>
To promote understanding between management and workers, she
added, some businesses take regular satisfaction surveys of
employees or convene audiences between the two. "Workers'
viewpoints have been adopted to improve management or their
working and living conditions," Phillips said.
</P>
<P>
Relations between management and workers have become a major
concern with the Chinese public in the past year because of highly
publicized incidents in which some overseas-funded firms ignored
or encroached on the rights of their Chinese employees. There were
cases in which employees were forced to work extra hours without
proper pay, and those in which the workers were even insulted and
persecuted for failing to follow unreasonable demands from their
overseas employers.
</P>
<P>
Trade unions and government departments across the country have
made efforts to protect workers' rights. According to Shanghai's
municipal committee for overseas investment, the majority of
overseas-funded businesses in the city have signed labor contracts
with employees which establish clear stipulations on working
hours, wages, pay, labor security, hygiene, medical insurance and
pension plans.
</P>
<P>
By the end of 1997, about 10,000 overseas-funded enterprises
had been set up in Shanghai, employing nearly 950,000 people,
accounting for 17.7 percent of the city's total labor force.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980422.0212 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: Measures Taken To Ensure Economic Growth (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 22 (Xinhua) -- A fairly obvious change was
recorded in China's macro-economic policy since the beginning of
this year.
</P>
<P>
The government has placed its emphasis on boosting a rapid,
sustained economic growth by increasing investment and stimulating
consumption. A new upsurge of investment has started in all parts
of China.
</P>
<P>
A number of Chinese economists have proposed on many occasions
that the state should increase investment to make the country's
economy grow steadily. Some held the view that the buyer's market
benefits economic restructuring.
</P>
<P>
The speed of growth has long been the crux of the matter in
China's economic development. The country's economic growth rate
had a slight reduction in the past few years, with a growth of 8.8
percent in 1997 and an expected 8 percent growth rate this year.
</P>
<P>
An official with the State Development Planning Commission said
that only if the annual growth rate stands around 8 percent in
forthcoming years can it promote economic restructuring and
enterprise reforms as well as provide more job opportunities.
</P>
<P>
China's economy is in the process from a planned one to a
market one. The supply of a great number of consumer goods has met
or exceeded the market demand in urban districts, hindering
full-scale production at industrial firms. And the development of
rural markets will take a long time.
</P>
<P>
Under such circumstances, the central government has decided to
increase investment in the fields of agriculture, water
conservation, infrastructures, new-technology and high-tech
businesses, technological upgrading of enterprises, public
utilities and residential housing.
</P>
<P>
China's investment for development in the next three years is
estimated at eight trillion yuan, which will be raised in the form
of government investment, foreign funds and bonds. Investment in
fixed assets for this year is expected to increase by 400 billion
yuan, compared with the figure for last year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980422.0213 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-22 </DATE_TIME>
