<DOCNO> XIE19980422.0215 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Commentary: China Sets to Foster Institutional </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
By launching three securities investment funds in a row in less
than a month, China has showed its strong determination to nurture
institutional investors in the securities market, and facilitate
its stable and healthy development, economists here have agreed.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese securities market has already undergone rapid
expansion in recent years, with the share of the market capital in
the national GDP soaring from less than eight percent in 1995 to
23 percent last year. At the end of March, the number of listed
companies on the stock market surged to 763, while the market
capital hit 1.878 trillion yuan.
</P>
<P>
However, the market is still not spared of over-speculation and
irrational investment as a result of the still flawed legal
framework and lack of adequate supervision.
</P>
<P>
With the deepening of the state enterprise reform and the
introduction of a socialist market economic system,
direct financing, or raising funds on the capital market, is bound
to play a more important role, which in turn will give rise to the
necessity of a stable and healthy securities market.
</P>
<P>
To this end, China unveiled the regulations governing the
management of securities investment funds, and launched the first
two such funds early this month.
</P>
<P>
Through purchasing investment funds, the investors entrust
their personal savings to the professional fund managers, who will
then invest in bonds and stocks in the principles of "safety,
liquidity, and profitability".
</P>
<P>
Since risks in investment funds are much lower than the stocks,
securities investment funds are expected to attract more private
savings into the securities market, thereby facilitating the
reform in state-owned ventures.
</P>
<P>
The investment funds are also conducive to fostering rational
and reliable institutional investors on the securities market, and
making the market more rational and stable by reducing the
predominant proportion of individual investors for the present,
economists agreed.
</P>
<P>
The macro-economic backdrop also provided a solid foundation
for the investment funds and the securities market: the Chinese
economy soft-landed and finally embarked on the path of "high
growth and low inflation"; the savings of the Chinese people kept
rising steadily, with the total outstanding individual bank
savings surpassing 4.8 trillion yuan at the end of March.
</P>
<P>
Actually, the first two funds have already received warm
greetings on the market. Both were nearly 40 times oversubscribed
upon issuing and their prices have surged to and remained at a
high level since being listed on the stock exchanges. The
optimistic market sentiment triggered by the listing of the two
funds also brought the stock indices and turnover to a ten-month
high.
</P>
<P>
Due to the favorable market performance of the two experimental
funds, China is expected to launch the rest two funds after the
debut of Fund Xinghua very soon, according to Zhou Zhengqing,
chairman of the China Securities Regulatory Commission, who also
revealed that more such funds may be on the way if all the five
funds are successful.
</P>
<P>
Based on the fact that the Chinese authorities is already set
on giving a full play to the securities investment funds and
fostering institutional investors, the nation's securities market
is blessed with a promising future, agreed economists.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980422.0216 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australia Unveils Five-Year Plan for Auto Industry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, April 22 (Xinhua) -- The Australian federal
government Wednesday unveiled a 1.3-billion-U.S.-dollar plan aimed
at encouraging car manufacturing firms to make long-term
commitments to the nation's automotive industry.
</P>
<P>
Under the plan, or the Automotive Competitiveness and
Investment Scheme (ACIS), the duty-free allowance for imported
components to be used in cars assembled in Australia would be
expanded, and incentives would be introduced for increased
investment spending.
</P>
<P>
"The scheme will be consistent with World Trade Organization
(WTO) rules and will ensure a stable transition towards a secure
global position for Australia's car industry," Fischer said in a
statement.
</P>
<P>
The scheme launched by Australian Trade Minister Tim Fischer
and Industry Minister John Moore will not come into force until
the next stage of winding back protection when tariffs are cut
from 20 percent to 15 percent on January 1, 2001.
</P>
<P>
The plan seeks to ease the transition to an even lower industry
protection regime when tariffs on passenger motor vehicles are
further cut to 10 percent from January 1, 2005.
</P>
<P>
Several global car producers, including Toyota, General Motor
and Ford, have set up plants in Australia, with Ford Australia's
annual vehicle output totaling about 100,000 units.
</P>
<P>
Australia's Federation of Automotive Products Manufacturers
Director Malcolm Stewart described the government's plan as a
significant step in securing investment, growth, jobs and exports
for Australia's component industry. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
