<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesian Government Abolishes its Supervision Over </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, April 22 (Xinhua) -- The Indonesian government decided
on Wednesday to abolish its supervision over nine troubled tanks
as their financial conditions have been improved.
</P>
<P>
At a press conference held here jointly by several cabinet
ministers after attending the second meeting of Economic and
Financial Resilience Council headed by President Soeharto, Finance
Minister Fuad Bawazir said out of the nine banks which have broken
away from the direct supervision of the Indonesian Bank
restructuring Agency (IBRA), four are state-owned banks, one
construction bank under local administration and four private
banks.
</P>
<P>
As part of the national banking reforms to restore its
reputation and regain the confidence of people at home and abroad,
54 banks have been placed under the INRA's supervision since the
beginning of this year.
</P>
<P>
On April 4, the government stopped the operation of seven
private banks and placed another seven banks under the management
of IBRA. The 14 banks are described as the "grave troubled banks"
from the 54 troubled banks.
</P>
<P>
The operations of the seven banks were frozen because they had
been using liquidity funds of Bank Indonesia (BI), central bank,
in excess of 500 percent of their paid-up capital and equal to or
in excess of 75 percent of their total assets.
</P>
<P>
The other seven banks placed under IBRA control had been using
BI liquidity funds totaling more than 2 trillion rupiah (about 240
million U.S. dollars) and also in excess of 500 percent of their
total equity.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia has 240 banks and about 200 of them are private ones.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia started its banking reforms in October last year
after signing an agreement with the International Monetary Fund
(IMF) on economic and financial reforms in exchange for the
IMF-led bailout package of 43 billion U.S. dollar to overcome
monetary crisis in the country.
</P>
<P>
At the end of October last year, the Indonesian government
closed down 16 unsolved private banks in a bid to improve the
efficiency of the banking system.
</P>
<P>
Fuad said the government encourages small and troubled banks to
make their own efforts to merge among them, to supplement funds or
introduce new investment in order to strengthen their competition.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
