<HEADLINE> Six Asian Countries Sign MOU for Cooperation in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
 Space Technology Development
</P>
<P>
BANGKOK, April 22 (Xinhua) -- Six Asian countries Wednesday
signed at the Thai government house an inter-governmental
Memorandum of Understanding (MOU) to promote multilateral
cooperation in space technology development and applications.
</P>
<P>
Senior government officials from China, Iran, Pakistan,
Mongolia, South Korea and Thailand signed "the Memorandum of
Understanding for Cooperation in the Small Multi-Mission Satellite
(SMMS) Project and Related Activities".
</P>
<P>
Thai Prime Minister Chuan Leekpai, together with Transport and
Communication Minister Suthep Thausuban, presided over the
official signing ceremony.
</P>
<P>
The SMMS project is one of the important elements of the
Asia-Pacific Multilateral Cooperation in Space Technology and
Applications (AP-MCSTA) Initiative.
</P>
<P>
The initial formal proposal of the SMMS project was offered
during the first AP-MCSTA conference in Bangkok in 1994.
</P>
<P>
Under the MOU, the participating countries, by signing the
MOU, agreed that they will take some joint actions to support the
implementation of the SMMS project, conduct joint research and
applications, and initiate training program in the related areas.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, the participating countries agreed to
establish a project committee, with its members being the
government officials and technical experts, to conduct the
feasibility study and turn up suggestions and recommendations in
the related technological, scientific managerial and financial
aspects.
</P>
<P>
According to the MOU, participating member countries of this
MOU is willing to work together with all the nations in the
Asia-Pacific region to bring about space technology and
applications to the developing countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
