<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Personal Computers: Revenue Grows Slower Than Sales </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, April 21 (Xinhua) -- Worldwide personal computer
sales are expected to increase 15.6 percent, while revenue will
grow only 6.4 percent this year, Dataquest, a leading market
research firm in California, said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
According to Dataquest, worldwide PC shipments will total 93.1
million units in 1998 and revenue will reach 166 billion
U.S. dollars for computer sellers.
</P>
<P>
Both figures are lower than the firm's previous projections
which estimated a sales growth of 17 percent and a revenue growth
of 16 percent in 1998.
</P>
<P>
The main reason, Dataquest said, is the fact that the
proliferation of personal computers which are priced lower than
1,000 dollars is boosting sales while curbing overall revenue
growth for PC makers.
</P>
<P>
The firm also forecast a slightly higher growth rate for home
PC market than the business sector as more families buy their
first or extra PCs.
</P>
<P>
The United States, Europe and Asia would remain top-selling
regions in the world PC market this year, Dataquest said.
</P>
<P>
Sales increase in the United States, Europe and Asia will be 16
percent, 14 percent and 23 percent respectively, while revenue
growth for them will be three percent, nine percent and 17
percent, in 1998. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980422.0231 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkey, Israel to Hold Military Talks in May </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, April 22 (Xinhua) -- Turkey and Israel are expected to
hold military talks in Tel Aviv, capital of Israel, at the end of
May in a bid to further develop the military ties between the two
countries.
</P>
<P>
The Daily News reported Wednesday that Deputy Chief of Turkish
General Staff Cevik Bir and Israeli Defense Under-secretary David
Ivry will meet to discuss the "threats" to the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted a military source, who asked not to be named,
as saying that "The rising missile threat in the Middle East, as
well as support for terrorism, from which both Turkey and Israel
have been suffering, will be discussed and evaluated during the
talks."
</P>
<P>
Iran, Iraq and Syria are among the countries which will be
reportedly discussed for their alleged support for terrorism and
their efforts to increase their offensive missile technologies,
said the source.
</P>
<P>
The paper also reported that Turkish and Israeli high-ranking
military officials will discuss another joint military
maneuver. But there is no detail about where and when.
</P>
<P>
Turkey, Israel and the United States held a joint naval
maneuver in the Mediterranean off Israel last January, which drew
harsh reactions from the Arab world.
</P>
<P>
At the beginning of April, a group of 30 Israeli defense
officials visited Turkey seeking more opportunities to boost their
current defense industry capacities through cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Israel is upgrading 54 Turkish F-4 warplanes under a contract
worth 632 million U.S. dollars and has also won a bid to upgrade
48 Turkish F-5 fighters.
</P>
<P>
Ankara and Tel Aviv have agreed in principle to jointly
produce hundreds of Popeye II, which, as an advanced model of
Popeye I, has a range of 150 kilometers.
</P>
<P>
Popeye series missiles are being used in both F-16 and F-4
warplanes. Turkey purchased 200 Popeye I missiles from Israel and
deliveries began at the end of last year.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Military Industries is modernizing Turkey's aging M-60
tanks as part of Turkey's 4.5-billion-dollar project. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980422.0232 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ECOWAS Director Calls for Unity </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, April 22 (Xinhua) -- A director of the Economic
Community of West African States (ECOWAS) has criticized the
trend of disunity in the sub-regional body resulting in the
setting up of other organizations by some member states.
</P>
<P>
"There must be only one regional community for success to be
achieved, if not it will amount to dissipation of efforts," said
Frank Ofei, ECOWAS Director of Statistics, quoted by New Nigerian
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The director was referring to the establishment of the
Monetary Union of West Africa (Umoa) in 1994, an umbrella body
for French-speaking ECOWAS member countries, said the official
daily.
</P>
<P>
A bigger body with a larger regional market was more likely to
grow better than smaller ones, the director added.
</P>
<P>
Certain ECOWAS programs have been stalled because of the
divided interests of some members which belong to both
organizations.
</P>
<P>
In the latest case, the last-minute withdrawal of Umoa
countries last December has stalled the production and launching
of the ECOWAS travelers' check, a major move taken by the
sub-regional body toward a single monetary zone in west Africa.
</P>
<P>
According to Ofei, French speaking countries within Umoa
cannot be viable unless they are linked to a bigger viable market
to give it a regional outlook.
</P>
<P>
"If you privatize or sell an enterprises to Umoa, it cannot
thrive unless it has a bigger market for its products," the
ECOWAS director said.
</P>
<P>
Another official in the ECOWAS money and payment department,
David Asate, was more straight forward.
</P>
<P>
He urged France not to stall the emergence of a single
currency in west Africa because it was supporting a common
currency within the European Union.
</P>
<P>
The issue of single currency within the ECOWAS sub-region
should be left to the political decisions of members which are
free to place their will where they feel they have more interest,
Asate told journalists last weekend in Abuja, the Nigerian
capital.
</P>
<P>
ECOWAS, set up in 1975 as a sub-regional economic bloc, has 16
members, including 11 French-speaking countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980422.0233 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China, Portugal to Strengthen Education Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 22 (Xinhua) -- Chinese and Portuguese ministers
today pledge to strengthen bilateral education exchanges and
cooperation in line with the smooth development of relations
between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
The pledge came from Chinese Minister of Education Chen Zhili
and her Portuguese counterpart Marcal Grilo, who is visiting China
along with Prime Minister Antonio Guterres.
</P>
<P>
Educational exchanges and cooperation constitute an important
part of bilateral relation and will in turn help promote
country-to-country relations, said Chen.
</P>
<P>
She noted that China is willing to cooperate with Portugal and
all other European Union countries in related efforts.
</P>
<P>
Grilo voiced agreement with Chen's view and said the Portuguese
side highly values cooperation with China in all fields,
particularly in the realm of education, science and technology,
economic ties and trade.
</P>
<P>
The two ministers also exchanged views on enhancing links
between universities, as well as professional and technical
training, and the prospects for education in Macao following its
return to China in December next year. Discussions also centered
on a number of related issues, including Chinese language and
Chinese culture instruction in Portuguese universities.
</P>
<P>
Sino-Portuguese exchanges and cooperation in the realm of
education have developed smoothly since the two countries signed
an agreement on cultural, scientific and technological cooperation
in 1982. More than 100 Chinese students are currently studying in
Portugal, and eight Chinese universities, including Beijing
University and Qinghua University, have established direct links
with Portuguese counterparts.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
