<HEADLINE> Zambia Puts Fund into Local Elections </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, April 22 (Xinhua) -- The Zambian government has
allocated 15.9 billion Kwacha (about 8.8 million U.S. Dollars)
for the local government elections expected to be held in June
this year.
</P>
<P>
Of the allocated money, nearly 500 million Kwacha has already
been released to the national registration office to facilitate a
speedy issuance of registration cards, the Zambia Daily Mail
reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted Election Commission Chairman Bobby Bwalya as
saying here Tuesday that the money was disbursed two weeks ago to
help the office put in place an effective mechanism of processing
cards to enable eligible voters to register for the polls.
</P>
<P>
Although the budgetary allocation may not adequately cater for
all the preparatory ground work, but Bwalya said he is optimistic
that at least a few logistics will be put in place.
</P>
<P>
So far, he said, preparations for the elections are underway
although they have not reached an advanced stage because a report
on the delimitation of wards exercise has not yet been submitted
to the relevant authorities.
</P>
<P>
The commission has been holding several meetings with some
opposition parties and the donor community on the elections, and
he is impressed with the response from them, said Bwalya.
</P>
<P>
There is no need to worry over the delay in holding the
elections, he said, adding that the local elections will
definitely take place this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
