<HEADLINE> Mubarak Invites Netanyahu for Cairo Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, April 22 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian President Hosni
Mubarak has invited Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu to
Cairo next Tuesday to discuss the Middle East peace process,
Israel Radio reported on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The report quoted a statement, issued by the Prime Minister's
Office Tuesday night, as saying that Mubarak and Netanyahu will
have a working breakfast together in the Egyptian capital.
</P>
<P>
The statement said Mubarak extended the invitation during a
phone conversation with Netanyahu about a week ago, but the
summit was settled on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The meeting will be the first between the two leaders in a full
year. Mubarak has repeatedly charged that Netanyahu is not
committed to advancing the peace process.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, the summit comes just days before Netanyahu and
Palestinian National Authority President Yasser Arafat are
scheduled to hold separate meetings with the U.S. Secretary of
State Madeline Albright in London on May 4th.
</P>
<P>
Israeli officials said that they believe Egypt would like to
enhance its role in the Israeli-Palestinian peace process.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak is expected to echo an appeal from Jordan's King
Hussein, who has urged Netanyahu to accept the U.S. initiative
for a 13 percent further Israeli withdrawal from the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu has stayed firm on 9 percent, although there have
been reports this week that he may soften the stance and settle at
11 percent after his meeting with visiting British Prime Minister
Tony Blair early this week.
</P>
<P>
The scope of Israeli troop redeployment in the West Bank has
remained a hurdle to unblocking the stalled peace process.
</P>
</TEXT>
