<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-22 07:54 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Istanbul Mayor Sentenced to 10 Months for </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, April 22 (Xinhua) -- Istanbul Mayor Tayyip Erdogan has
been sentenced to 10 months in prison and a fine of about 320
U.S. dollars for an anti-secular speech.
</P>
<P>
Turkey's State Security Court in Diyarbakir made the verdict
because Erdogan made made the pro-Islamic speech last December in
the southeastern province of Siirt, in violation of the
constitution, local Daily News reported here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The court convicted Erdogan, also member of the newly-founded
pro-Islamic Virtue party, of "inciting hatred" in an address to
Islamist supporters, in which he reportedly said that "Minarets
will be our bayonets and domes, our shields".
</P>
<P>
Erdogan was elected mayor of Istanbul, the largest city of
Turkey, in 1994. He did not appear at the hearing on Tuesday and
is not expected to be sent to jail immediately.
</P>
<P>
The case must now go through the Court of Appeals which may
approve the decision of the State Security Court in Diyarbakir. If
the Court of Appeals upholds that decision, Erdogan will be sent
to jail and removed from office, losing the chance to run for
election.
</P>
<P>
Erdogan is particularly believed to be preparing to replace
Islamist leader Necmettin Erbakan, whose Welfare Party (RP) was
banned on January 16, 1998.
</P>
<P>
Daily News said that the Interior Ministry can also appeal
to the higher court to remove Erdogan from office.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Turkish police has detained at least 16 leading
Islamist businessmen for questioning on suspected links to Islamic
groups this week. "They were taken from their houses at
four in the morning by anti-terrorist police squads and brought
to Ankara for questioning", Erol Yarar, head of an Islamist
business group, was quoted by the paper. 
</P>
</TEXT>
