<HEADLINE> Jiangsu Private Firms Participate in State Enterprise Reform </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANJING, April 22 (Xinhua) -- Private enterprises in east
China's Jiangsu Province have been active in participating in the
effort to reform state-owned and collective enterprises and
restructure the provincial economy.
</P>
<P>
Incomplete statistics show that 5,679 private enterprises have
been involved in the restructuring effort in terms of
acquisitions, mergers, leases and holding stakes.
</P>
<P>
Jiangsu, one of China's economic powerhouses, has more than
70,000 private enterprises, which employ more than 800,000 workers.
</P>
<P>
Official figures also indicate that Jiangsu's private
enterprises, including 28 private enterprise groups, have a
combined registered capital of 33 billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
To optimize the distribution of resources, Jiangsu has
encouraged private enterprises to merge with, take over and lease
small, financially weak or indebted state-owned and collective
enterprises.
</P>
<P>
In Yixing City, for example, 300 previously state-owned and
collective enterprises that have been restructured into private
firms have all reported increased worker salaries and growing
taxes to local coffers.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
