<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NZ Introduces Work for Dole Program </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, April 22 (Xinhua) -- The long-term unemployed
people will receive a community wage from October 1 instead of
unemployment benefit as in the past, the government announced on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Employment Minister Peter McCardle said from October 1,
jobseekers will have to sign contracts which require them to do
community work or participate in training or another organized
activity. In return, they will receive a community wage which will
replace the present unemployment.
</P>
<P>
He said the long-term unemployed will have to work or train for
20 hours a week or face losing their benefit.
</P>
<P>
If they refuse, quit or turn up late, their community wage will
be cut or suspended until they comply.
</P>
<P>
McCardle said he expected that at least 60,000 jobless people
will participate in this work-for-the-dole scheme in the next
fiscal year, with 25,000 of them doing community work.
</P>
<P>
He told Radio New Zealand that the amount of community wage is
about the same as the unemployment benefit. But those doing
community work will receive an additional traveling allowance and
be able to claim some extra costs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
