<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Business Confidence in NZ Sinks to New Low </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, April 22 (Xinhua) -- Business confidence in New
Zealand sank to a seven-year low in the first quarter of this
year, Radio New Zealand reported on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The radio quoted the latest survey of the Economic Research
Institute as reporting that difficult trading conditions and a
weakening domestic economy are chiefly responsible for the falling
confidence.
</P>
<P>
A net of 36 percent of businesses expect the general business
situation to deteriorate during the next six months, up from 20
percent shown in the last survey conducted in the fourth quarter
in 1997, according to the survey.
</P>
<P>
It has found that all sectors had turned pessimistic about the
general economic situation.
</P>
<P>
But the institute believes that pessimism is being driven by
several factors, but mainly the continued slowdown in domestic
activity.
</P>
<P>
"Sales in New Zealand have fallen steadily across all sectors
and are expected to decline again over the next three months," the
institute pointed out.
</P>
<P>
Other factors it listed are the Asian economic crisis which has
now hit all the sectors, continued drought in some parts of the
country and the power crisis in New Zealand's largest city
Auckland. 
</P>
</TEXT>
