<HEADLINE> Bangladesh Stresses Public Awareness About </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, April, 22 (Xinhua) -- Bangladeshi Minister for
Environment and Forest Syeda Sajeda Chowdhury has called for
creating public awareness about the adverse effect of
desertification, the Bangladesh Observer daily reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The minister made this call while inaugurating the country's
first national awareness seminar on "Combating Desertification in
Bangladesh" held in Dhaka Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Bangladesh, which has a total area of 148,393 square
kilometers, is situated within the tropical humid region, she
said.
</P>
<P>
"But its 74,000 square kilometers covering northwestern and
southwestern regions are arid as it experiences minimum rainfall
annually," she said.
</P>
<P>
Such an area accounts for about 50 percent of the country's
total land area, and the desertification problem is more acute in
the northern region, she said.
</P>
<P>
She said that 75 percent of the land is in a state of
conversion into deserts, and about 6 million hectares of land were
being lost due to desertification every year.
</P>
<P>
She also expressed concern over the possible permanent
inundation of 17.5 percent of the total land area should there be
a rise in the sea level by one meter.
</P>
<P>
A national environment committee has been formed to formulate
national programs to fight desertification, she told the seminar.
</P>
</TEXT>
