<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Internet Users to Miss out on Sydney Olympics </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, April 22 (Xinhua) -- Moving images of the 2000 Sydney
Olympics will not be available on the Internet to protect the
rights of host broadcasters, the International Olympic Committee
(IOC) said on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
According to reports from Sydney, The Internet received 600
million hits at the Nagano Winter Games in February, up from less
than 200 million at the Atlanta Olympics in 1996.
</P>
<P>
"The problem is you can no longer control the territorial
issues so you are then breaching other broadcasters' rights," IOC
marketing director Michael Payne told reporters in Sydney.
</P>
<P>
"The moment you put it on it's worldwide so you can't then
control it from the territorial side and I think the general view
is that the technology will not be sufficiently advanced (by
2000) to even consider doing something on a territorial
restricted basis."
</P>
<P>
He admitted that the booming Internet market was a threat to
television revenue, which will account for almost one billion
dollars (670 million) at the Sydney Games with the likes of US
giant NBC and Australia's Channel Seven invloved.
</P>
<P>
The IOC successfully trialled a system called Video On Demand
(VOD) in Nagano, which allowed users to access broadcast footage
of sport and press conferences at the Games, plus archival
material.
</P>
<P>
Australia's senior IOC member Kevan Gosper, who also chairs the
IOC's Press Commission, said an agreement was imminent between
broadcasters and IOC technology partner IBM regarding Internet
rights. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
