<HEADLINE> Kenya to Fight Water Weed in L. Victoria </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, April 22 (Xinhua) -- The Kenyan government awaits the
green-light from the World Bank to award the tender for the
mechanical removal of the water hyacinth mass now choking Lake
Victoria, the Kenya Times reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
However, the winning bidder out of the 16 companies which
placed tenders will remain confidential until the
Washington-based financial institution approves the project, said
the report.
</P>
<P>
Kenyan Minister for Natural Resources Francis Lotodo and World
Bank country director Harold Wackman held talks on this Tuesday.
They said the contract for the project would be signed as soon as
the World Bank approves the recommendations.
</P>
<P>
Wackman said that the World Bank was not dictating any terms
or setting a time limit for the ministry.
</P>
<P>
Tenders for the harvesting of the water hyacinth in Lake
Victoria, the second-largest fresh lake in the world, started on
November 7 last year and bids opened on January 5 this year with
a total of 39 firms having purchased the bid document.
</P>
<P>
The World Bank decided late last year to offer Kenya 2.3
million U.S. Dollars to help the east African country remove
water hyacinth from the lake, which also chokes their part of the
lake in Uganda and Tanzania. 
</P>
</TEXT>
