<HEADLINE> Malaysia's Residential Property Sector Strong in 1997 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, April 22 (Xinhua) -- All the indices show that
Malaysia's residential property sector in 1997 was fundamentally
strong and was gradually consolidating from the strong price
increases of the last few years, the Valuation and Property
Services Department said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The sector did not slow down in the second half of the year as
many expected despite the economic slowdown but remained generally
stable although the percentage increases in the volume and value
of transactions were getting noticeably smaller, the department
said in its July-December 1997 report of the Malaysian Housing
Price Index.
</P>
<P>
The Malaysian House Price Index rose 1.9 percent in 1997 to
216.8 points, a reflection that residential property prices were
generally slightly higher in 1997 from 1996, due to the
proportionately greater number of higher-priced properties
transacted in the market in 1997, especially in the first half of
the year, the department said.
</P>
<P>
Total volume of transactions for 1997 was at 175,569 with a
value of 21.8 billion ringgit (5.8445 billion U.S. dollars at the
present exchange rate), compared with a volume of 170,007
transactions and a value of 18.8 billion ringgit (5.0402 billion
dollars) in 1996, it said.
</P>
<P>
This showed a 3.3-percent jump in the volume of transactions
and a 16.2 percent increase in the value transacted.
</P>
<P>
However, it said the trend in the last quarter of 1997 began to
reflect the uncertainty in the national economy experienced in the
second half of the year.
</P>
<P>
"Given that there is a time-lag factor of about six to nine
months, the actual market situation may be more sluggish," the
department said.
</P>
<P>
The department said the amount of financing available to the
property sector will determine the outlook of the residential
property market in 1998.
</P>
<P>
It predicted that the total volume and value of transactions
might fall for the first time in the first quarter of 1998, to
support the earlier contention that the effects of the national
economic slowdown, first apparent around July-August 1997, are
beginning to show in the residential property sector about six
months later. 
</P>
</TEXT>
