<HEADLINE> Roundup: Sri Lanka Anti-Rebel Move Sees Slow Advance </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, April 22 (Xinhua) -- May 13 last year saw the Sri
Lankan government forces launching Operation Jayasikuru (Certain
Victory) to clear a 75-kilometer corridor on the main highway
through Tamil rebel-held territory from Vavuniya to the Jaffna
peninsula.
</P>
<P>
Almost a year later, the government forces have been able to
only inch along the corridor amid stiff resistance, advancing just
32 kilometers to near Mankulam Town, a rebel stronghold.
</P>
<P>
On Monday, after a brief respite for the Sinhala and Tamil New
Year celebrations in the middle of this month, the forces
attempted to penetrate the rebel fortress, only to be met with
heavy mortar and artillery fire.
</P>
<P>
Military sources said Wednesday that in the first assault 28
soldiers died and about 200 were injured, many of them seriously.
The rebels reportedly suffered even heavier casualties with more
than 60 dead and 300 injured.
</P>
<P>
However, the army claimed that it had been able to overrun a
rebel camp northwest of Olumadu following a series of clashes with
strong groups of rebels.
</P>
<P>
After a temporary lull, further fierce fighting broke out again
in the area and an air force Mi-24 helicopter gunship backing the
ground troops was hit by the rebels but not seriously damaged.
</P>
<P>
Opening the highway to the government is of great significance
as it would give the government a ground route for sending
supplies to both the military and the civilians living in the
Jaffna peninsula which was recaptured by government troops in May
1996.
</P>
<P>
At present the government has to transport the supplies by air
and sea and this has proved to be extremely costly, particularly
with the rebels regularly attacking aircraft and ships in the
northern area.
</P>
<P>
For the rebels, it is also important to prevent the government
from controlling the main highway, whose opening would bisect the
rebel-held territory which stretches from coast to coast in the
middle of the island.
</P>
<P>
Since the fall of the Jaffna peninsula, the rebels have made
this area their headquarters and army infiltration would mean the
disintegration of their new stronghold.
</P>
<P>
The government, which deployed more than 20,000 troops for
Operation Jaya Sikuru, had hoped that the operation would
accomplish its objective within a few months after it started. But
the target date has been ever receding, casting doubt on whether
the objective could be attained at all.
</P>
<P>
The Tamil rebels fighting for a separate state have been
throwing everything they have into this battle which for them is
one of survival.
</P>
<P>
As pointed out by military analysts here, if the road falls,
the Tamil rebels will be weakened considerably and lose their hold
on the Tamil population.
</P>
<P>
And this is something that the rebels have been trying their
utmost to prevent from happening. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980422.0262 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Albright Urges Senate Approval of Biodiversity Convention </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 21 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright Tuesday called for early Senate approval of the
U.N. biodiversity convention as many species of plants and animals
face being wiped out by environmental changes.
</P>
<P>
At an event sponsored by the Museum of Natural History to mark
the International Earth Day, Albright said she would appoint a
special state department coordinator for affairs related to global
climate changes.
</P>
<P>
She said that the nation's biologists were convinced a mass
extinction of plants and animals is underway and poses a major
threat to humans in the next century, yet most Americans were
dimly aware of the problem.
</P>
<P>
She urged the Senate to approve the U.N.-initiated Convention
on Biological Diversity as soon as possible.
</P>
<P>
The convention, signed by most of the world's governments at
the Earth Summit in Rio de Janeiro in 1992, seeks to protect
aquatic and agricultural resources, make their uses sustainable
and share their benefits.
</P>
<P>
The secretary of state noted a serious loss of biodiversity in
her country, admitting: "We have less than one-twentieth of the
world's people, but we generate one-fifth of all greenhouse gas
emissions."
</P>
<P>
She said in recent years Americans have seen floods, droughts
and tornados that inflicted enormous human and financial costs
upon this country.
</P>
<P>
In Africa, Asia, and in Mexico, the effects of El Nino have had
a devastating impact on coastal populations. Globally, nine of the
last 11 years have been among the warmest in this century, she
added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980422.0263 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-22 </DATE_TIME>
