<DOCNO> XIE19980422.0264 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australia Plans for Antarctic Base Cleanup </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, April 22 (Xinhua) -- One of the world's most remote
ghost towns, the abandoned Wilkes Antarctic base, is to be cleaned
up after almost 30 years.
</P>
<P>
The Australian government will conduct a detailed survey on how
to remove the accumulated rubbish and other material left behind
in the move to the Casey station in 1969, official sources said
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Parliamentary Secretary (with responsibility for the
Antarctic), Ian MacDonald said in a statement that the cleanup
would be an enormous task and could take more than 20 years,
almost twice as long as the base was in use.
</P>
<P>
MacDonald said he had instructed the Antarctic division to
allocate 90,000 Australian dollars (60,000 U.S. dollars) for a
survey of the old Wilkes station next summer.
</P>
<P>
"The survey will provide information to enable me to finalize
an environmentally friendly and cost-effective plan for the
cleanup of Wilkes," he said.
</P>
<P>
"Subject to any environmental or heritage requirements, the
plan will result in the removal of rubbish and old buildings from
the site."
</P>
<P>
The Wilkes station was established by the United States in 1957
and transferred to Australian control two years later.
</P>
<P>
But the base was located in a valley and faced continual
problems with ice and snow accumulation.
</P>
<P>
It was abandoned when Australia opened the more suitably
located Casey station on nearby hills.
</P>
<P>
MacDonald said it is like a buried ghost town with
accommodation, dining, storage and working structures still in
place.
</P>
<P>
It also features extensive rubbish dumps, old fuel drums and
bladders and food stores.
</P>
<P>
Under the Environmental Protocol to the Antarctic Treaty which
came into force in January, signatory nations are required to
remove abandoned facilities and rubbish.
</P>
<P>
"Cleaning up Wilkes is a big task and may take more than 20
years to complete because many buildings are only exposed during
major thaws," MacDonald said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980422.0265 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-22 </DATE_TIME>
