<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> FAO Calls for Urgent Action to Promote Fisheries </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, April 22 (Xinhua) -- The on-going senior officials
meeting of the 24th Food and Agriculture Organization (FAO)
Regional Conference for Asia and the Pacific has called for urgent
action to promote fisheries and sustainable development of
aquaculture.
</P>
<P>
It was agreed at the three-day meeting, which opened here on
Monday, that greater attention should be paid to fisheries
management and international cooperation and coordination
strengthened in fisheries conservation and management in the
region, according to the FAO's regional office.
</P>
<P>
Participants also agreed that the FAO-based Asia-Pacific Fish
Commission (APFIC) is one of the best mechanisms for such
cooperation.
</P>
<P>
The meeting voiced support for the work of APFIC and asked FAO
to assume a leading role in cooperation and coordination among
various fishery organizations in the region so as to avoid
duplications.
</P>
<P>
Fishery is crucial for food security in the Asia and Pacific
region and contributes to economic and social well-being in all
developing countries in the region.
</P>
<P>
About 85 percent of fishers in the world live in Asia and the
Pacific and they contributed 52 percent of the world fishery
production in 1995.
</P>
<P>
Income from fishery exports from Asia increased to more than 19
million U.S. dollars in the same year.
</P>
<P>
It is estimated, however, that demand for food-fish for direct
human consumption in the region by 2010 would be 24 million tons
more than the current level of production.
</P>
<P>
The senior officials meeting is to be followed by a two-day
ministerial-level meeting on Thursday. The FAO regional conference
is being attended by about 150 representatives from 26 FAO member
countries in Asia and the Pacific, non-governmental organizations
and U.N. agencies. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
