<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cablecar Victims' Families Want Trial of Airmen in Italy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, April 21 (Xinhua) -- Relatives of the victims of a
cablecar disaster at an Italian ski resort said Tuesday that U.S.
military proceedings against the servicemen who caused the
disaster would not stop their campaign to seek justice in an
Italian civil court.
</P>
<P>
Twenty cablecar passengers were killed at Mt. Cermis on
February 3 after an Italy-based U.S. jet on a training flight cut
the cable and sent the car crashing into the slopes.
</P>
<P>
Eight of the victims were German, five Belgian, three Italian,
two Polish, one Dutch and one Austrian.
</P>
<P>
In Camp Lejeune, North Carolina, a U.S. military judge set two
hearings Monday to decide if the four U.S. Marine Corps officers
aboard the jet should be court-martialed.
</P>
<P>
In a statement issued here Tuesday, the "February 3 Committee"
said it expected the Italian government to appeal to NATO's
central council to bring the trial back to Italy.
</P>
<P>
It said there were strong legal arguments for waiving usual
practice in this case, and assigning jurisdiction to Italy.
</P>
<P>
The committee said it expected a "clear stance" in this
direction from a joint session of the Parliamentary Justice and
Foreign Affairs Committees, when they meet to discuss the tragedy
in a week.
</P>
<P>
Noting that U.S. military procedures do not include civil
plaintiffs, the Committee said this would make it harder to "get
to the bottom of the responsibilities that led to the deaths of
the 20 people".
</P>
<P>
The Committee said the U.S. hearings should focus on the whole
chain of command, the whole system of U.S. training flights in
northern Italy, and repeated local warnings about low-level
flights over inhabited areas -- warnings which were ignored.
</P>
<P>
It also pointed out that the U.S. proceedings were based on
military findings presented well before Italian prosecutors
concluded their own investigation.
</P>
<P>
The military findings "ignore various pieces of testimony and
contain several inaccuracies," the Committee said.
</P>
<P>
The crew on board the U.S. jet were Captains Richard Ashby, 30,
William Raney, 26, Joseph Schweitzer, 30, and Chandler Seagraves,
28.
</P>
<P>
U.S. Military Judge Ronald Rogers on Monday decided on a May 5
hearing for crewmen Seagraves and Raney and a June 15 hearing for
pilots Ashby and Schweitzer. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
