<TEXT>
<P>
SANTA FE DE BOGOTA, April 21 (Xinhua) -- A 300-member rescue
team resumed work Tuesday to recover the bodies of a Boeing 727
that crashed east of the Colombian capital, killing all 53 people
on board.
</P>
<P>
Heavy rain and the complicated topography of the crash site
slowed down the rescue operation.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman for Colombia's Civil Aviation said two black boxes
have been found, which are to be sent to Washington for analysis.
</P>
<P>
Some 40 officials from the district attorney office were called
to try to identify the corpses found, which will be difficult
because the majority of the bodies were mutilated.
</P>
<P>
The jetliner slammed into the mountains east of Bogota three
minutes after take-off from the city's El Dorado airport.
</P>
<P>
An official of the airport said the control tower had warned
the plane for its deviation off the course but copied no response.
</P>
<P>
The plane belonged to Ecuador's military-run TAME airline and
was leased by Air France.
</P>
<P>
Air France spokesman confirmed that 43 passengers and a
10-member crew were killed.
</P>
<P>
"That's official according to the tickets we have," said the
spokesman. The company initially put the toll at 61.
</P>
<P>
Colombian President Ernesto Samper sent a condolence message to
families of the victims.
</P>
<P>
The air crash was the worst in Colombia since December 20,
1995, when an American Airlines Boeing 757 flew into mountains
near the southwest city of Cali, killing all 159 people on board.
</P>
