<HEADLINE> Layoffs Soar in Vietnam As Financial Crisis Bites </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, April 22 (Xinhua) -- Unemployment in Vietnam has soared
to record highs as companies feeling the pinch from the Asian
financial crisis and domestic restructing are forced to lay off
thousands of workers, Vietnam Investment Review said in the latest
issue.
</P>
<P>
The English weekly newspaper quoted figures released by the
Ministry of Labor last week as saying that eight percent of
workers at state-owned companies and 11 percent of employees in
foreign-backed companies have been made redundant.
</P>
<P>
The ministry estimated that by the end of last year, around
170,000 people had been laid off, representing 10 percent of the
total workforce.
</P>
<P>
The numbers are even worse in other sectors. According the
ministry figures, industry, agriculture and construction have laid
off 16 percent, 12 percent and eight percent of their respective
workforces.
</P>
<P>
The ministry predicted more pain ahead, with a further 80,000
people, mainly in the state and foreign-backed sectors, expected
to be laid off this year.
</P>
<P>
The financial crisis in the region is only partly to blame for
the heavy layoffs, said an official with the ministry.
</P>
<P>
The slow-down in economic growth, restructuring of state-owned
firms and the modernization of all sectors have contributed
significantly to the high number of layoffs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
