<HEADLINE> World Organizations Agree to Unify Rules </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CARACAS, April 21 (Xinhua) -- The World Boxing Association
(WBA) and the World Boxing Council (WBC) have agreed to harmonise
their fight rules, paving the way for undisputed title bouts
between holders of the two belts, a top WBA official said on
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Gilberto Jesus Mendoza, vice-president of the WBA's
classification committee, said that The rule changes were hammered
out at a meeting last weekend in Mexico City.
</P>
<P>
He added: "The project is to create a super-champion. That
means that a WBA boxer will fight one from the WBC for a so-called
super championship."
</P>
<P>
Among the rule changes were the WBC's decision to adopt the
WBA's system of awarding a knockout victory for three knockdowns
in the same round.
</P>
<P>
Similarly, the WBA will apply the WBC's procedure of
deducting one point for an intentional or unintentional clash of
heads.
</P>
<P>
A second meeting will be held in two weeks in Venezuela,
where the WBA is based, to finalise the rule changes which also
include the adoption of common glove sizes and weight classes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
