<DOCNO> XIE19980422.0279 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sino-U.S. Team Finds Similarity in Geological Origin </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIANJIN, April 22 (Xinhua) -- A group of Chinese and U.S.
geologists have determined that China, North America and Australia
were on the same continent dating back 1.8 billion years ago,
supporting the well-known Wegener Hypothesis of continental drift,
a spokesman said here today.
</P>
<P>
By means of measuring magnetic inclination and declination, the
geologists unraveled the mystery of continental movement and
depicted detailed courses of their faraway travel.
</P>
<P>
In the 1980s, U.S. and Australian scientists found that North
America and Australia were both located near the equator 800
million to 1.8 billion years ago.
</P>
<P>
Later geological surveys showed that the Jixian Section in
Tianjin and the Changhe Section in central Hubei Province have
samples of rock core which were aged 800 million-to-1.8 billion
years ago.
</P>
<P>
The magnetic information from those rock core samples indicates
that modern China's geology is closely linked with that of North
America and Australia, the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
Magnetically similar Earth layers always have the same fossils
of living things, said Zhang Huimin, a research fellow with
Tianjin Institute of Geology and Mineral Resources.
</P>
<P>
Geologists have found the same plant fossils between the Jixian
Section and layers in North America.
</P>
<P>
Furthermore, scientists proved that the mineral veins and ore
deposits in the Asian and Australian paleo-continents are the same.
</P>
<P>
Zhang said that the research, also joined by the
U.S. Geological Survey, would explain continental drift and plate
movement.
</P>
<P>
Zhang said he hopes for further cooperation among scientists
from various countries in the field. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980422.0280 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Panama Begins Regular Power Shutdown to Save Water </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PANAMA CITY, April 21 (Xinhua) -- Panama has begun a power
shutdown two hours per day as part of an emergency plan to deal
with a water shortage in its main hydro-electrical plants.
</P>
<P>
The regulation, in force since Tuesday, will cut economic
activity by 25 percent, private business sources said.
</P>
<P>
A source from the Panamanian Chamber of Commerce and Industry
said that commercial and industrial activities will be affected
most by the measure.
</P>
<P>
Fernando Aramburu Porras, director of the Institute of
Hydraulic and Electrical Resources, said that water shortage in
the hydro-electrical plants of "Bayano" and "Fortuna" forced the
government to take the extreme step.
</P>
<P>
He urged the Panamanian people to save electricity to avoid an
indefinite energy rationing.
</P>
<P>
"In spite of the isolated rains which have recently fallen in
the central zone of the country, there has been no increase in the
flows of the river which funnel energy in hydro-electrical plants,"
he added.
</P>
<P>
The regular electrical shutdown arrangement is expected to last
more than a month until the rainy season begins in June. 
</P>
</TEXT>
