<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Court Ruling Will Not Divert Dock Reforms: Howard </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, April 22 (Xinhua) -- An adverse Federal Court finding
in Australia's ongoing waterfront dispute would not divert the
government from its plan to reform the docks, Australian Prime
Minister John Howard said on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Howard said the government would continue to support any
company that sought to improve productivity on the docks as long
as they operated within the law.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister played down the significance of Tuesday's
Federal Court ruling which ordered Patrick Stevedores to reinstate
1,400 fired workers.
</P>
<P>
Stevedoring company Patrick dismissed the 1,400 unionized dock
workers throughout the nation on April 7 with the encouragement of
the federal government, triggering a two-week-long nationwide
labor dispute.
</P>
<P>
In supporting the company's move, the government aims to break
the monopoly of the Maritime Union of Australia (MUA) over the
nation's ports and improve their efficiency.
</P>
<P>
Federal Court Justice Tony North said on Tuesday that Patrick
had a case to answer over claims that it had conspired with other
parties to illegally lay off its workforce.
</P>
<P>
The matter became complicated after the full bench of the
Federal Court Tuesday night froze the order for 24 hours. The
court will hear an application for leave from Patrick to appeal
against the order on Wednesday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
"I never thought the cause of waterfront reform was going to be
easy," Howard told Australia's John Laws radio program.
</P>
<P>
He also rejected any use of the armed forces.
</P>
<P>
"This issue does not involve the use of the army," he said. "I
believe the role of enforcing the domestic law of this country is
a role that has to be discharged by the police."
</P>
<P>
Howard said waterfront workers were the aristocracy of the
union movement who earned an average 48,000 U.S. dollars a year.
</P>
<P>
But the issue was about productivity, not high wages, he said.
</P>
<P>
"This is not an anti-union campaign. I do not hate the MUA, I
do not hate the unions," he said.
</P>
<P>
The future of Patrick's government-sanctioned push to replace
unionized labor with non-union one now hinges on the outcome of
its appeal against Justice North's decision to the full bench of
the Federal Court.
</P>
<P>
The outcome is expected to be known on Wednesday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
Analysts believe that if the dispute drags on for months, the
nation's economy will be severely affected as it relies on import
and export. Some of the nation's major ports have been blocked by
protesting dock workers to varying extent.
</P>
<P>
Such a failure would lead to the use of force by the government
to end the dispute.
</P>
<P>
In the late 1960s, the arrest of an Australian labor union
leader by policemen prompted 1 million Australian union members to
go on strike. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
