<HEADLINE> Anti-Cuba Resolution Defeated in U.N. Human Rights Commission </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAVANA, April 21 (Xinhua) -- A U.S.-sponsored anti-Cuba
resolution was defeated in the United Nations Human Rights
Commission by 19 votes to 16 on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
It was the first defeat in years for the U.S. annual anti-Cuba
resolution, which has been adopted every year since 1992. Eighteen
countries abstained from the vote.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on the victory, Cuban Foreign Minister Roberto
Robaina said here that it was a success not only for the Cuban
people but also for all peoples in developing countries.
</P>
<P>
"We obtained the victory in the name of the developing nations
of the world, and of the Cuban people who have sacrificed
themselves to defend socialism on the island."
</P>
<P>
Truth and justice have finally been achieved, Robaina said.
</P>
<P>
He also criticized "the unfairness and selectiveness of the
mechanism the U.S has used against Cuba for years." 
</P>
</TEXT>
