<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Italian Railways to Increase Investment for Safety </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, April 21 (Xinhua) -- Italian railway company Ferrovie
dello Stato (FS) Tuesday announced a plan to invest 10 trillion
lire (5.5 billion U.S. dollars) over the next three years to
improve safety on the country's rail network.
</P>
<P>
The FS has come under heavy fire recently following a string of
rail accidents, which have thrown the spotlight on the country's
aging rail system and chronic problems with efficiency, safety and
crisis-management mechanisms.
</P>
<P>
Presenting the new plan, FS managing Director Giancarlo Cimoli
said safety standards on Italian railways were in fact higher than
the European average.
</P>
<P>
Nevertheless he promised a range of improvements, including
cutting the number of trains on the most crowded routes,
introducing automatic velocity control systems on key lines, using
"black box" recorders on many trains and a reduction in the number
of level-crossings.
</P>
<P>
By the end of the year, the FS will activate its new Automatic
Train Control security system on 280 of Italy's 16,000 kilometers
of railway, officials said. The system, which controls velocity,
will be extended to 7,000 kilometers of track in the subsequent
two or three years.
</P>
<P>
Cimoli also promised that in addition to the basic investment
of 10 trillion lire (5.5 billion U.S. dollars), a further 1.2
trillion lire (5.61 billion U.S. dollars) would be spent each year
to upgrade tracks, trains and other infrastructure.
</P>
<P>
With the new safety plan, the FS will need more qualified staff
who are able to handle the automated systems, he said, promising
intensified training for drivers and an internal inquiry aimed at
identifying potentially dangerous habits in train and station
personnel.
</P>
<P>
An attached report on accidents in 1997 said one of the main
causes was "the failure of train personnel to observe signals and
other procedures correctly."
</P>
<P>
The FS added that despite appearances, the number of rail
accidents fell from 174 in 1996 to 146 last year.
</P>
<P>
However, it conceded that last year's accidents had been more
serious, causing eight deaths and 39 injuries compared to five and
14 in the previous year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
