<HEADLINE> Qaidam Basin Using World Bank Loan to Aid 170,000 Farmers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XINING, April 22 (Xinhua) -- Northwest China's Qinghai Province
will enact a five-year project to help 170,000 farmers get rid of
poverty with the aid of a World Bank loan.
</P>
<P>
The project, with an investment of 689 million yuan and 40
million U.S. dollars of World Bank loans, includes:
</P>
<P>
-- Four small irrigation zones, each with 6,500 hectares of
land;
</P>
<P>
-- A 35-kilwatt transmission line 65 kilometers long;
</P>
<P>
-- A 271-kilometer, 10 kilowatt transmission line;
</P>
<P>
-- And 20,000 hectares of arable land.
</P>
<P>
The Qinghai provincial government increased input for poverty
relief in recent years, helping 690,000 people rise above the
poverty line in the last four years.
</P>
<P>
Since 1996, farmers in the arid eastern mountainous area have
migrated to the Qaidam Basin to develop oasis agriculture and to
lead a better life.
</P>
<P>
Liu Guanghe, deputy governor of the province, said the Qaidam
Basin is the most promising place for developing farming in
Qinghai. It is abundant in arable land with 300,000 hectares
available for exploration.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that a combination of available labor in the
eastern portion of the province with natural resources in the
western part should contribute to Qinghai's development.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
