<HEADLINE> Ukraine Sanctions Economic Projection </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KIEV, April 21 (Xinhua) -- Ukrainian annual economic growth
rate is expected to reach five percent by 2006, according to
government projections.
</P>
<P>
The cabinet approved the medium-long range economic projections
up to the years of 2000 and 2010 on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Deputy Economic Minister Igor Shumilo said that these
estimates are guided by the principles of financial stability,
economic freedom, investment stimulation and structural reshaping.
</P>
<P>
According to the medium range estimation, by the year 2000, the
projected gross domestic product (GDP) will increase to four
percent, with the inflation rate falling to 6.5 percent and total
investments amounting to 18.5 billion Gryvna (9.088 billion
U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
The long-range projection spells out the economic future for
the next 13 years, indicating stable GDP growth from 2006 to 2010
of between four and five percent.
</P>
<P>
This is the first Ukrainian medium-long-range economic
projection since its independence in 1991. 
</P>
</TEXT>
