<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rubber Dam to Help Revitalize Area Near Marco Polo Bridge </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 22 (Xinhua) -- A rubber dam under construction
in southwestern Beijing will return the area around the Marco Polo
Bridge to its beautiful past, officials believe.
</P>
<P>
The project started last week below the bridge and will be
finished at the end of this year, according to Wang Minzhou of the
Beijing Water Sources Bureau.
</P>
<P>
The 800-year-old bridge is famous for its 485 stone lions. It
is also the site where Japanese started an all-out invasion of
China on July 7, 1937.
</P>
<P>
Thirty kilometers from the downtown area, the white stone
bridge was the first stop for ancient people when they left
Beijing. "Passers-by at that time could enjoy fresh air, bright
moonlight, clear water and weeping willows with a backdrop of
remote, dark-green mountains," Wang said.
</P>
<P>
A stone inscription penned by Emperor Qian Long of the Qing
dynasty (1644-1911) 250 years ago stands on the east end of the
bridge just the same as before.
</P>
<P>
However, beautiful scenes have been absent for decades because
of a water shortage. Local farmers said they could drive their
tractors, cows and sheep on the dried-up river bed.
</P>
<P>
"Silver moonlight, blue water and green willows are only
colorful dreams left for us," complained young visitors.
</P>
<P>
When a 300-meter-long dam is built below the bridge, water will
be re-directed from a branch of the Yongding River one kilometer
away, Wang said.
</P>
<P>
He added that the height of the dam could be lowered to avoid
strong presure brought by floods. The city now has 52 such rubber
dams.
</P>
<P>
Sources said three years ago water was introduced to the bridge
area, which attracted thousands of visitors. However, the program
was stopped because of a shortage of water. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980422.0297 </DOCNO>
