<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nicaraguan Writers Mourn Paz's Death </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANAGUA, April 21 (Xinhua) -- Nicaraguan writers expressed
their condolences Tuesday on the death of Mexican poet and
philosopher Octavio Paz, winner of the 1990 Nobel Prize for
Literature.
</P>
<P>
Paz died from cancer at his home in Mexico City on Sunday night
at the age of 84.
</P>
<P>
In a press release, Clement Guido, general director of the
Nicaraguan Institute of Culture, said the poetic works and
critical thinking of Paz constitute part of the historical and
invaluable legacy of Latin American countries.
</P>
<P>
Poet Pablo Antonio Cuadra, a friend of the deceased, said Paz
"was a poet in a permanent state of invention. Invention was for
him to destroy the old and fill the abyss with the new, and to
build the unexpected with the remains of the repeated."
</P>
<P>
Ramirez Mercado, former Nicaraguan president and one of the
most important novelists of the country, said that Paz was "one of
the greatest literary voices on the continent," and described him
as "brilliant."
</P>
<P>
Writer Carlos Tunnermann, former director of the National
Autonomous University of Nicaragua, said that Paz was "the summit
of Hispano-American literature, one of the most eminent figures
writing in the Spanish language." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980422.0301 </DOCNO>
