<HEADLINE> More Investments in Fixed Assets in Western China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 22 (Xinhua) -- Western China has invested more
in fixed assets than eastern or central China do in the first
quarter of this year, according to a report released recently by
the State Development Planning Commission.
</P>
<P>
The report said that from January to March, the fixed-asset
investment increase rates for eastern, central and western areas
of China stood at 14.3 percent, 10.3 percent and 24.81 percent,
respectively, with the west areas overtaking eastern and central
areas by 10 percentage points and 15 percentage points,
respectively.
</P>
<P>
In the first quarter of last year, the eastern, central and
western parts of the country drew an upturn line by reporting
14.47 percent, 19.92 percent and 28.78 percent increases in
fixed-assets investment, respectively.
</P>
<P>
Ningxia Hui Autonomous Region, Sichuan, Guizhou provinces,
Chongqing, Beijing municipalities witnessed increases of
fixed-assets investment more than 20 percent from January to March
this year. Among them, the fixed-assets investment increased by
82.6 percent in Ningxia, said the report.
</P>
<P>
The growth of fixed-assets investment in seven regions was less
than ten percent, including Inner Mongolia Autonomous Region and
Jiangxi Province, both reporting decreases, or 19.68 percent and
1.8 percent drop in fixed assets investment, respectively.
</P>
<P>
The report also showed that from January to March this year,
fixed assets investment dropped by varying degrees in all other
areas except Hebei, Liaoning, Hainan, Jilin, Jiangxi, Hubei,
Shaanxi, Gansu, Qinghai provinces and Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous
Region, according to comparable figures for the same period last
year.
</P>
<P>
To maintain a fair growth speed in China's national economy, it
is necessary to spur domestic demand appropriately, to increase
investment and improve investment efficiency so as to meet the
demand of an economic restructuring in the country, said the
report. 
</P>
</TEXT>
