<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bulgarian Scientist Claims Cracking of "Millennium Bug" </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SOFIA, April 21 (Xinhua) -- A Bulgarian computer expert claimed
that he has cracked the problem of the so-called "millennium bug"
that would crash nearly all the computers in the world on the
first day of the next century.
</P>
<P>
In headline stories in the nation's major newspapers Tuesday,
Evgenii Nikolov, head of the National Laboratory for Computer
Viruses, said he has cracked the problem, but wants to keep his
findings secret for now.
</P>
<P>
"We have the fate of some 500 million desktop PCs at our finger
tips and if their owners want to stride over into the new
millennium, they would have to come up with 500 U.S. dollars which
is the price of our product," Evgenii Nikolov said.
</P>
<P>
He said he and his fellow researchers have found it difficult
to raise enough money to patent their discovery. They may need
100 million U.S. dollars to do that in Bulgaria and in at least
five G-7 countries. Another option for them is to patent the
discovery with the U.S. Patent and Trademark Office which will
cost one million dollars.
</P>
<P>
The reports said Microsoft has shown an interest in the
discovery.
</P>
<P>
Computer users have long been warned to expect software
failures on the first day of the new millennium. Currently,
computers recognize the year by its last two digits. So no
problems are expected till after December 31, 1999, but at
midnight that day computers worldwide can lose track of time
confusing the date with January 1, 1900.
</P>
<P>
The idea behind computers using a two-digit reference was to
increase memory capacity. At the time it was thought that the
problem would be solved in due course. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980422.0307 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tibetan Children Having Sufficient Reading Materials </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 22 (Xinhua) -- The children of southwest China's
Tibet Autonomous Region have had the same access to popular
children's books like "Crow and Fox" and "Little Carp Wanting To
Be A Dragon" for a decade as did the children of Beijing -- the
difference now is that they read Tibetan versions of those popular
books.
</P>
<P>
Sources at several major publishers of Tibetan translations
told Xinhua Tuesday that they have published plenty of children's
books in the Tibetan language to meet the needs of more than
780,000 Tibetan children.
</P>
<P>
In addition to the specialized Tibetan Language Press in Tibet,
there are a number of other publishers in Beijing, Tibet, Qinghai,
Gansu, Sichuan, and Yunnan that can publish children's books in
the Tibetan language.
</P>
<P>
Beijing's National Minority Press, for example, has published
more than 50 different children's books in the Tibetan language
since 1980, from fairy tales to popular science reading materials.
</P>
<P>
"These books are rich in content and reasonable in price," a
senior editor of National Minority Press says. An eight-volume set
of World Famous Fairy Tales published in 1993 sold for only five
yuan (60 U.S. cents), for example.
</P>
<P>
Tibetan People's Press, which mainly publishes books in the
Tibetan language, has published a large number of children's books
in its 27-year history, including the widely praised "One Hundred
Thousand Whys".
</P>
<P>
According to a Tibetan Press and Publication Administration
official, in addition to children's books, there are special
columns and pages in more than 30 newspapers published in the
Tibetan language.
</P>
<P>
The Tibetan language has existed for more than 1,300 years, and
is the record of Tibetan history and culture, scholars point
out. The Tibetan Autonomous Region is now applying a policy of
Tibetan language being the dominant language while using both
Chinese and Tibetan, in accordance with the Chinese Constitution.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980422.0308 </DOCNO>
