<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bank of Italy Cuts Discount Rate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, April 21 (Xinhua) -- The Bank of Italy Tuesday announced
a reduction of its discount rate from 5.5 percent to 5 percent,
the lowest level for 14 years.
</P>
<P>
It also lowered its overnight rate from 7 percent to 6.5
percent. The new rates, which will be effective as of Wednesday,
were "confirmation of the positive state of financial
markets... and the consolidation of low inflation rates," the
central bank said in a statement released to the press.
</P>
<P>
The biggest beneficiary of the reduction will be public
accounts because of the indirect link between the key discount rate
and yields paid on state bonds.
</P>
<P>
A half-point cut, according to the Treasury, corresponds to
savings of 10 trillion lire (5.56 billion U.S. dollars) in
interest paid on state paper. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
