<HEADLINE> Portuguese Police Sieze 12 Tons of Drugs in 1997 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LISBON, April 21 (Xinhua) -- Portugal siezed 12 tons of
narcotics last year -- only one tenth of the drugs sneaking into
the country, a police report said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Besides nine tons of marijuana, police also caught three tons
of cocaine -- a 290 percent increase on 1996 -- and 58 kilograms
of heroin, up 23 percent.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, police arrested 6,455 people in connection with drug
smuggling in 1997, three percent less than the previous year.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that the demand for heroin is rising in
Portugal, pushing its price above that in other countries.
</P>
<P>
The local press has blamed politicians for the rising tide of
drugs, saying that parliamentary groups had failed to close ranks
against smuggling. 
</P>
</TEXT>
