<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Join Asian Satellite Project </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 22 (Xinhua) -- China will join several Asian
nations in developing a satellite system to provide mobile
telecommunication service for the region's 3.1 billion people,
today's China Daily reported.
</P>
<P>
The total investment of the Asian-Pacific Mobile
Telecommunications Satellite (APMT) system is expected at 650
million US dollars.
</P>
<P>
To be developed by China, Singapore, Thailand, Malaysia, Japan
and Indonesia, the system which is expected to be put into
operation in the middle of 2000 will cover 22 countries in the
region, the Daily said.
</P>
<P>
According to the English newspaper, one APMT operation center
and one satellite operation center will be located in Beijing to
monitor and manage the APMT network and satellite resources.
</P>
<P>
Hughes Space and Communications International is responsible
for supplying the APMT satellite, and China's Long March 3B will
put the satellite into orbit. The satellite is designed to have a
life span of 12 years.
</P>
<P>
Using the geo-stationary APMT satellite and a pocket-sized
satellite handphone, APMT users will be able to make phone calls
at any time and anywhere within the Asia-pacific region. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
