<HEADLINE> Highlights of Beijing-based Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 22 (Xinhua) -- Highlights of today's major
Beijing-based newspapers:
</P>
<P>
"People's Daily"
</P>
<P>
-- Premier Zhu Rongji, who presided over a State Council
meeting in Beijing yesterday, said that a rudimentary plan for
finding jobs for unemployed workers and reforming the grain
circulation system has been worked out.
</P>
<P>
He also said that there should be more measures to do a better
job in the employment efforts for laid-off workers and in the
grain circulation reforms.
</P>
<P>
-- China witnessed a fairly 8.7 percent increase in revenue in
the first three months this year over the corresponding period of
last year. Of the figure, central government revenue grew by 5.3
percent.
</P>
<P>
-- Major inter-city rail journeys in China will be slightly
quicker as of October 1 when train speeds are marginally
increased, according to a senior official from the Ministry of
Railways.
</P>
<P>
Trains with a speed of 140-to-160 km per hour will run on three
key lines linking Beijing with Guangzhou, Shanghai and Harbin,
said Vice-Minister Liu Zhijun at the a national railway transport
meeting held in Beijing yesterday.
</P>
<P>
 "Xinhua Daily Telegraph"
</P>
<P>
-- Pyramid sales schemes have been outlawed as of April 21 in
China, the State Council said in a circular on the same day,
noting that they were not suited to national conditions and have
done some serious harm.
</P>
<P>
-- The paper frontpaged a moving story about Wang Tao who made
a great success in repairing motor vehicles and published four
books on vehicle structure and repair, while suffering from
serious vasculitis.
</P>
<P>
 "China Daily"
</P>
<P>
-- Despite the effects of the financial crisis sweeping
Southeast Asia, China insists that it will not devalue its
currency, Vice-Premier Li Lanqing said yesterday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the World Economic Forum in Beijing, which will end
today, Li said that "We will pay a certain price for the decision
not to devalue out currency, but it is worthwhile in order to
maintain the healthy development of China's economy and to ease
the ongoing Southeast Asian financial turmoil."
</P>
<P>
-- China's top banker, Dai Xianglong, said yesterday that the
country would soon introduce a system for evaluating the loan
quality of its commercial banks.
</P>
<P>
The system, designed to be in line with international
standards, will provide a clearer picture of the banks' financial
conditions for the central bank's reference, said Dai, governor of
the People's Bank of China. 
</P>
</TEXT>
