<P>
BAGHDAD -- A mass funeral was held in Baghdad on Tuesday for
52 Iraqi children who died of sanctions-spawned malnutrition
diseases.
</P>
<P>
The funeral procession set out from ar-Rasheed street, heading
for the United Nations office in Baghdad. Arab student
organizations as well as a U.S. student delegation, now visiting
Iraq, took part in the funeral. (Iraq-Mass Funeral)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
OTTAWA -- Canadian Prime Minister Jean Chretien will visit Cuba
from April 27 to 28 at the invitation of Cuban President Fidel
Castro.
</P>
<P>
The visit, announced Tuesday by the Canadian government, will
be the first by a Canadian prime minister since Pierre Trudeau
made the trip to the Caribbean island nation 22 years ago.
(Canada-Cuba-Visit)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
TOKYO -- Chinese Vice-President Hu Jintao said Tuesday that he
hoped his present visit to Japan would create a good atmosphere
for the coming autumn visit by Chinese President Jiang Zemin to
Japan.
</P>
<P>
He said Jiang's trip would advance Sino-Japanese friendly
relations to a new stage.
</P>
<P>
Hu made the remarks at a meeting with Japanese Prime Minister
Ryutaro Hashimoto at his official residence in Tokyo. They
exchanged views on bilateral ties and regional and international
issues of common concern. (Japan-China-Hu Jintao) 
</P>
