<DOCNO> XIE19980422.0328 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Romanian FM Leaves for U.S. to Impulse Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUCHAREST, April 21 (Xinhua) -- Romanian Foreign Affairs
Minister Andrei Plesu Tuesday left for the United States on a
five-day visit to give a new impulse to the Romanian-American
relations.
</P>
<P>
Andrei Plesu will present to the U.S. leaders some of the ideas
stipulated in the new governmental program, so as to convince
Washington that Radu Vasile's government will accomplish the
reform.
</P>
<P>
Washington declared recently its discontent for the way in
which the reform of the Romanian society is carried on, and
threatened that if nothing changes about the reform within 6
months, the United States will withdraw its support for Romania.
</P>
<P>
The authorities of Bucharest want to consolidate the bilateral
relations with the U.S. by an efficient application of the
strategic partnership, which was officially launched last July,
when U.S. President Bill Clinton visited Bucharest.
</P>
<P>
The strategic partnership was defined as a form of coordination
and solidarization in accomplishing some common objectives
referring to the political-military relations, to the economic
reform in Romania, to the common fight against the organized crime
and the non-conventional risks and to Romania's contribution to
security in central and southeastern Europe.
</P>
<P>
Plesu will plead for the improvement of economic relations
between the two countries, which are far from achieving their
target.
</P>
<P>
The total U.S. investments in Romania were 360 million dollars
by March 31, 1998. The U.S. represents only 9 percent of the total
foreign capital invested in Romania. At the end of the last year,
the U.S. was in the 5th place as regards the capital invested in
Romania, following France, South Korea, the Netherlands and
Germany.
</P>
<P>
Andrei Plesu's coming talks with U.S. Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright are considered as preparations for the visit of
Romanian President Emil Constantinescu to the United States in
July this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
