<HEADLINE> Washington D.C. Gets New Police Chief </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 21 (Xinhua) -- Charles Ramsey, a veteran
policeman from Chicago, became the 28th chief of the beleaguered
police department in Washington D.C. Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Ramsey, 48, swore to protect the city, saying, "My boss is
going to be the people of Washington D.C."
</P>
<P>
Earlier, the city council unanimously approved Ramsey's
appointment to the position.
</P>
<P>
"The Metropolitan Police Department is a good police department
with good and talented people within its ranks but good is not
enough," Ramsey said after his swearing-in. "I will expect and
accept nothing less than MPD becoming the finest police department
in the nation."
</P>
<P>
Ramsey, a Chicago native who was deputy police superintendent
there, was selected from 51 applicants by a coalition of local
officials, community leaders and a presidentially appointed board
that oversees much of the capital's government.
</P>
<P>
Residents and officials alike had expressed the need for
bringing in an outsider to deal with the department.
</P>
<P>
The department has been through several upheavals in the last
year, including the resignation of Police Chief Larry Soulsby last
November. 
</P>
</TEXT>
