<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Annan Calls for Support for U.N. Humanitarian Program </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, April 21 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary-General
Kofi Annan said Tuesday that U.N. humanitarian aid for those
suffering from civil conflict is imperative.
</P>
<P>
He made the remarks when speaking to the Los Angeles World
Affairs Council during his tour of the western United States.
</P>
<P>
The end of the Cold War seemed to herald a new era of peace and
security, but these hopes were quickly dashed as ethnic conflict
and political upheavals led to a series of massive humanitarian
tragedies, he said.
</P>
<P>
"The nature of warfare has changed. Most wars are now internal
struggles," Annan said.
</P>
<P>
He said, "The dividing line between combatants and civilians
has become less clear cut. Ninety percent of victims are
civilians, whereas during the First World War the comparable
figure was 5 percent."
</P>
<P>
"There are more lethal weapons available to a greater number of
people than at any other time in history. Many are in the hands of
the estimated 250,000 child soldiers, as young as ten or twelve,"
Annan said.
</P>
<P>
Sudan, Afghanistan and Rwanda are the cases where the United
Nations has found not only big humanitarian aid workload but also
remarkable challenges to make the aid done, he said.
</P>
<P>
A 14-year civil war in Sudan has taken more than 1 million
lives with an equivalent number of people vulnerable to famine and
starvation, he said.
</P>
<P>
"But Sudan is in jeopardy of falling off the screen. It has
become one of the world's `forgotten emergencies,'" he added.
</P>
<P>
The secretary-general said that too often humanitarian agencies
are left alone on the front line because there is no political
will by U.N. member states to intervene and sometimes there is "a
dangerous tendency towards isolationism."
</P>
<P>
Emphasizing the importance of humanitarian aid, he said that if
a society does not secure basic fundamental human rights and at
least some prospect of sustainable political, economic and social
development, "there is a potential for a humanitarian crisis."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980422.0337 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-22 </DATE_TIME>
