<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Helps Remove Nuclear Material from Georgia Republic </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 21 (Xinhua) -- The United States has begun a
secretive operation to remove a cache of highly enriched uranium
and spent nuclear fuel from the former Soviet republic of Georgia,
Secretary of State Madeleine Albright said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
There was concern the material would fall into "the wrong
hands," and other countries are cooperating in the operation,
Albright said.
</P>
<P>
"We are taking the appropriate steps to ensure the safety of
this material," she said.
</P>
<P>
Albright said obviously one of the great priorities the U.S.
has is dealing with the weapons of mass destruction and ensuring
the materials for them would not get into the wrong hands.
</P>
<P>
The project at the Physics Institute just outside the capital,
Tbilisi, remained shrouded in secrecy. Institute Director Georgy
Kharadze confirmed that the uranium and spent nuclear fuel are in
the Institute and an American group was working at the institute,
news reports said.
</P>
<P>
The nuclear material consists of 9.5 pounds of highly enriched
uranium-235 and 2 pounds of spent nuclear fuel. The uranium-235
was used for scientific projects involving the Physics Institute's
research reactor, built in the late 1950s, and was left in Georgia
when the Soviet Union collapsed in 1991.
</P>
<P>
Georgia has said it wants to get rid of the uranium, and
officials have offered it for sale on condition it not be used for
military purposes.
</P>
<P>
The British Foreign Office said Tuesday that Britain had agreed
to take "a small amount of fresh and spent highly enriched uranium
fuel" from the Georgian institute.
</P>
<P>
Britain said that most of the material is fresh fuel and will
be usable immediately in the routine production of medical isotope
targets for the treatment of cancer.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. Air Force planes would fly the 10-plus pounds of
nuclear material from Georgia to Britain for reprocessing.
American military and civilian personnel were in the midst of
packing up the shipment, The New York Times reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The report also said that the Americans also asked the French
to take the material, but were rebuffed. British Prime Minister
Tony Blair agreed to store the material in Britain when he visited
Washington early February. 
</P>
</TEXT>
